 improved our competitive position, we went on the offensive. In my weekly staff meeting, I inserted an agenda item titled “What Are We Not Doing?” Ordinarily in a staff meeting, you spend lots of time reviewing, evaluating, and improving all of the things that you do: build products, sell products, support customers, hire employees, and the like. Sometimes, however, the things you’re not doing are the things you should actually be focused on.\",\"index\":299,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In one such meeting, after asking the question, every person on my staff agreed: “We are not automating the network.” Although the original version of Opsware that we used in Loudcloud automated our network, the software was not robust and, of course, featured the purple-pimp-hat user interface. As a result, when we switched over to being a software company, we narrowed our focus to server automation and never revisited the decision. This worked well for the first several years of Opsware, but now we had an opportunity to bring back our network automation product.\",\"index\":300,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Unfortunately, the Jive was not a good code base and could not be turned into a commercial product. My choices were: (a) start a new project or (b) buy one of the four existing network automation companies. Early in my career as an engineer, I’d learned that all decisions were objective until the first line of code was written. After that, all decisions were emotional. In addition, I had John O’Farrell, the industry’s greatest M&A negotiator, on my team so I decided to investigate the other companies before sizing the internal effort.\",\"index\":301,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Surprisingly, among the four existing network automation players, the company that we thought had the best product architecture, Rendition Networks, had the lowest revenues. This made some of our businesspeople skeptical of our technical evaluation. However, if I’d learned anything it was that conventional wisdom had nothing to do with the truth and the efficient market hypothesis was deceptive. How else could one explain Opsware trading at half of the cash we had in the bank when we had a $20 million a year contract and fifty of the smartest engineers in the world? No, markets weren’t “efficient” at finding the truth; they were just very efficient at converging on a conclusion—often the wrong conclusion.\",\"index\":302,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After confirming that acquiring would be superior to building, we negotiated a deal to buy Rendition Networks for $33 million. Within three months of completing the acquisition, John negotiated a deal with Cisco Systems—the world’s largest networking company—to resell our product. The deal included an agreement to prepay us $30 million for advanced licenses. As a result, the Cisco deal alone paid more than 90 percent of the acquisition costs.\",\"index\":303,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Note to self: It’s a good idea to ask, “What am I not doing?”\",\"index\":304,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As soon as the EDS crisis was resolved, I learned we were losing three clients to a strong competitor, BladeLogic, which hurt our quarterly numbers and dropped our stock price to $2.90. With a losing product, a declining stock price, and an exhausted team, we faced severe challenges, compounded by my partner Marc’s decision to start another company. Despite feeling drained, I candidly urged the team to commit intensely for six months, making one last effort. This challenging period, known as the Darwin Project, later became a source of pride for Ted Crossman and the team. Following my speech, we struggled to redefine our product amidst numerous customer demands, but true product strategy requires innovation beyond customer feedback. I pushed the management team to reinvent our product with a winning focus, and nine months later, we succeeded. Mark Cranney revamped our sales force, demanding high standards and rigorously scrutinizing every deal. His tough stance proved correct, leading to critical wins. To uncover missed opportunities, I introduced the agenda item “What Are We Not Doing?” in weekly staff meetings. This led us to realize the need for network automation, culminating in the acquisition of Rendition Networks for $33 million. Soon after, we secured a $30 million deal with Cisco, nearly covering the acquisition costs. Key takeaway: regularly ask, “What am I not doing?”\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE ULTIMATE DECISION**\",\"index\":305,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As we fielded the broader product line, our momentum steadily grew. From the ashes, we’d built a software business that approached a $150 million revenue run rate. Along with our revenue, our stock price rose from its floor of $0.35 per share as well as we traded between $6 per share and $8 per share, sometimes trading at a market capitalization of more than $800 million.\",\"index\":306,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Still, everything was not rosy. Every quarter was tough, and the competitive and the technology landscapes changed rapidly. A technology called virtualization was taking the market by storm and changing the way customers thought about automating their environments. In fact, it looked to me like virtualization might be the technological breakthrough that finally enabled the cloud computing business model to work. Beyond that, being a public company was still never going to get easy. At one point, a shareholder activist named Rachel Hyman decided that my ego was out of control, and she demanded that the board remove me and sell the company immediately. This was despite the fact that we were trading at $7 per share, which was ten times the original price of her shares.\",\"index\":307,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Nonetheless, I was not looking for the exits. Whenever a potential acquirer approached us, I would always reply, “We are not for sale.” It was a great answer in that I wasn’t ready to sell and it conveyed that, but it also left the door open to a particularly aggressive buyer. “Not for sale” didn’t mean that we wouldn’t listen to offers—it just meant that we weren’t trying to sell the company. So, when EMC implied that it wanted to buy us, I thought nothing of it. We were trading at about $6.50 per share and I wasn’t planning to sell at anything close to that price. But this time the news of the offer leaked to the press and the stock shot up to $9.50 per share, changing the economic equation, especially since the stock was going up for all the wrong reasons.\",\"index\":308,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ironically, the higher the stock price went up, the more companies wanted to buy us. Over the course of the next month, eleven companies expressed interest. Given the uncertainty in the business and the implied earnings multiple, their interest was too much to ignore.\",\"index\":309,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"To get things started, John and I called Michael Ovitz to get some advice. We felt one of the potential bidders, Oracle, would be the least likely to bid high, because it was extremely disciplined in its financial analysis. We conveyed this to Michael and questioned whether we should pursue Oracle at all. His reply was priceless: “Well, boys, if you are going to have a dog race, then you are going to need a rabbit. And Oracle will be one hell of a rabbit.”\",\"index\":310,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"With that strategy in hand, we generated a broad set of bids, all between $10 and $11 per share, with the highest bids representing a 38 percent premium over the current stock price. Although this was considered a good premium, I did not feel right selling the company for $11 per share. The team had worked too hard, we’d accomplished too much, and we were too good a company. The risks of staying stand-alone were substantial, but I still wanted to bet on the team. I recommended to the board that we not sell.\",\"index\":311,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The board was surprised, but supportive. Still, they had a fiduciary responsibility to shareholders to ask the tough questions. “If you’re unwilling to sell at eleven dollars per share, is there a price at which you would sell?” I had to think about that one. I had promised the team that if we got to be the number-one company in a big market, we would not sell. We were number one, but how big was the market? Did the team really want to continue or was it just me who wanted to continue? How could I know without panicking the company? And thus began a series of very long talks with myself.\",\"index\":312,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It was an argument to the death, and it was me against me. On the one hand, I argued that virtualization created an explosion of virtual server instances, making what we did more essential than ever. In the next breath, I retorted that while that may have been true, the architectural changes would make our market position vulnerable. I battled myself for weeks before concluding that things were changing fast enough that we’d need to make major changes to our product architecture in order to stay on top. The key to answering the ultimate question was knowing the state of the team. Were they up for yet another giant challenge or were they at the end of a very long road? I decided to bring my direct reports into the loop and ask them what they thought. The answers came back clear: Everyone, with the exception of one person who felt that the opportunity in front of us was still quite large, opted for the sale. Now it was just a matter of price. But what price?\",\"index\":313,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After a long discussion with John O’Farrell, I decided that the right price to sell the company would be $14 per share, or about $1.6 billion. I took that number back to the board. They thought the number was extremely high and that it was unlikely we’d be able to generate a bid at that level, but they were supportive nonetheless. I called back all the potential acquirers and let them know that we would only entertain bids of $14 or more. There were no takers.\",\"index\":314,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"More than a month passed without a word, and I figured the M&A talks had ended. I began refocusing on how to make the necessary changes to keep us competitive. And then I received a call from Bob Beauchamp, the CEO of BMC Software. He offered $13.25 per share. I held firm: “Bob, that’s great, but the number is fourteen dollars per share.” Bob said that he’d have to think about it. He called back two days later and offered $14 per share. Wow. The dog had caught the bus.\",\"index\":315,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"John and I immediately called back all the other suitors to let them know that we had an offer that we planned to take. Hewlett-Packard was still interested and offered $13.50 per share in an effort to make sure that I wasn’t bluffing. I responded that as a public company CEO, I couldn’t take a lower offer. HP eventually offered $14.25 or $1.65 billion in cash. We had a deal.\",\"index\":316,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When it finally ended—the long road from Loudcloud to Opsware—I couldn’t believe that I’d sold what it took eight years and all of my life force to build. How could I have done that? I was sick. I couldn’t sleep, I had cold sweats, I threw up, and I cried. And then I realized that it was the smartest thing that I’d ever done in my career. We’d built something from nothing, saw it go back to nothing again, and then rebuilt it into a $1.65 billion franchise.\",\"index\":317,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At that point, it felt like my business life was kind of over. I had hired all the best people that I knew or could find, and I had gone through every step from founding to going public to sale. I definitely did not feel like doing any of that again. But I had learned so much. It seemed like such a waste to do something completely different. And then I got an idea to build a new kind of venture capital firm.\",\"index\":318,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"We will explore this idea in chapter 9, but first, chapters 4 through 8 will take you through most everything I learned to this point plus a few new war stories from my experiences running Loudcloud and Opsware.\",\"index\":319,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As our product line expanded, our software business flourished, hitting a $150 million revenue run rate, raising our stock from $0.35 to between $6 and $8 per share, and achieving a market cap over $800 million. Despite these successes, each quarter was challenging due to rapid changes in competition and technology, particularly with virtualization and cloud computing. As a public company, pressures mounted, exemplified when activist shareholder Rachel Hyman demanded my removal and the immediate sale of our company. Though our stock was $7 per share, I wasn’t looking to sell. Interest peaked when EMC’s implied interest leaked, driving the stock to $9.50 and attracting eleven companies. Seeking advice, Michael Ovitz suggested leveraging bidders to fuel competition, leading to bids up to $11 per share. Despite this, I believed $11 undervalued our efforts and advised against selling, sparking board discussions on whether there was any price at which we would sell. Amid personal turmoil and rigorous team consultations, we set the price at $14 per share. With no initial takers, I focused on maintaining our competitive edge until BMC Software’s CEO offered $13.25 per share, which I raised to $14. HP’s subsequent offer of $14.25 per share sealed the deal, finalizing a $1.65 billion cash acquisition. Though satisfied with transforming our company, the sale marked an intense emotional and physical journey. Feeling my business journey complete yet eager for new challenges, I envisioned a distinct venture capital firm. We'll explore this in Chapter 9, with Chapters 4 through 8 detailing the hard-earned lessons and experiences from leading Loudcloud and Opsware.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Early into Opsware, EDS, our primary client representing 90% of our revenue, encountered severe technical problems with our product, putting our contract at risk. To address this, I worked with Jason Rosenthal and Anthony Wright to resolve the chaos at EDS, marked by outdated infrastructure and disheartened staff. After proposing a 60-day fix-it period and acquiring Tangram for $10 million to satisfy EDS’s Frank Johnson, we managed to salvage the account. Despite challenges such as deciding which employees to keep, the acquisition was ultimately profitable. During this period, Tangram’s CFO, John Nelli, was diagnosed with brain cancer. Opting to cover his health costs, which amounted to $200,000, had a profound impact on his family, who showed their immense gratitude. Just as the EDS crisis resolved, we began losing clients to BladeLogic, driving our stock down to $2.90. Encouraging the team to commit for six more months, we embarked on the Darwin Project, eventually reinventing our product and achieving crucial wins. We recognized a need for network automation, leading to the acquisition of Rendition Networks for $33 million and a significant $30 million deal with Cisco. Our software business grew, driving stock from $0.35 to $6-$8 and reaching a market cap of $800 million, despite shifting competition and technology. As pressures mounted, activist shareholder Rachel Hyman demanded my removal and the company’s sale. With EMC’s interest, we sparked a bidding war, ultimately agreeing to HP’s offer of $14.25 per share, amounting to a $1.65 billion acquisition. This marked the end of a strenuous yet victorious journey, paving the way for new ventures and a forthcoming distinct venture capital firm, as elaborated in Chapter 9. Chapters 4 through 8 will delve into the lessons and experiences from leading Loudcloud and Opsware.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Early into Opsware, EDS, our primary client representing 90% of our revenue, encountered severe technical problems with our product, putting our contract at risk. To address this, I worked with Jason Rosenthal and Anthony Wright to resolve the chaos at EDS, marked by outdated infrastructure and disheartened staff. After proposing a 60-day fix-it period and acquiring Tangram for $10 million to satisfy EDS’s Frank Johnson, we managed to salvage the account. Despite challenges such as deciding which employees to keep, the acquisition was ultimately profitable. During this period, Tangram’s CFO, John Nelli, was diagnosed with brain cancer. Opting to cover his health costs, which amounted to $200,000, had a profound impact on his family, who showed their immense gratitude. Just as the EDS crisis resolved, we began losing clients to BladeLogic, driving our stock down to $2.90. Encouraging the team to commit for six more months, we embarked on the Darwin Project, eventually reinventing our product and achieving crucial wins. We recognized a need for network automation, leading to the acquisition of Rendition Networks for $33 million and a significant $30 million deal with Cisco. Our software business grew, driving stock from $0.35 to $6-$8 and reaching a market cap of $800 million, despite shifting competition and technology. As pressures mounted, activist shareholder Rachel H