the idea that statistical ways of thinking are going to drive the future.”\",\"index\":323,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**—PETER THIEL**\",\"index\":324,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“There are several different frameworks one could use to get a handle on the indeterminate vs. determinate question. The math version is calculus vs. statistics. In a determinate world, calculus dominates. You can calculate specific things precisely and deterministically. When you send a rocket to the moon, you have to calculate precisely where it is at all times. It’s not like some iterative startup where you launch the rocket and figure things out step by step. Do you make it to the moon? To Jupiter? Do you just get lost in space? There were lots of companies in the ’90s that had launch parties but no landing parties. \\n\\n “But the indeterminate future is somehow one in which probability and statistics are the dominant modality for making sense of the world. Bell curves and random walks define what the future is going to look like. The standard pedagogical argument is that high schools should get rid of calculus and replace it with statistics, which is really important and actually useful. There has been a powerful shift toward the idea that statistical ways of thinking are going to drive the future.” \\n\\n **—PETER THIEL**\"},{\"content\":\"**W**hen I was attempting to sell the cloud computing services part of the Loudcloud business, I met with Bill Campbell to update him on where I was with the deal. The deal was critical, because without it, the company would almost certainly go bankrupt.\",\"index\":325,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After I carefully briefed him on where we were with both interested parties, IBM and EDS, Bill paused for a moment. He looked me in the eyes and said, “Ben, you need to do something in addition to working on this deal. You need to do it alone with your general counsel. You need to prepare the company for bankruptcy.” To an objective observer, this might sound like Bill was prudently advising me to build my contingency plan. But something in his voice and his eyes said something different. They said that he believed the contingency plan was going to be *the* plan.\",\"index\":326,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The conversation brought to mind a story that a friend told me about his brother, a young doctor. A thirty-five-year-old man came to see my friend’s brother. The man looked awful. His eyes were hollow and his skin was ashen. The young doctor knew something was wrong, but he could not figure out what, so he brought in an elder colleague to help with the diagnosis. The more experienced doctor examined the man and then sent him on his way. The old doctor then turned to the young doctor and said, “He’s dead.” The young doctor was flabbergasted: “What are you talking about? He just walked out of here alive!” The older doctor replied, “He doesn’t know it yet, but he’s dead. He’s had a heart attack and when people that young have heart attacks their bodies are not yet pliable enough to recover. He won’t recover. He’s dead.” Three weeks later the patient died.\",\"index\":327,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I felt that Bill was telling me, although I was walking around trying to get the deal done, that I was already dead and that I did not know it. It was a very hard thing for him to say and only the best of friends will muster the courage to break news that horrible. It was an even harder thing for me to hear. He told me so that I could emotionally prepare myself and financially prepare the company for the inevitable funeral. The odds of landing a company-saving deal during the technology industry’s nuclear winter were close to nil. Chances were, I was dead.\",\"index\":328,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I never built that contingency plan. Through the seemingly impossible Loudcloud series C and IPO processes, I learned one important lesson: Startup CEOs should not play the odds. When you are building a company, you must believe there is an answer and you cannot pay attention to your odds of finding it. You just have to find it. It matters not whether your chances are nine in ten or one in a thousand; your task is the same.\",\"index\":329,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the end, I did find the answer, we completed the deal with EDS, and the company did not go bankrupt. I was not mad at Bill. To this day, I sincerely appreciate his telling me the truth about the odds. But I don’t believe in statistics. I believe in calculus.\",\"index\":330,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":331,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**P**eople always ask me, “What’s the secret to being a successful CEO?” Sadly, there is no secret, but if there is one skill that stands out, it’s the ability to focus and make the best move when there are no good moves. It’s the moments where you feel most like hiding or dying that you can make the biggest difference as a CEO. In the rest of this chapter, I offer some lessons on how to make it through the struggle without quitting or throwing up too much.\",\"index\":332,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"While most management books focus on how to do things correctly, so you don’t screw up, these lessons provide insight into what you must do after you have screwed up. The good news is, I have plenty of experience at that and so does every other CEO.\",\"index\":333,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I put this section first even though it deals with some serious endgame issues such as how to fire an executive and how to lay people off. In doing so, I follow the first principle of the Bushido—the way of the warrior: keep death in mind at all times. If a warrior keeps death in mind at all times and lives as though each day might be his last, he will conduct himself properly in all his actions. Similarly, if a CEO keeps the following lessons in mind, she will maintain the proper focus when hiring, training, and building her culture.\",\"index\":334,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":335,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":336,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"To understand the indeterminate vs. determinate question, consider the difference between calculus and statistics: calculus is integral in a determinate world like rocket science for precise calculations, whereas an indeterminate future relies on probability and statistics, suggesting schools should emphasize statistics for its practical relevance. When I was trying to sell Loudcloud's cloud services, Bill Campbell starkly advised me to prepare for bankruptcy despite my efforts with IBM and EDS. His tone implied that bankruptcy wasn't just a contingency but the likely outcome, much like a doctor with a doomed patient. This harsh reality prepared me for potential failure during a tech downturn. However, I never built that contingency plan. Through the arduous Loudcloud series C and IPO processes, I learned that startup CEOs shouldn't play the odds but must believe in finding answers regardless. I avoided bankruptcy by closing a deal with EDS. Despite appreciating Bill's honesty, I believe in calculus over statistics. The secret to being a successful CEO lies in focusing and making the best of bad options. The toughest times offer the biggest impact. This chapter teaches lessons on surviving without quitting, handling endgame issues, and maintaining focus, drawing from the Bushido principle of acting with death in mind to keep focus when hiring, training, and building company culture.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[THE STRUGGLE]()**\",\"index\":337,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Every entrepreneur starts her company with a clear vision for success. You will create an amazing environment and hire the smartest people to join you. Together you will build a beautiful product that delights customers and makes the world just a little bit better. It’s going to be absolutely awesome.\",\"index\":338,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Then, after working night and day to make your vision a reality, you wake up to find that things did not go as planned. Your company did not unfold like the Jack Dorsey keynote that you listened to when you started. Your product has issues that will be very hard to fix. The market isn’t quite where it was supposed to be. Your employees are losing confidence and some of them have quit. Some of the ones who quit were quite smart and have the remaining ones wondering if staying makes sense. You are running low on cash and your venture capitalist tells you that it will be difficult to raise money given the impending European economic catastrophe. You lose a competitive battle. You lose a loyal customer. You lose a great employee. The walls start closing in. Where did you go wrong? Why didn’t your company perform as envisioned? Are you good enough to do this? As your dreams turn into nightmares, you find yourself in *the Struggle*.\",\"index\":339,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Every entrepreneur starts with a clear vision of success, creating an amazing environment and hiring the smartest people to build a product that delights customers and enhances the world. It's going to be awesome. However, after countless nights of hard work, you may find things didn't go as planned. Your company doesn't unfold like the inspiring Jack Dorsey keynote you once heard. Your product faces tough issues, the market isn't as expected, and employees are losing confidence and quitting. Some of the smartest people leave, causing others to question their stay. Cash runs low, and your venture capitalist warns of difficulty raising funds amidst an impending economic catastrophe in Europe. You lose competitive battles, loyal customers, and great employees. The walls close in. You wonder where you went wrong, why the company didn’t perform as envisioned, and if you’re good enough. As dreams turn into nightmares, you find yourself in *the Struggle*.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**ABOUT THE STRUGGLE**\",\"index\":340,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“Life is struggle.”\",\"index\":341,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**—KARL MARX**\",\"index\":342,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“Life is struggle.” \\n\\n **—KARL MARX**\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you wonder why you started the company in the first place.\",\"index\":343,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when people ask you why you don’t quit and you don’t know the answer.\",\"index\":344,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when your employees think you are lying and you think they may be right.\",\"index\":345,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when food loses its taste.\",\"index\":346,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you don’t believe you should be CEO of your company. The Struggle is when you know that you are in over your head and you know that you cannot be replaced. The Struggle is when everybody thinks you are an idiot, but nobody will fire you. The Struggle is where self-doubt becomes self-hatred.\",\"index\":347,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you are having a conversation with someone and you can’t hear a word that they are saying because all you can hear is the Struggle.\",\"index\":348,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you want the pain to stop. The Struggle is unhappiness.\",\"index\":349,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you go on vacation to feel better and you feel worse.\",\"index\":350,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is when you are surrounded by people and you are all alone. The Struggle has no mercy.\",\"index\":351,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is the land of broken promises and crushed dreams. The Struggle is a cold sweat. The Struggle is where your guts boil so much that you feel like you are going to spit blood.\",\"index\":352,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is not failure, but it causes failure. Especially if you are weak. Always if you are weak.\",\"index\":353,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"The Struggle is when you wonder why you started the company in the first place. \\n\\n The Struggle is when people ask you why you don’t quit and you don’t know the answer. \\n\\n The Struggle is when your employees think you are lying and you think they may be right. \\n\\n The Struggle is when food loses its taste. \\n\\n The Struggle is when you don’t believe you should be CEO of your company. The Struggle is when you know that you are in over your head and you know that you cannot be replaced. The Struggle is when everybody thinks you are an idiot, but nobody will fire you. The Struggle is where self-doubt becomes self-hatred. \\n\\n The Struggle is when you are having a conversation with someone and you can’t hear a word that they are saying because all you can hear is the Struggle. \\n\\n The Struggle is when you want the pain to stop. The Struggle is unhappiness. \\n\\n The Struggle is when you go on vacation to feel better and you feel worse. \\n\\n The Struggle is when you are surrounded by people and you are all alone. The Struggle has no mercy. \\n\\n The Struggle is the land of broken promises and crushed dreams. The Struggle is a cold sweat. The Struggle is where your guts boil so much that you feel like you are going to spit blood. \\n\\n The Struggle is not failure, but it causes failure. Especially if you are weak. Always if you are weak.\"},{\"content\":\"Most people are not strong enough.\",\"index\":354,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Every great entrepreneur from Steve Jobs to Mark Zuckerberg went through the Struggle and struggle they did, so you are not alone. But that does not mean that you will make it. You may not make it. That is why it is the Struggle.\",\"index\":355,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The Struggle is where greatness comes from.\",\"index\":356,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"\\\"Life is struggle.\\\" —Karl Marx\\n\\nThe Struggle is all-consuming, questioning every decision and doubting every step you take. It’s wondering why you started your company, feeling lost when people suggest you quit, and grappling with the belief that you might be deceiving your employees. The Struggle dulls your senses, makes you question your role as CEO, and isolates you even in a crowd. It’s the relentless self-doubt turning into self-hatred, the endless worry that you're losing control, the unhappiness that accompanies you even on vacations, and the lack of mercy it shows. The Struggle is a landscape of broken promises and shattered dreams, a place of cold sweats and boiling anxiety. It's not failure itself, but it leads to failure, especially if you’re not strong enough. History's great entrepreneurs, like Steve Jobs and Mark Zuckerberg, experienced the Struggle, proving it’s a universal ordeal for those daring to dream big. Yet, survival is not guaranteed—strength through the Struggle is rare, and while greatness can emerge from it, not everyone makes it. That's why it is the Struggle.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SOME STUFF THAT MAY OR MAY NOT HELP**\",\"index\":357,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There is no answer to the Struggle, but here are some things that helped me:\",\"index\":358,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Don’t put it all on your shoulders.* It is easy to think that the things that bother you will upset your people more. That’s not true. The opposite is true. Nobody takes the losses harder than the person most responsible. Nobody feels it more than you. You won’t be able to share every burden, but share every burden that you can. Get the maximum number of brains on the problems even if the problems represent existential threats. When I ran Opsware and we were losing too many competitive deals, I called an all hands and told the whole company that we were getting our asses kicked, and if we didn’t stop the bleeding, we were going to die. Nobody blinked. The team rallied, built a winning product, and saved my sorry ass.\\n\\n* *This is not checkers; this is motherfuckin’ chess.* Technology businesses tend to be extremely complex. The underlying technology moves, the competition moves, the market moves, the people move. As a result, like playing three-dimensional chess on *Star Trek*, there is always a move. You think you have no moves? How about taking your company public with $2 million in trailing revenue and 340 employees, with a plan to do $75 million in revenue the next year? I made that move. I made it in 2001, widely regarded as the worst time ever for a technology company to go public. I made it with six weeks of cash left. There is always a move.\\n\\n* *Play long enough and you might get lucky.* In the technology game, tomorrow looks nothing like today. If you survive long enough to see tomorrow, it may bring you the answer that seems so impossible today.\\n\\n* *Don’t take it personally.* The predicament that you are in is probably all your fault. You hired the people. You made the decisions. But you knew the job was dangerous when you took it. Everybody makes mistakes. Every CEO makes thousands of mistakes. Evaluating yourself and giving yourself an F doesn’t help.\\n\\n* *Remember that this is what separates the women from the girls.* If you want to be great, this is the challenge. If you don’t want to be great, then you never should have started a company.\",\"index\":359,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"There is no single answer to the Struggle, but here are some things that helped me: First, don't carry it all on your shoulders. Share every burden you can; no one feels the losses more deeply than you. For instance, when Opsware was struggling, I called an all-hands meeting, laid out our dire situation, and the team rallied to build a winning product. Second, this isn't checkers; it's motherfuckin’ chess. Technology businesses are complex and always offer another move—even in bleak times like when I took my company public with $2 million in trailing revenue and six weeks of cash left. Third, play long enough and you might get lucky as tomorrow could bring answers that seem impossible today. Fourth, don't take it personally; blame and self-criticism are inevitable but unhelpful. Finally, remember that overcoming these challenges is what separates the great from the mediocre. If you aim to be great, embrace the struggle.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE END**\",\"index\":360,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When you are in the Struggle, nothing is easy and nothing feels right. You have dropped into the abyss and you may never get out. In my own experience, but for some unexpected luck and help, I would have been lost.\",\"index\":361,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summari