 comes by about once a quarter to blow a little sunshine up my ass.” At that moment, I knew that I’d been screwing up my company by being too positive.\",\"index\":368,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In my mind, I was keeping everyone in high spirits by accentuating the positive and ignoring the negative. But my team knew that reality was more nuanced than I was describing it. And not only did they see for themselves the world wasn’t as rosy as I was describing it; they still had to listen to me blowing sunshine up their butts at every company meeting.\",\"index\":369,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"How did I make such a mistake and why was it such a big mistake?\",\"index\":370,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"One of the most critical, though counterintuitive, management lessons I've learned as a founder/CEO is to stop being overly positive. Initially, as a young CEO, I felt immense pressure—responsibility for employees, inexperience in my role, and stewardship of significant investor funds. This pressure led me to take losses deeply to heart, believing that burdening my team with these setbacks would demoralize them. Consequently, I adopted a perpetually upbeat demeanor to rally my team. This approach faltered when my brother-in-law, Cartheu, a lineman for AT&T, mentioned how an executive he knew would come by quarterly, only to \\\"blow a little sunshine up my ass.\\\" Realizing that my team saw through the falsely sunny outlook I projected, I understood that ignoring the negative aspects only hindered our progress. My mistake lay in failing to address reality as it was, leading to a disconnection between me and my team, thus making a tough situation even tougher.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE POSITIVITY DELUSION**\",\"index\":371,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As the highest-ranking person in the company, I thought that I would be best able to handle bad news. The opposite was true: Nobody took bad news harder than I did. Engineers easily brushed off things that kept me awake all night. After all, I was the founding CEO. I was the one “married” to the company. If things went horribly wrong, they could walk away, but I could not. As a consequence, the employees handled losses much better.\",\"index\":372,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Even more stupidly, I thought that it was my job and my job only to worry about the company’s problems. Had I been thinking more clearly, I would have realized that it didn’t make sense for me to be the only one to worry about, for example, the product not being quite right—because I wasn’t writing the code that would fix it.\",\"index\":373,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A much better idea would have been to give the problem to the people who could not only fix it, but who would also be personally excited and motivated to do so. Another example: If we lost a big prospect, the whole organization needed to understand why, so that we could together fix the things that were broken in our products, marketing, and sales process. If I insisted on keeping the setbacks to myself, there was no way to jump-start that process.\",\"index\":374,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As the founding CEO of the company, I painfully learned that I took bad news far harder than anyone else, even the engineers who could sleep soundly despite issues that kept me awake. Unlike them, I couldn't walk away when things went wrong, making me feel solely responsible for the company's troubles. Foolishly, I believed it was my duty alone to worry about the company's problems, even when I wasn't directly involved in tasks like coding. A better approach would have been to delegate issues to those capable and enthusiastic about solving them. For instance, if we lost a major prospect, it was crucial for the entire organization to understand why so that we could collectively address the flaws in our products, marketing, and sales processes. By isolating the setbacks, I hindered our ability to effectively tackle and overcome these issues together.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHY IT’S IMPERATIVE TO TELL IT LIKE IT IS**\",\"index\":375,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"There are three key reasons why being transparent about your company’s problems makes sense:\",\"index\":376,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"There are three key reasons why being transparent about your company’s problems makes sense:\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**1. Trust.**\",\"index\":377,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Without trust, communication breaks. More specifically:\",\"index\":378,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In any human interaction, the required amount of communication is inversely proportional to the level of trust.\",\"index\":379,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Consider the following: If I trust you completely, then I require no explanation or communication of your actions whatsoever, because I know that whatever you are doing is in my best interests. On the other hand, if I don’t trust you at all, then no amount of talking, explaining, or reasoning will have any effect on me, because I do not trust that you are telling me the truth.\",\"index\":380,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In a company context, this is a critical point. As a company grows, communication becomes its biggest challenge. If the employees fundamentally trust the CEO, then communication will be vastly more efficient than if they don’t. Telling things as they are is a critical part of building this trust. A CEO’s ability to build this trust over time is often the difference between companies that execute well and companies that are chaotic.\",\"index\":381,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Without trust, communication falters. In any human interaction, the required amount of communication is inversely proportional to the level of trust. If I trust you completely, no explanations are needed; I assume your actions are in my best interest. Conversely, without trust, no amount of discussion or reasoning will convince me of your truthfulness. In a company setting, this principle is crucial. As companies grow, communication becomes a major challenge. If employees fundamentally trust the CEO, communication is far more efficient than if they don't. Building this trust by honestly communicating is essential. A CEO's ability to foster trust over time often distinguishes well-executed companies from chaotic ones.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**2. The more brains working on the hard problems, the better.**\",\"index\":382,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In order to build a great technology company, you have to hire lots of incredibly smart people. It’s a total waste to have lots of big brains but not let them work on your biggest problems. A brain, no matter how big, cannot solve a problem it doesn’t know about. As the open-source community would explain it, “Given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow.”\",\"index\":383,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In order to build a great technology company, you have to hire lots of incredibly smart people. It’s a total waste to have lots of big brains but not let them work on your biggest problems. A brain, no matter how big, cannot solve a problem it doesn’t know about. As the open-source community would explain it, “Given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow.”\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**3. A good culture is like the old RIP routing protocol: Bad news travels fast; good news travels slow.**\",\"index\":384,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you investigate companies that have failed, you will find that many employees knew about the fatal issues long before those issues killed the company. If the employees knew about the deadly problems, why didn’t they say something? Too often the answer is that the company culture discouraged the spread of bad news, so the knowledge lay dormant until it was too late to act.\",\"index\":385,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A healthy company culture encourages people to share bad news. A company that discusses its problems freely and openly can quickly solve them. A company that covers up its problems frustrates everyone involved. The resulting action item for CEOs: Build a culture that rewards—not punishes—people for getting problems into the open where they can be solved.\",\"index\":386,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As a corollary, beware of management maxims that stop information from flowing freely in your company. For example, consider the old management standard: “Don’t bring me a problem without bringing me a solution.” What if the employee cannot solve an important problem? For example, what if an engineer identifies a serious flaw in the way the product is being marketed? Do you really want him to bury that information? Management truisms like these may be good for employees to aspire to in the abstract, but they can also be the enemy of free-flowing information—which may be critical for the health of the company.\",\"index\":387,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Investigating failed companies often reveals that employees were aware of critical issues long before the company's downfall. These issues typically go unreported because the company culture discourages sharing bad news. On the other hand, a healthy company culture promotes open discussion of problems, enabling swift solutions and preventing frustrations. CEOs should therefore foster an environment that rewards transparency and problem-sharing. Additionally, management practices that hinder information flow, like the adage \\\"Don’t bring me a problem without a solution,\\\" should be scrutinized. It's crucial for employees to report issues even if they can't offer immediate solutions, as this transparency is vital for the company's health.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Without trust, communication breaks down. In any human interaction, more communication is needed when trust levels are low. Complete trust eliminates the need for explanations as we assume others act in our best interest. Conversely, without trust, no amount of discussion will convince us of one's truthfulness. This principle is crucial in companies, where trust in leadership makes communication efficient. Building this trust requires honest communication from the CEO and is key to distinguishing well-managed companies from chaotic ones.\\n\\nTo build a great tech company, hiring incredibly smart people is essential, but it's a waste if they're not working on your biggest problems. A brain can’t solve a problem it doesn’t know about, and as the open-source community says, “Given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow.” Failed companies often falter because employees knew about critical issues but didn’t report them due to a culture that discourages sharing bad news. A healthy culture, however, promotes open discussion of problems, enabling swift solutions. CEOs should foster an environment that rewards transparency and encourages problem-sharing. Practices like \\\"Don’t bring me a problem without a solution\\\" should be scrutinized, as reporting issues without immediate solutions is vital for a company's health.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Without trust, communication breaks down. In any human interaction, more communication is needed when trust levels are low. Complete trust eliminates the