es hiring smart people and ensuring they work on critical problems. A culture that discourages sharing bad news leads to failure, while a healthy culture promotes open discussion and transparency. CEOs should foster an environment that rewards problem-sharing. The pressure to stay overly positive is immense, so it's vital to confront fears and be honest about the reality.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[THE RIGHT WAY TO LAY PEOPLE OFF]()**\",\"index\":392,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Shortly after we sold Opsware to Hewlett-Packard, I had a conversation with the legendary venture capitalist Doug Leone of Sequoia Capital. He wanted me to recount the story of how we went from doomed in the eyes of the world to a $1.6 billion outcome with no recapitalization.\",\"index\":393,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After I took him through the details—including several near bankruptcies, a stock price of $0.35 per share, unlimited bad press, and three separate layoffs where we lost a total of four hundred employees—he was most amazed by the layoffs. During more than twenty years in the venture capital business, he’d never seen a company recover from consecutive layoffs and achieve a billion-dollar-plus outcome. He confessed that he’d bet against that every time. Since my only experience was the great exception, I needed more information. I asked him why all the other startups failed. He replied that the layoffs inevitably broke the company’s culture. After seeing their friends laid off, employees were no longer willing to make the requisite sacrifices needed to build a company. He said that although it was possible to survive an isolated layoff, it was hugely unlikely that a company would experience great success. Building a highly valuable business, he added, after three consecutive giant layoffs accompanied by horrible prominent press coverage (we got taken apart with cover stories in both the *Wall Street Journal* and *BusinessWeek*), was a complete violation of the laws of venture capital physics. He wanted to know how we did it. After thinking about this question, here’s my answer.\",\"index\":394,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In retrospect, we were able to keep cultural continuity and retain our best employees despite multiple massive layoffs because we laid people off the right way. This may sound nutty—how can you do something that’s fundamentally wrong in “the right way”? Here’s how.\",\"index\":395,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Shortly after selling Opsware to Hewlett-Packard, I shared our story with Doug Leone of Sequoia Capital, detailing our journey from near bankruptcy and a stock price of $0.35 per share to a $1.6 billion outcome, without recapitalization. Doug was particularly astonished by our recovery despite three separate layoffs that saw 400 employees leave. In his 20+ years in venture capital, he had never seen a company rebound from consecutive layoffs to achieve such success. He explained that layoffs typically break a company's culture, making employees unwilling to make the sacrifices needed to build the company. It was this cultural continuity and retention of top employees that allowed us to defy the odds. We managed this by conducting layoffs in the right way—something that may sound unconventional, but here's how we did it.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 1: GET YOUR HEAD RIGHT**\",\"index\":396,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When a company fails to hit its financial plan so severely that it must fire the employees it went to great time and expense to hire, it weighs heavily on the chief executive. During the first layoff at our company, I remember being forwarded an email exchange among a group of employees. In the exchange, one of our smarter employees wrote, “Ben is either lying or stupid or both.” I remember reading that and thinking, “definitely stupid.” During a time like this, it is difficult to focus on the future, because the past overwhelms you—but that’s exactly what you must do.\",\"index\":397,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When a company fails to hit its financial plan so severely that it must fire the employees it went to great time and expense to hire, it weighs heavily on the chief executive. During the first layoff at our company, I remember being forwarded an email exchange among a group of employees. In the exchange, one of our smarter employees wrote, “Ben is either lying or stupid or both.” I remember reading that and thinking, “definitely stupid.” During a time like this, it is difficult to focus on the future, because the past overwhelms you—but that’s exactly what you must do.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 2: DON’T DELAY**\",\"index\":398,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Once you decide that you will have to lay people off, the time elapsed between making that decision and executing that decision should be as short as possible. If word leaks (which it will inevitably if you delay), then you will be faced with an additional set of issues. Employees will question managers and ask whether a layoff is coming. If the managers don’t know, they will look stupid. If the managers do know, they will either have to lie to their employees, contribute to the leak, or remain silent, which will create additional agitation. At Loudcloud/Opsware, we badly mismanaged this dynamic with our first round of layoffs, but sharply corrected things on the next two.\",\"index\":399,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Once you decide that you will have to lay people off, the time elapsed between making that decision and executing that decision should be as short as possible. If word leaks (which it will inevitably if you delay), then you will be faced with an additional set of issues. Employees will question managers and ask whether a layoff is coming. If the managers don’t know, they will look stupid. If the managers do know, they will either have to lie to their employees, contribute to the leak, or remain silent, which will create additional agitation. At Loudcloud/Opsware, we badly mismanaged this dynamic with our first round of layoffs, but sharply corrected things on the next two.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 3: BE CLEAR IN YOUR OWN MIND ABOUT WHY YOU ARE LAYING PEOPLE OFF**\",\"index\":400,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Going into a layoff, board members will sometimes try to make you feel better by putting a positive spin on things. They might say, “This gives us a great opportunity to deal with some performance issues and simplify the business.” That may be true, but do not let that cloud your thinking or your message to the company. You are laying people off because the company failed to hit its plan. If individual performance were the only issue, then you’d be taking a different measure. *Company* performance failed. This distinction is critical, because the message to the company and the laid-off individuals should not be “This is great, we are cleaning up performance.” The message must be “The company failed and in order to move forward, we will have to lose some excellent people.” Admitting to the failure may not seem like a big deal, but trust me, it is. “Trust me.” That’s what a CEO says every day to her employees. Trust me: This will be a good company. Trust me: This will be good for your career. Trust me: This will be good for your life. A layoff breaks that trust. In order to rebuild trust, you have to come clean.\",\"index\":401,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Going into a layoff, board members will sometimes try to make you feel better by putting a positive spin on things. They migh