 every last detail about that day and the details will matter greatly. The reputations of your company and your managers depend on you standing tall, facing the employees who trusted you and worked hard for you. If you hired me and I busted my ass working for you, I expect you to have the courage to lay me off yourself.\",\"index\":405,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Once you make it clear that managers must lay off their own people, be sure to prepare them for the task:\",\"index\":406,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** They should explain briefly what happened and that it is a company rather than a personal failure.\",\"index\":407,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** They should be clear that the employee is impacted and that the decision is nonnegotiable.\",\"index\":408,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** They should be fully prepared with all of the details about the benefits and support the company plans to provide.\",\"index\":409,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Once you make it clear that managers must lay off their own people, be sure to prepare them for the task: \\n\\n **1.** They should explain briefly what happened and that it is a company rather than a personal failure. \\n\\n **2.** They should be clear that the employee is impacted and that the decision is nonnegotiable. \\n\\n **3.** They should be fully prepared with all of the details about the benefits and support the company plans to provide.\"}],\"summary\":\"Training the management team is the most critical step in executing layoffs smoothly. Managers must personally lay off their own people—this task cannot be outsourced to HR or assigned to a confrontational peer. The rationale is simple: while employees may forget routine workdays, the layoff day will be etched in their memory, affecting both the company's and the managers' reputations. Employees expect the same person who hired them and appreciated their hard work to have the courage to deliver bad news directly. To prepare managers for this challenging task, they should 1) briefly explain the situation as a company failure, not a personal one, 2) clearly state that the decision is final, and 3) be ready with all details regarding the employee's benefits and support from the company.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 5: ADDRESS THE ENTIRE COMPANY**\",\"index\":410,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Prior to executing the layoff, the CEO must address the company. The CEO must deliver the overall message that provides the proper context and air cover for the managers. If you do your job right, the managers will have a much easier time doing their jobs. Keep in mind what former Intuit CEO Bill Campbell told me—*The message is for the people who are staying*. The people who stay will care deeply about how you treat their colleagues. Many of the people whom you lay off will have closer relationships with the people who stay than you do, so treat them with the appropriate level of respect. Still, the company must move forward, so be careful not to apologize too much.\",\"index\":411,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Prior to executing the layoff, the CEO must address the company. The CEO must deliver the overall message that provides the proper context and air cover for the managers. If you do your job right, the managers will have a much easier time doing their jobs. Keep in mind what former Intuit CEO Bill Campbell told me—*The message is for the people who are staying*. The people who stay will care deeply about how you treat their colleagues. Many of the people whom you lay off will have closer relationships with the people who stay than you do, so treat them with the appropriate level of respect. Still, the company must move forward, so be careful not to apologize too much.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 6: BE VISIBLE, BE PRESENT**\",\"index\":412,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After you make the speech telling your company that you will be letting many of them go, you will not feel like hanging out and talking to people. You will probably feel like going to a bar and drinking a fifth of tequila. Do not do this. Be present. Be visible. Be engaging. People want to see you. They want to see whether you care. The people whom you laid off will want to know if they still have a relationship with you and the company. Talk to people. Help them carry their things to their cars. Let them know that you appreciate their efforts.\",\"index\":413,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":414,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":415,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"After delivering the tough news about layoffs, you might feel like retreating to a bar with a bottle of tequila, but resist that urge. Instead, be present, visible, and engaging. Your employees need to see that you care. Those laid off will question if they still have a relationship with you and the company. Interact with your team, assist them with their belongings, and express your appreciation for their efforts.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When a company severely misses its financial targets, resulting in layoffs of recently hired employees, it greatly burdens the chief executive. From my experience, once you decide layoffs are necessary, execute them swiftly to avoid leaks and additional issues. Employees will inevitably suspect and stress over forthcoming decisions, complicating the situation if delayed. At Loudcloud/Opsware, we learned from our first poorly managed layoff and improved in subsequent rounds. Despite optimistic spins from board members, acknowledge the real issue: company failure, not individual performance. Transparency maintains trust, which is crucial to rebuild after layoffs. Training management is pivotal; they must personally handle layoffs, as employees expect this from those who hired and valued their work. Managers should convey that the layoffs result from company failure, affirm the finality of the decision, and provide detailed support information. Beforehand, the CEO should address the company to set context and support managers. Remember, the people staying will judge how well you treat their colleagues, impacting their morale. Ultimately, avoid excessive apologies; deliver the news respectfully and be visible to support your team, showing care and appreciation even in tough times.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When a company severely misses its financial targets, resulting in layoffs of recently hired employees, it greatly burdens the chief executive. From my experience, once you decide layoffs are necessary, execute them swiftly to avoid leaks and additional issues. Employees will inevitably suspect and stress over forthcoming decisions, complicating the situation if delayed. At Loudcloud/Opsware, we learned from our first poorly managed layoff and improved in subsequent rounds. Despite optimistic spins from board members, acknowledge the real issue: company failure, not individual performance. Transparency maintains trust, which is crucial to rebuild after layoffs. Training management is pivotal; they must personally handle layoffs, as employees expect this from those who hired and valued their work. Managers should convey that the layoffs result from company failure, affirm the finality of the decision, and provide detailed support information. Beforehand, the CEO should address the company to set context and support managers. Remember, the people staying will judge how well you treat their colleagues, impacting their morale. Ultimately, avoid excessive apologies; deliver the news respectfully and be visible to support your team, showing care and appreciation even in tough times.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[PREPARING TO FIRE AN EXECUTIVE]()**\",\"index\":416,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"When you recruit an executive, you paint a beautiful picture of her future in your company. You describe in great depth and in vibrant color how awesome it will be for her to accept your offer and how much better it will be than joining that other company. Then one day you realize you must fire her. Reconcile that, Ms. CEO.\",\"index\":417,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It turns out that the actual act of firing an executive can be relatively easy compared with any other firing. Executives have experience being on the other side of the conversation and tend to be quite professional. Firing an executive correctly is a bit more complicated and extremely important. If you do not learn the right lessons, you will be doing it again soon.\",\"index\":418,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Like so many things, the key to correctly firing an executive is preparation. Here is a four-step process that will treat the executive fairly and improve your company.\",\"index\":419,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When you recruit an executive, you paint a vibrant picture of her promising future in your company, emphasizing how much better it will be compared to joining another firm. However, one day the reality hits that you must fire her. Reconciling this as a CEO is tough. Surprisingly, the act of firing an executive is often easier than firing other employees, as executives tend to handle such conversations professionally due to their experience. The real challenge lies in firing an executive correctly, which is crucial because failing to learn the right lessons means you might face the same situation again. Like many things, the key to correctly firing an executive is preparation. Here is a four-step process to ensure you treat the executive fairly and improve your company.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 1: ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS**\",\"index\":420,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"While it’s possible to fire an executive for bad behavior, incompetence, or laziness, those cases are rare and relatively easy. Unfortunately, unless you have a horribly deficient hiring process, those are probably not the reasons why you got to this point. At this level, almost every company screens for the proper skill set, motivation, and track record. Yes, the reason that you have to fire your head of marketing is not because he sucks; it’s because *you* suck.\",\"index\":421,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In other words, the wrong way to view an executive firing is as an executive failure; the correct way to view an executive firing is as an interview/integration process system failure. Therefore, the first step to properly firing an executive is figuring out why you hired the wrong person for your company.\",\"index\":422,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"You may have blown it for a variety of reasons:\",\"index\":423,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *You did a poor job defining the position in the first place.* If you don’t know what you want, you will be unlikely to get it. Far too often, CEOs hire executives based on an abstract notion of what they think and feel the executive should be like. This error often leads to the executive not bringing the key, necessary qualities to the table.\\n\\n* *You hired for lack of weakness rather than for strengths.* This is especially common when you run a consensus-based hiring process. The group will often find the candidate’s weaknesses, but they won’t place a high enough value on the areas where you need the executive to be a world-class performer. As a result, you hire an executive with no sharp weaknesses, but who is mediocre where you need her to be great. If you don’t have world-class strengths where you need them, you won’t be a world-class company.\\n\\n* *You hired for scale too soon.* The most consistently wrong advice that venture capitalists and executive recruiters give CEOs is to hire someone “bigger” than required. “Think about the next three to five years and how you will be a large company” is how the bad advice usually sounds. It’s great to hire people who can run a large-scale organization if you have one. It’s also great to hire people who know how to grow an organization very fast if you are ready to grow your organization very fast. However, if you do not or you are not, then you need someone who can do the job for the next eighteen months. If you hire someone who will be great *in* eighteen months but will be poor for the next eighteen months, the company will reject her before she ever gets a chance to show her stuff. Your other employees will wonder: Why did we give her all those stock options when she’s not contributing anything? Those kinds of questions are impossible to recover from. It turns out that venture capitalists and executive recruiters are not stupid; they just learned the wrong lessons from previous failures. To learn the right lesson, see the *special case of scaling* and *the special case of fast growth* as explained below.\\n\\n* *You hired for the generic position.* There is no such thing as a great CEO, a great head of marketing, or a great head of sales. There is only a great head of sales for your company for the next twelve to twenty-four months. That position is not the same as the same position at Microsoft or Facebook. Don’t look for the candidate out of central casting. This is not a movie.\\n\\n* *The executive had the wrong kind of ambition.* In chapter 6, I will describe the difference between ambition for the company and ambition for oneself. If an executive has the wrong kind of ambition, then despite her skills, the company may reject her.\\n\\n* *You failed to integrate the executive.* Bringing a new person into your company in an important role is difficult. Other employees will be quick to judge, her expectations may be different from yours, and the job may be largely undefined. Be sure to review and improve your integration plan after you fire an executive.\",\"index\":424,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Firing an executive for bad behavior, incompetence, or laziness is rare and easy because proper companies usually screen for the right skills and motivation at this level. So, if you need to fire your head of marketing, it's likely a failure in your hiring or integration process. The correct way to view an executive firing is as a system failure and not an executive failure. Reasons for hiring the wrong person include:\\n\\n* Poorly defining the position.\\n* Hiring for lack of weaknesses instead of strengths.\\n* Hiring for scale too soon, based on bad advice from venture capitalists or recruiters.\\n* Hiring for a generic position rather than specific needs of your company.\\n* The executive having the wrong kind of ambition.\\n* Failure to properly integrate the executive into your company.\\n\\nIt's crucial to review and improve your interview and integration processes to avoid these pitfalls.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**The special case of scaling**\",\"index\":425,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A fairly common reason for firing an executive is that when the company quadruples in size, the executive no longer does the job effectively at the new size. The reason is that when a company multiplies in size, the management jobs become brand-new jobs. As a result, everybody needs to requalify for the new job, because the new job and the old job are not the same. Running a two-hundred-person global sales organization is not the same job as running a twenty-five-person local sales team. If you get lucky, the person you hired to run the twenty-five-person team will have learned how to run the two-hundred-person team. If not, you need to hire the right person for the new job. This is neither an executive failure nor a system failure; it is life in the big city. Do not attempt to avoid this phenomenon, as you will only make things worse.\",\"index\":426,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"A fairly common reason for firing an executive is that when the company quadruples in size, the executive no longer does the job effectively at the new size. The reason is that when a company multiplies in size, the management jobs become brand-new jobs. As a result, everybody needs to requalify for the new job, because the new job and the old job are not the same. Running a two-hundred-person global sales organization is not the same job as running a twenty-five-person local sales team. If you get lucky, the person you hired to run the twenty-five-person team will have learned how to run the two-hundred-person team. If not, you need to hire the right person for the new job. This is neither an executive failure nor a system failure; it is life in the big city. Do not attempt to avoid this phenomenon, as you will only make things worse.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**The special case of fast growth**\",\"index\":427,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you build a great product and the market wants it, you will find yourself needing to grow your company extremely quickly. Nothing will ensure your success like hiring the right executive who has grown an organization like yours very quickly and successfully before. Note that this is not the same as inheriting a very large organization or working your way up to running a very large organization. Make sure you hire the right kind of fast-growth executive. Also, do not hire this person if you are not ready to give them lots of budget to grow their organization; expect them to do what they do. The successful fast-growth executive is so important to building successful startups that recruiters and venture capitalists often advise CEOs to bring them in before the company is ready.\",\"index\":428,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"If you build a great product and the market wants it, you will find yourself needing to grow your company extremely quickly. Nothing will ensure your success like hiring the right executive who has grown an organization like yours very quickly and successfully before. Note that this is not the same as inheriting a very large organization or working your way up to running a very large organization. Make sure you hire the right kind of fast-growth executive. Also, do not hire this person if you are not ready to give them lots of budget to grow their organization; expect them to do what they do. The successful fast-growth executive is so important to building successful startups that recruiters and venture capitalists often advise CEOs to bring them in before the company is ready.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When a company quadruples in size, the effectiveness of an executive can diminish because the job fundamentally changes, necessitating requalification for what is essentially a new role. Managing a 200-person global sales team is vastly different from leading a 25-person local sales group. If the original hire adapts and grows with the company, great—but if not, you must bring in someone suited for the larger role. This is a natural part of business scaling, not a failure. Rapid company growth hinges on hiring the right executives with proven experience in scaling organizations swiftly. Ensure that these fast-growth executives have the necessary budget and authority to drive expansion. Recruiters and venture capitalists often suggest onboarding such talent even before the company seems ready, highlighting their critical role in successful startups.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"content\":\"Once you identify the problem, then you create the basis for the next steps.\",\"index\":429,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When a company quadruples in size, an executive's effectiveness may diminish because the role fundamentally changes, requiring requalification for what is essentially a new job. Managing a 200-person global sales team is markedly different from leading a 25-person local group. If the initial hire can adapt and grow with the company, great—but if not, you need to bring in someone better suited for the larger role. This is a natural aspect of business scaling, not a failure. Rapid growth relies on hiring executives experienced in scaling organizations quickly. These fast-growth executives need the necessary budget and authority to drive expansion. Recruiters and venture capitalists often propose hiring such talent even before the company seems ready, emphasizing their critical role in startup success. Once you identify the problem, you create the basis for the next steps.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 2: INFORMING THE BOARD**\",\"index\":430,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Informing the board is tricky and many issues can further complicate the task:\",\"index\":431,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* This is the fifth or sixth executive that you had to fire.\\n\\n* This is the third executive that you fired in this role.\\n\\n* The candidate was referred by a board member who recommended the executive as a superstar.\",\"index\":432,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Realize that in any of these cases the board will be at least somewhat alarmed and there is nothing that you can do about that. But keep in mind that your choices are: (a) alarm the board or (b) enable an ineffective executive to remain in her position. While choice (a) is not great, it’s a heck of a lot better than choice (b). Leaving a failing leader in place will cause an entire department in your company to slowly rot. Let that happen and the board will be more than alarmed.\",\"index\":433,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"You should have three goals with the board:\",\"index\":434,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Get their support and understanding for the difficult task that you will execute.* You should start by making sure that they understand the root cause and your plan to remedy the situation. This will give them confidence in your ability to hire and manage outside executives in the future.\\n\\n* *Get their input and approval for the separation package.* This will be critical for the next step. Executive packages are larger than regular severance packages and rightly so. It takes about ten times longer for an executive to find a new job than it does for an individual contributor.\\n\\n* *Preserve the reputation of the fired executive.* The failure was very likely a team effort, and it’s best to portray it that way. You don’t make yourself look good by trashing someone who worked for you. A mature approach to this issue will help keep the board confident in your ability to be CEO. It’s also the fair and decent thing to do.\",\"index\":435,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Finally, firing an executive turns out to be a piece of news that’s handled better with individual phone calls than in dramatic fashion during a board meeting. It takes a bit longer, but it’s well worth the effort. Individual conversations will be particularly important if one of the board members introduced the executive to the company. Once everyone agrees individually, you can finalize the details in a board meeting or call.\",\"index\":436,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Informing the board about firing an executive is challenging, especially if this is the fifth or sixth executive you've had to let go or the third in this particular role, particularly when the candidate was recommended as a \\\"superstar\\\" by a board member. While the board will undoubtedly be alarmed, you must choose between alarming them or keeping an ineffective executive, risking greater harm to your company. When approaching the board, aim to (1) gain their support and understanding by explaining the root cause and your remedial plan, which will boost their confidence in your hiring and management skills; (2) secure their input and approval for the executive's separation package, crucial because executive severance takes longer to resolve; and (3) preserve the reputation of the fired executive, acknowledging that the failure was likely a team effort, which maintains your credibility and is the fair thing to do. Additionally, it's best to inform the board individually via phone calls, especially if a member recommended the executive, allowing for a smoother final agreement during a meeting or call.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 3: PREPARING FOR THE CONVERSATION**\",\"index\":437,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After you know what went wrong and have informed the board, you should tell the executive as quickly as possible. In preparation for that meeting, I recommend scripting or rehearsing what you plan to say so that you do not misspeak. The executive will remember the conversation for a very long time, so you need to get it right.\",\"index\":438,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As part of your preparation, you should review any performance reviews or written performance conversations to understand any inconsistencies in your prior communication.\",\"index\":439,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Three keys to getting it right:\",\"index\":440,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** *Be clear on the reasons.* You have thought about this long and hard; don’t equivocate or sugarcoat it. You owe it to them to be clear about what you think happened.\",\"index\":441,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** *Use decisive language.* Do not leave the discussion open-ended. This is not a performance review; it’s a firing. Use words and phrases like “I have decided” rather than “I think.”\",\"index\":442,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** *Have the severance package approved and ready.* Once the executive hears the news, she will stop caring about the company and its issues; she will be highly focused on herself and her family. Be ready to provide specific details of the severance package.\",\"index\":443,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Three keys to getting it right: \\n\\n **1.** *Be clear on the reasons.* You have thought about this long and hard; don’t equivocate or sugarcoat it. You owe it to them to be clear about what you think happened. \\n\\n **2.** *Use decisive language.* Do not leave the discussion open-ended. This is not a performance review; it’s a firing. Use words and phrases like “I have decided” rather than “I think.” \\n\\n **3.** *Have the severance package approved and ready.* Once the executive hears the news, she will stop caring about the company and its issues; she will be highly focused on herself and her family. Be ready to provide specific details of the severance package.\"},{\"content\":\"Finally, the executive will be keenly interested in how the news will be communicated to the company and to the outside world. It is best to let her decide. Bill Campbell once gave me a critical bit of advice when I was preparing to fire an executive. He said, “Ben, you cannot let him keep his job, but you absolutely can let him keep his respect.”\",\"index\":444,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"After identifying what went wrong and informing the board, promptly tell the executive. Prepare for the meeting by scripting or rehearsing to avoid misspeaking since the executive will remember the conversation for a long time. Review any performance reviews or communication for inconsistencies. Follow these key guidelines: \\n\\n**1.** Be crystal clear on the reasons; don't sugarcoat. You owe them clarity on what happened. \\n**2.** Use decisive language, indicating final decisions rather than possibilities. Say “I have decided” instead of “I think.”\\n**3.** Have the severance package approved and ready, as the executive will focus on personal implications. Provide specific details. \\n\\nFinally, allow the executive to decide how the news is communicated to others. As Bill Campbell advised, while they can't keep their job, they can keep their respect.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 4: PREPARING THE COMPANY COMMUNICATION**\",\"index\":445,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After you have informed the executive, you must quickly update the company and your staff on the change. The correct order for informing the company is (1) the executive’s direct reports—because they will be most impacted; (2) the other members of your staff—because they will need to answer questions about it; and (3) the rest of the company. All of these communications should happen on the same day and preferably within a couple of hours. When disclosing the firing to the direct reports, make sure that you have a plan for whom they will report to in the meantime and what’s next (executive search, reorganization, internal promotion, or something else). Generally, it’s smart for the CEO to act in the executive role in the meanwhile. If you do act in the role, you must really act—staff meetings, one-on-ones, objective setting, etc. Doing so will provide excellent continuity for the team and greatly inform your thinking on whom to hire next.\",\"index\":446,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As you did when you updated the board, keep the message positive and refrain from throwing the executive under the bus. The best employees in the organization will likely be the ones closest to the executive. If you trash her, you will put all her best employees on notice that they are next. Is that a message you want to send?\",\"index\":447,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When you update the company, you might worry about employees misinterpreting the news and thinking the company is in trouble. Do not try to maneuver around such a reaction. When you expect your employees to act like adults, they generally do. If you treat them like children, then get ready for your company to turn into one big *Barney* episode.\",\"index\":448,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"After informing the executive, swiftly update the company and staff about the change. The correct order is (1) the executive’s direct reports, as they will be most impacted; (2) the other staff members, who will need to answer questions; and (3) the rest of the company. Aim to communicate all this on the same day, ideally within a few hours. When telling direct reports, have a clear plan for interim reporting, such as the CEO stepping in temporarily and handling all related duties—staff meetings, one-on-ones, and objective setting. This ensures continuity and helps inform your decision on the next hire. Keep the announcement positive and avoid badmouthing the executive to prevent unsettling her best employees. If you worry about misinterpretation and concerns about the company’s stability, address it head-on. Expect your employees to act like adults, and they usually will. Trying to manage their reactions as if they were children can backfire, akin to turning the workplace into a *Barney* episode.\",\"type\":\"