,\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** People who quit\",\"index\":474,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** People who got fired\",\"index\":475,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** People who quit, but it’s okay because the company didn’t want them anyway\",\"index\":476,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“She left, but we were going to fire her, or give her a bad performance review.” High-tech companies tend to track employee attrition in three categories: \\n\\n **1.** People who quit \\n\\n **2.** People who got fired \\n\\n **3.** People who quit, but it’s okay because the company didn’t want them anyway\"},{\"content\":\"Fascinatingly, as companies begin to struggle, the third category always seems to grow much faster than the first. In addition, the sudden wave of “semi-performance-related attrition” usually happens in companies that claim to have a “super-high talent bar.” How do all these superstar employees suddenly go from great to crap? How is it possible that when you lose a top-rated employee before you can say “unwanted attrition,” the manager carefully explains how her performance fell off?\",\"index\":477,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"“We would have won, but the other guys gave the deal away.” “The customer selected us technically and thinks we are the better company, but our competitor just gave the product away. We would never sell so cheaply as it would hurt our reputation.” Anybody who has ever run an enterprise sales force has heard this lie before. You go into an account, you fight hard, and you lose. The sales rep, not wanting to shine the light on himself, blames the “used car dealer” rep from the other company. The CEO, not wanting to believe that she’s losing product competitiveness, believes the rep. If you hear this lie, try to validate the claim with the actual customer. I’ll bet you can’t.\",\"index\":478,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"“Just because we missed the intermediate milestones doesn’t mean we won’t hit our product schedule.” In engineering meetings where there is great pressure to ship on time—a customer commitment, a quarter that depends on it, or a competitive imperative—everybody hopes for good news. When the facts don’t align with the good news, a clever manager will find the narrative to make everybody feel better—until the next meeting.\",\"index\":479,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"“We have a very high churn rate, but as soon as we turn on email marketing to our user base, people will come back.” Yes, of course. The reason that people leave our service and don’t come back is that we have not been sending them enough spam. That makes total sense to me, too.\",\"index\":480,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Where do lies come from?\",\"index\":481,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"To answer that question, I thought back to a conversation I had years ago with the incomparable Andy Grove.\",\"index\":482,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Back at the tail end of the Great Internet Bubble in 2001, as all the big technology companies began missing their quarters by giant amounts, I found myself wondering how none of them saw it coming. One would think that after the dot-com crash of April 2000, companies like Cisco, Siebel, and HP would realize that they would soon face a slowdown as many of their customers hit the wall. But despite perhaps the most massive and public early warning system ever, each CEO reiterated strong guidance right up to the point where they dramatically whiffed their quarters.\",\"index\":483,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I asked Andy why these great CEOs would lie about their impending fate.\",\"index\":484,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"He said they were not lying to investors, but rather, they were lying to themselves.\",\"index\":485,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Andy explained that humans, particularly those who build things, only listen to leading indicators of good news. For example, if a CEO hears that engagement for her application increased an incremental 25 percent beyond the normal growth rate one month, she will be off to the races hiring more engineers to keep up with the impending tidal wave of demand. On the other hand, if engagement decreases 25 percent, she will be equally intense and urgent in explaining it away: “The site was slow that month, there were four holidays, and we made a UI change that caused all the problems. For gosh sakes, let’s not panic!”\",\"index\":486,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Both leading indicators may have been wrong, or both may have been right, but our hypothetical CEO—like almost every other CEO—only took action on the positive indicator and only looked for alternative explanations on the negative leading indicator.\",\"index\":487,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If this advice sounds too familiar. and you find yourself wondering why your honest employees are lying to you, the answer is they are not. They are lying to themselves.\",\"index\":488,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"And if you believe them, you are lying to yourself.\",\"index\":489,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":490,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":491,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"High-tech companies meticulously track employee attrition in three categories: people who quit, those who were fired, and those who quit but weren’t valued. Notably, as companies struggle, the third category expands faster than the first, particularly in firms with a \\\"super-high talent bar.\\\" This raises questions about how top-rated employees suddenly become unremarkable. Managers often rationalize a top employee's departure by citing a decline in performance. Similarly, in enterprise sales, lost deals are frequently blamed on competitors underselling, a narrative readily accepted by CEOs to avoid facing product competitiveness issues. In engineering, missed milestones are downplayed to preserve hope for meeting final product schedules, and user churn is often blamed on insufficient email marketing, assuming spam will recover users. These rationalizations, discussed with the exceptional Andy Grove, highlight that lies often stem from a need to deflect blame or maintain optimism. Andy explained that during the dot-com crash, CEOs weren’t lying to investors about their struggles; they were lying to themselves. Builders, especially CEOs, focus on positive indicators and rationalize away negative ones, acting on good news and dismissing bad news with excuses. This self-deception means if you believe them, you’re lying to yourself too.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"High-tech companies meticulously track employee attrition in three categories: people who quit, those who were fired, and those who quit but weren’t valued. Notably, as companies struggle, the third category expands faster than the first, particularly in firms with a \\\"super-high talent bar.\\\" This raises questions about how top-rated employees suddenly become unremarkable. Managers often rationalize a top employee's departure by citing a decline in performance. Similarly, in enterprise sales, lost deals are frequently blamed on competitors underselling, a narrative readily accepted by CEOs to avoid facing product competitiveness issues. In engineering, missed milestones are downplayed to preserve hope for meeting final product schedules, and user churn is often blamed on insufficient email marketing, assuming spam will recover users. These rationalizations, discussed with the exceptional Andy Grove, highlight that lies often stem from a need to deflect blame or maintain optimism. Andy explained that during the dot-com crash, CEOs weren’t lying to investors about their struggles; they were lying to themselves. Builders, especially CEOs, focus on positive indicators and rationalize away negative ones, acting on good news and dismissing bad news with excuses. This self-deception means if you believe them, you’re lying to yourself too.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"High-tech companies meticulously track employee attrition in three categories: people who quit, those who were fired, and those who quit but weren’t valued. Notably, as companies struggle, the third category expands faster than the first, particularly in firms with a \\\"super-high talent bar.\\\" This raises questions about how top-rated employees suddenly become unremarkable. Managers often rationalize a top employee's departure by citing a decline in performance. Similarly, in enterprise sales, lost deals are frequently blamed on competitors underselling, a narrative readily accepted by CEOs to avoid facing product competitiveness issues. In engineering, missed milestones are downplayed to preserve hope for meeting final product schedules, and user churn is often blamed on insufficient email marketing, assuming spam will recover users. These rationalizations, discussed with the exceptional Andy Grove, highlight that lies often stem from a need to deflect blame or maintain optimism. Andy explained that during the dot-com crash, CEOs weren’t lying to investors about their struggles; they were lying to themselves. Builders, especially CEOs, focus on positive indicators and rationalize away negative ones, acting on good news and dismissing bad news with excuses. This self-deception means if you believe them, you’re lying to yourself too.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[LEAD BULLETS]()**\",\"index\":492,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Early in my tenure at Netscape, when we realized that Microsoft’s new Web server had every feature that ours had, but was also five times faster and was to be given away for free, I immediately went to work trying to pivot our server product line to something that we could sell for money. The late, great Mike Homer and I worked furiously on a set of partnerships and acquisitions that would broaden the product line and surround the Web server with enough functionality that we would be able to survive the attack.\",\"index\":493,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I excitedly reviewed the plan with my engineering counterpart, Bill Turpin, who looked at me as though I were a little kid who had much to learn. Bill was a longtime veteran of battling Microsoft from his time at Borland and understood what I was trying to do, but he was not persuaded. He said, “Ben, those silver bullets that you and Mike are looking for are fine and good, but our Web server is five times slower. There is no silver bullet that’s going to fix that. No, we are going to have to use a lot of lead bullets.” Oh snap.\",\"index\":494,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As a result of Bill’s advice, we focused our engineering team on fixing the performance issues while working on the other things in the background. We eventually beat Microsoft’s performance and grew the server line to become a $400 million business, and we would never have done it without those lead bullets.\",\"index\":495,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I carried that lesson with me for many years. Six years later, when I was CEO of Opsware, our toughest competitor, BladeLogic, started to consistently beat us in large deals. We were a public company, and the losses were all too visible. To make matters worse, we needed to win those deals in order to beat Wall Street’s projections, so the company felt tremendous pressure. Many of our smartest people came to me with ideas for avoiding the battle:\",\"index\":496,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* “Let’s build a lightweight version of the product and go down-market.”\\n\\n* “Let’s acquire a company with a simpler architecture.”\\n\\n* “Let’s focus on service providers.”\",\"index\":497,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"All these approaches reinforced to me was that we weren’t facing a market problem. The customers were buying; they just weren’t buying *our* product. This was not a time to pivot. So I said the same thing to every one of them: “There are no silver bullets for this, only lead bullets.” They did not want to hear that, but it made things clear: We had to build a better product. There was no other way out. No window, no hole, no escape hatch, no back door. We had to go through the front door and deal with the big, ugly guy blocking it. Lead bullets.\",\"index\":498,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After nine months of hard work on an extremely rugged product cycle, we regained our product lead and eventually built a company that was worth $1.6 billion. Without the lead bullets, I suspect we would have ended at about one-tenth that value.\",\"index\":499,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There may be nothing scarier in business than facing an existential threat. So scary that many in the organization will do anything to avoid facing it. They will look for any alternative, any way out, any excuse not to live or die in a single battle. I see this often in startup pitches. The conversations go something like this:\",\"index\":500,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Entrepreneur: “We have the best product in the market by far. All the customers love it and prefer it to competitor X.”\",\"index\":501,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Me: “Why does competitor X have five times your revenue?”\",\"index\":502,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Entrepreneur: “We are using partners and OEMs, because we can’t build a direct channel like competitor X.”\",\"index\":503,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Me: “Why not? If you have the better product, why not knuckle up and go to war?”\",\"index\":504,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Entrepreneur: “Ummm.”\",\"index\":505,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Me: “Stop looking for the silver bullet.”\",\"index\":506,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Entrepreneur: “We have the best product in the market by far. All the customers love it and prefer it to competitor X.” \\n\\n Me: “Why does competitor X have five times your revenue?” \\n\\n Entrepreneur: “We are using partners and OEMs, because we can’t build a direct channel like competitor X.” \\n\\n Me: “Why not? If you have the better product, why not knuckle up and go to war?” \\n\\n Entrepreneur: “Ummm.” \\n\\n Me: “Stop looking for the silver bullet.”\"},{\"content\":\"There comes a time in every company’s life where it must fight for its life. If you find yourself running when you should be fighting, you need to ask yourself, “If our company isn’t good enough to win, then do we need to exist at all?”\",\"index\":507,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":508,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":509,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Early in my time at Netscape, we discovered that Microsoft's new Web server was not only as feature-rich as ours but also five times faster and free. Mike Homer and I scrambled to pivot through partnerships and acquisitions to stay competitive. However, Bill Turpin, my engineering counterpart, made it clear our significant performance lag required fundamental improvements—\\\"lead bullets.\\\" By focusing on performance issues alongside additional functionality, we eventually surpassed Microsoft's performance and grew substantially. Years later, as CEO of Opsware, facing a similar threat from BladeLogic, many suggested diversion tactics, but I emphasized \\\"lead bullets\\\" once more. We committed to enhancing our product, regained our market position, and built a $1.6 billion company. This experience taught me that when faced with an existential threat, silver bullets are futile; the only path to survival and success is through hard, unglamorous work.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[NOBODY CARES]()**\",\"index\":510,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“Just win, baby.”\",\"index\":511,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**—AL DAVIS**\",\"index\":512,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“Just win, baby.” \\n\\n **—AL DAVIS**\"},{\"content\":\"Back in those bad old days at Loudcloud, I often thought to myself: How could I have possibly prepared for this? How could I know that half our customers would go out of business? How could I know that it would become impossible to raise money in the private markets? How could I have figured out that there would be 221 IPOs in 2000 and 19 in 2001? Could anybody expect me to achieve a reasonable outcome given those circumstances?\",\"index\":513,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As I was feeling sorry for myself, I randomly watched an interview with famous football coach Bill Parcells. He was telling the story of how he had a similar dilemma when he began his head coaching career. In his very first season, Parcells’s team, the New York Giants, was hit with a rash of injuries. He worried incessantly about the impact of the injuries on his team’s fortunes, as it is difficult enough to win with your best players, let alone a bunch of substitutes. Wh