ly I’d attempted to take the VP of professional services from Loudcloud and make him the VP of sales. That didn’t work. The next head of sales would be the fourth one hired since we had founded the company three years earlier—not a great track record. More important, the next mistake I made on a sales leader would be my last. The marketplace, not to mention Wall Street investors, did not leave me with much rope.\",\"index\":529,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"To better prepare for the hire this time, I decided in the interim to run sales myself. I managed the team, ran the forecast calls, and was the one person responsible for the revenue number for Opsware. I’d learned the hard way that when hiring executives, one should follow Colin Powell’s instructions and hire for strength rather than lack of weakness. By running sales, I understood very clearly the strengths we needed. I made a careful list and set out to find the sales executives with the right skills and talents for Opsware.\",\"index\":530,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After interviewing about two dozen candidates—none of whom had the strengths I sought—I interviewed Mark Cranney. He wasn’t what I expected; he didn’t fit the stereotype of a hard-charging sales executive. For starters, Mark was average height, whereas most sales executives tend to be rather tall. Next, he was a square guy—that is, he was as wide as he was tall. Not fat, just square. His square body seemed to fit rather uncomfortably into what must have been a custom-tailored suit—there is no way an off-the-rack business suit would fit a square guy like Mark.\",\"index\":531,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"And then I looked at his résumé. The first thing I noticed was that he went to a school that I’d never heard of, Southern Utah University. I asked him what kind of school it was. He replied, “It was the MIT of southern Utah.” That was the last joke he told. Mark’s seriousness was so intense that it seemed to make him uncomfortable in his own skin. He made me uncomfortable, too. Ordinarily, that vibe would rule out a candidate for me, but the strengths that I needed were so critical to the business that I was willing to overlook every weakness. One interview technique that I’d used to sort the good from the bad was to ask a series of questions about hiring, training, and managing sales reps. Typically, it would go like this:\",\"index\":532,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Ben: “What do you look for in a sales rep?”\",\"index\":533,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Candidate: “They need to be smart, aggressive, and competitive. They need to know how to do complex deals and navigate organizations.”\",\"index\":534,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ben: “How do you test for those things in an interview?”\",\"index\":535,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Candidate: “Umm, well, I hire everybody out of my network.”\",\"index\":536,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ben: “Okay, once you get them on board, what do you expect from them?”\",\"index\":537,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Candidate: “I expect them to understand and follow the sales process, I expect them to master the product, I expect them to be accurate in their forecasting. . . .”\",\"index\":538,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ben: “Tell me about the training program that you designed to achieve this.”\",\"index\":539,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Candidate: “Umm.” They would then proceed to make something up as they went along.\",\"index\":540,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Ben: “What do you look for in a sales rep?” \\n\\n Candidate: “They need to be smart, aggressive, and competiti