 to fill the VP of sales role faltered multiple times, pushing me to manage sales directly and understand the role's requirements deeply. After interviewing about two dozen candidates, I met Mark Cranney, who, despite his serious demeanor and atypical background, exhibited essential strengths and a comprehensive approach to training sales teams. Although his aggressive style and cultural fit raised concerns, particularly from Joe, his sales acumen and proactive nature impressed many, leading to tough yet ultimately positive endorsements. Despite executive and board opposition, I recognized that Cranney's unique capabilities were crucial for our wartime needs. With Marc Andreessen's eventual agreement, Cranney was hired, marking a pivotal decision in forging a world-class team from the remnants of Loudcloud. Embracing Mark’s genius, despite cultural challenges, exemplified Jim Barksdale’s principle of prioritizing people, ensuring a creative and joyful workplace crucial for surviving tough times.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[A GOOD PLACE TO WORK]()**\",\"index\":575,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"At Opsware I used to teach a management expectations course because I deeply believed in training. I made it clear that I expected every manager to meet with her people on a regular basis. I even gave instructions on how to conduct a one-on-one meeting so there could be no excuses.\",\"index\":576,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Then one day, while I happily went about my job, it came to my attention that one of my managers hadn’t had a one-on-one meeting with any of his employees in more than six months. While I knew to “expect what I inspect,” I did not expect this. No one-on-one in more than six months? How was it possible for me to invest so much time thinking about management, preparing materials, and personally training my managers and then get no one-