FERENCE BETWEEN LIFE AND DEATH**\",\"index\":607,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When things go well, the reasons to stay at a company are many:\",\"index\":608,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Your career path is wide open because as the company grows lots of interesting jobs naturally open up.\\n\\n* Your friends and family think you are a genius for choosing to work at the “it” company before anyone else knew it was “it.”\\n\\n* Your résumé gets stronger by working at a blue-chip company in its heyday.\\n\\n* Oh, and you are getting rich.\",\"index\":609,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When things go poorly, all those reasons become reasons to leave. In fact, the only thing that keeps an employee at a company when things go horribly wrong—other than needing a job—is that she likes her job.\",\"index\":610,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When things go well, the reasons to stay at a company are numerous: a wide-open career path as the company grows, admiration from friends and family for being at the \\\"it\\\" company, a stronger résumé from working at a blue-chip company in its prime, and financial gains. However, when things go poorly, all those reasons become motives to leave. Ultimately, the only factor that keeps an employee at a company when things go horribly wrong—aside from needing a job—is that she likes her job.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THINGS ALWAYS GO WRONG**\",\"index\":611,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There has never been a company in the history of the world that had a monotonously increasing stock price. In bad companies, when the economics disappear, so do the employees. In technology companies, when the employees disappear, the spiral begins: The company declines in value, the best employees leave, the company declines in value, the best employees leave. Spirals are extremely difficult to reverse.\",\"index\":612,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"There has never been a company in the history of the world that had a monotonously increasing stock price. In bad companies, when the economics disappear, so do the employees. In technology companies, when the employees disappear, the spiral begins: The company declines in value, the best employees leave, the company declines in value, the best employees leave. Spirals are extremely difficult to reverse.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**BEING A GOOD COMPANY IS AN END IN ITSELF**\",\"index\":613,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I first met Bill Campbell, he was chairman of Intuit, on the board of Apple, and a mentor to many of the top CEOs in the industry. However, those things did not impress me nearly as much as his time running GO Corporation back in 1992. The company raised more money than almost any other venture-capital-backed startup in history and lost nearly all of it before selling itself for nearly nothing to AT&T in 1994.\",\"index\":614,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Now that probably doesn’t sound impressive. In fact, it probably sounds like a horrible failure. But I’d met dozens of GO employees in my career, including great people like Mike Homer, Danny Shader, Frank Chen, and Stratton Sclavos. The amazing thing was that every one of those GO employees counted GO as one of the greatest work experiences of their lives. The best work experience ever despite the fact that their careers stood still, they made no money, and they were front-page failures. GO was a good place to work.\",\"index\":615,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"This made me realize what an amazingly effective CEO Bill was. Apparently, John Doerr thought that, too, because when Scott Cook needed a CEO for Intuit, John recommended Bill even though Bill lost a ton of John’s money at GO. And for years, everyone who ever came into contact with GO employees knew what Bill was about. He was about building good companies.\",\"index\":616,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you do nothing else, be like Bill and build a good company.\",\"index\":617,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":618,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":619,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When I first met Bill Campbell, he was chairman of Intuit, on the board of Apple, and a mentor to many top CEOs, but what impressed me most was his time running GO Corporation in 1992. Despite GO raising vast amounts of venture capital and ultimately losing nearly all of it before selling to AT&T in 1994, every former GO employee I met, including greats like Mike Homer and Danny Shader, considered it the best work experience of their lives. They valued their time at GO, not for the financial success, which was nonexistent, but for the quality of the work environment Bill created. This showed me just how effective a CEO Bill truly was, a sentiment shared by John Doerr, who recommended Bill to lead Intuit despite the financial losses at GO. Bill was dedicated to building good companies, and if you do nothing else, be like Bill and build a good company.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"You could argue that no company can succeed without product/market fit, and poorly managed companies can still thrive if they achieve it. You'd be right. My dramatic speech and threat to one of my executives were necessary for three reasons: being a good company matters when things go awry, problems are inevitable, and being a good company is valuable in itself. When things go well, employees stay for numerous reasons—career growth, admiration from family and friends, a stronger résumé, and financial gains. However, when things go poorly, these motives turn into reasons to leave. 