y, create valuable collateral, and focus on market value, avoiding distractions and maintaining clear reporting. Bad product managers, on the other hand, make excuses, focus on the wrong metrics, and fail in communication and management, leading to poor execution and constant need for direction.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[IS IT OKAY TO HIRE PEOPLE FROM YOUR FRIEND’S COMPANY?]()**\",\"index\":663,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Every good technology company needs great people. The best companies invest time, money, and sweat equity into becoming world-class recruiting machines. But how far should you take your quest to build the world’s greatest team? Is it fair game to hire employees from your friend’s company? Will you still be friends?\",\"index\":664,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"First, what do I mean by “friends”? There are two relevant categories:\",\"index\":665,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Important business partners\\n\\n* Friends\",\"index\":666,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For this discussion, friends and important business partners are roughly the same.\",\"index\":667,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Most CEOs would never target a friend’s company as a source of talent. As CEO, one generally doesn’t have many true friends in business, and raiding your friend’s company is a sure way to lose one. Nevertheless, almost every CEO will be faced with the decision of whether to hire an employee out of her friend’s company. How does it happen? When is it okay? When will it cost you a friend?\",\"index\":668,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Every good technology company needs great people and must invest time, money, and effort to become a world-class recruiting machine. But how far should you go in building the best team? Is it ethical to hire employees from a friend’s company? And can your friendship survive it? For this discussion, “friends” and \\\"important business partners\\\" are roughly the same. Most CEOs wouldn’t target a friend’s company for talent, as it's a surefire way to lose one of their few true business friends. However, every CEO will likely face the decision of whether to hire someone from a friend's company. So, how does this happen, when is it okay, and when will it cost you a friend?\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**BUT THEY WERE ALREADY LOOKING**\",\"index\":669,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It always starts in the same way. Your friend Cathy has a great engineer working for her named Mitchell. Mitchell happens to be friends with one of your top engineers. Your engineer brings Mitchell in for an interview, unbeknownst to you, and he naturally sails through the process. The final step is the interview with you, the CEO. You immediately notice that Mitchell currently works at your good friend Cathy’s company. You check with your people to make sure that they did not approach Mitchell first, and they assure you that Mitchell was already looking and will go to another company if not yours. Now what?\",\"index\":670,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At this point, you might be thinking, “If Mitchell is leaving, then logically my friend Cathy should want him to go to my company rather than to a competitor or a company with a CEO whom she doesn’t like.” Maybe Cathy will see it that way, but probably not.\",\"index\":671,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"People generally leave companies when things are not going well, so you should assume that Cathy is fighting for her company’s life. In this situation, nothing will cut her deeper than losing a great employee, because she knows that the other employees will see that as a leading indicator of the company’s demise. Even more damaging for Cathy is the fact that her employees will perceive your move as an act of betrayal—Cathy’s so-called friend is raiding her company. They will think, “Cathy is such an ineffective CEO that she cannot even keep her friends from hiring her people.” In this way, a logical issue quickly becomes an emotional one.\",\"index\":672,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"You don’t want to lose Cathy as a friend, so you assure her that Mitchell is the exception and that he came to you and that he will be the first and only one of her employees that joins your company. Generally, this explanation will work and Cathy will understand and appreciate the gesture. She will forgive, but rest assured, she will not forget.\",\"index\":673,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Her memory of Mitchell will be important, because Mitchell will be just the first step in the demise of your relationship. Since Mitchell is a stellar hire, Cathy’s other strong employees will likely call Mitchell to understand why he left and where he is going. He will explain his reasoning and his reasons will be compelling. And suddenly they will want to follow Mitchell’s path and join your company, too. By the time you become aware of the situation, promises will have been made to prospective employees who approached Mitchell and offers may be out.\",\"index\":674,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In each case, your employees will assure you that they were approached by Cathy’s employees and not vice versa. They will point out that the candidates have offers from other companies as well, so they will definitely leave and you might as well benefit from their restlessness. Cathy’s managers will almost certainly tell a different story. They will plead with her to get her friend to stop raiding their stable of employees or else they will never be able to meet their commitments. This will embarrass and enrage Cathy. In the end, social pressure will trump all your brilliant countervailing logic.\",\"index\":675,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Here’s an easy way to think about the dynamic. If your husband left you, would you want your best friend to date him? He’s going to date somebody, so wouldn’t you want your friend to have him? It seems logical, but this situation is far from logical and you just lost one friend.\",\"index\":676,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"It always begins the same way: Mitchell, a talented engineer working for your friend Cathy, gets brought in for an interview at your company by one of your top engineers. He sails through the process and is now up for a final interview with you, the CEO. Realizing he works for Cathy, you verify that Mitchell was already looking for a new job and would go elsewhere if not hired by you. While you might think Cathy would prefer Mitchell join your company over a competitor’s, the situation is more complex. Employees leaving signals trouble, and Cathy’s team might see this as a betrayal, damaging her leadership credibility. You assure Cathy that Mitchell is an exception and not a poaching strategy, typically calming the initial tension. However, Mitchell's departure can trigger a domino effect, compelling other top employees to follow his path to your company. Despite assurances that Cathy’s employees approached Mitchell first, the narrative will likely anger her, viewing it as a raid. In the end, social pressures and emotions override logical explanations, risking not just professional friction but also your personal friendship with Cathy. This dynamic resembles a friendship fracturing if your best friend started dating your ex; logical or not, it’s deeply personal and potentially damaging.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SO WHAT SHOULD YOU DO?**\",\"index\":677,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"First, keep in mind that the employees are either extremely good or you probably won’t want them in your company anyway. So, you will either be recruiting top-notch employees from your friend’s company or you will be adding mediocre people. Do not assume the people you are taking will not be missed.\",\"index\":678,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A good rule of thumb is my Reflexive Principle of Employee Raiding, which states, “If you would be shocked and horrified if Company X hired several of your employees, then you should not hire any of theirs.” The number of such companies should be small and may very well be zero.\",\"index\":679,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In order to avoid these sticky situations, many companies employ written or unwritten policies that name companies where it is not okay to hire without CEO (or senior executive) approval. With such a policy in place, you will be able to give your friend one last chance to save their employee or to object prior to you hiring them.\",\"index\":680,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"With that in mind, the best way to deal with these situations is openly and transparently. Once you become aware of the conflict between hiring the superstar employee and double-crossing your valued friend, you should get the issue onto the table by informing the employee that you have an important business relationship with his existing company and you will have to complete a reference check with the CEO prior to extending the offer. Let him know that if he does not want that to happen, then you will stop the process now and keep the process to date confidential. By speaking with your friend before making the hire, you will be able to better judge the relationship impact of hiring her employee. In addition, you may avoid making a bad hire, as often candidates who do well in interviews turn out to be bad employees.\",\"index\":681,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Remember, employees are either top-notch or not worth hiring. So, when recruiting from your friend's company, you're either getting excellent staff or mediocre ones. Don’t assume the people you take won't be missed. My Reflexive Principle of Employee Raiding states: \\\"If you would be shocked and horrified if Company X hired several of your employees, then you should not hire any of theirs.\\\" This principle applies to a small number of companies, possibly none. To avoid conflicts, many companies have written or unwritten policies requiring CEO approval before hiring from specific firms. This allows your friend a chance to save their employee or object. Handle these situations openly and transparently. Inform the candidate about your business relationship with their current employer and that a reference check with the CEO is necessary before extending an offer. If the candidate objects, stop the process and keep it confidential. Speaking with your friend can help assess the impact on your relationship and avoid a potentially bad hire.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**CLOSING THOUGHTS**\",\"index\":682,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the classic movie *The Good, the Bad and the Ugly*, Clint Eastwood “The Good” and Eli Wallach “The Ugly” are partners in crime. Wallach, a known criminal, has a bounty on his head and the two of them run a scam to collect the reward money. Eastwood turns Wallach in and collects the reward. Then Wallach is sentenced to death by hanging. As Wallach sits on a horse, hands tied behind his back and about to be hanged with a rope around his neck, Eastwood shoots the rope from a distance and frees Wallach and they split the reward money. This scheme works brilliantly, until one day Eastwood frees Wallach but informs Wallach: “I don’t think you’ll ever be worth more than three thousand dollars.” Wallach retorts, “What do you mean?” Eastwood informs him, “I mean, our partnership is untied. Oh no, not you. You remain tied. I’ll keep the money, and you can have the rope.” What follows is one of the great revenge pursuits in motion picture history.\",\"index\":683,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"So, when you tell your CEO friend that you don’t think she’ll ever be worth more than this employee, don’t expect to stay friends.\",\"index\":684,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":685,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":686,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In the classic movie *The Good, the Bad and the Ugly*, Clint Eastwood’s character, “The Good,” partners with Eli Wallach’s character, “The Ugly,” to scam bounty hunters. With a bounty on Wallach’s head, Eastwood turns him in, collects the reward, and then shoots the rope to free Wallach just before he’s hanged. This risky but profitable scheme continues until Eastwood informs Wallach that their partnership is over. He says, “I don’t think you’ll ever be worth more than three thousand dollars,” takes the money, and leaves Wallach tied up, setting the stage for an epic revenge chase. So, when you tell your CEO friend that you think she’ll never be worth more than an employee, don’t expect to stay friends.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When Mitchell, a talented engineer working for your friend Cathy, comes to your company for an interview and impresses everyone, it puts you, the CEO, in a delicate position. Even though you confirm he was already job hunting, hiring him might strain your friendship with Cathy. This scenario isn't just about losing one employee; it can cause a domino effect and create a perception of betrayal. To manage this complex dynamic, I advise following my Reflexive Principle of Employee Raiding: \\\"If you would be shocked and horrified if Company X hired several of your employees, then you should not hire any of theirs.\\\" Be transparent about the business relationship with the candidate, requiring CEO approval for hiring decisions from specific firms. Informing your friend can not only preserve professional and personal relationships but also gauge the candidate's impact, avoiding unnecessary conflict. Drawing a parallel to *The Good, the Bad and the Ugly*, if you imply that your friend isn't worth more than an employee, don't expect to maintain that friendship.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When Mitchell, a talented engineer working for your friend Cathy, comes to your company for an interview and impresses everyone, it puts you, the CEO, in a delicate position. Even though you confirm he was already job hunting, hiring him might strain your friendship with Cathy. This scenario isn't just about losing one employee; it can cause a domino effect and create a perception of betrayal. To manage this complex dynamic, I advise following my Reflexive Principle of Employee Raiding: \\\"If you would be shocked and horrified if Company X hired several of your employees, then you should not hire any of theirs.\\\" Be transparent about the business relationship with the candidate, requiring CEO approval for hiring decisions from specific firms. Informing your friend can not only preserve professional and personal relationships but also gauge the candidate's impact, avoiding unnecessary conflict. Drawing a parallel to *The Good, the Bad and the Ugly*, if you imply that your friend isn't worth more than an employee, don't expect to maintain that friendship.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[WHY IT’S HARD TO BRING BIG COMPANY EXECS INTO LITTLE COMPANIES]()**\",\"index\":687,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"So you’ve achieved product market fit and you are ready to start building the company. The board encourages you to bring in some “been there, done that” executives who will provide the right financial, sales, and marketing 