 thing to understand is that the job of a big company executive is very different from the job of a small company executive. When I was managing thousands of people at Hewlett-Packard after the sale of Opsware, there was an incredible number of incoming demands on my time. Everyone wanted a piece of me. Little companies wanted to partner with me or sell themselves to me, people in my organization needed approvals, other business units needed my help, customers wanted my attention, and so forth. As a result, I spent most of my time optimizing and tuning the existing business. Most of the work that I did was “incoming.” In fact, most skilled big company executives will tell you that if you have more than three new initiatives in a quarter, you are trying to do too much. As a result, big company executives tend to be interrupt-driven.\",\"index\":691,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In contrast, when you are a startup executive, nothing happens unless you make it happen. In the early days of a company, you have to take eight to ten new initiatives a day or the company will stand still. There is no inertia that’s putting the company in motion. Without massive input from you, the company will stay at rest.\",\"index\":692,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Fast-forward six months and frustration spreads as everyone wonders why the underperforming sales (or marketing, finance, or product) guy received a massive stock option package while those doing the heavy lifting received much less. Worse, the company's in trouble for missing targets because this highly-paid executive is idle. What went wrong? Understanding that a big company executive's job vastly differs from a small company executive's role is key. At Hewlett-Packard, managing thousands meant constant incoming demands, from partnerships and approvals to customer attention and internal needs, requiring me to optimize the business. Big company executives often focus on tuning existing operations and are interrupt-driven, typically handling no more than three new initiatives per quarter. Conversely, startup executives must drive action; with no existing momentum, you need to launch eight to ten new initiatives daily to avoid stagnation, as nothing moves without your massive input.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SO WHAT HAPPENS?**\",\"index\":693,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Once you hire one of these big company executives, there are two dangerous mismatches that you will face:\",\"index\":694,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**1.** **Rhythm mismatch** Your executive has been conditioned to wait for the emails to come in, wait for the phone to ring, and wait for the meetings to get scheduled. In your company, he will be waiting a long time. If your new executive waits (as per his training), your other employees will become suspicious. You’ll hear things like “What does that guy do all day long?” and “Why did he get so many options?”\",\"index\":695,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** **Skill set mismatch** Running a large organization requires very different skills than creating and building an organization. When you run a large organization, you tend to become very good at tasks such as complex decision-making, prioritization, organizational design, process improvement, and organizational communication. When you are building an organization, there is no organization to design, there are no processes to improve, and communicating with the organization is simple. On the other hand, you have to be very adept at running a high-quality hiring process, have terrific domain expertise (you are personally responsible for quality control), know how to create process from scratch, and be extremely creative about initiating new directions and tasks.\",\"index\":696,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**1.** **Rhythm mismatch** Your executive has been conditioned to wait for the emails to come in, wait for the phone to ring, and wait for the meetings to get scheduled. In your company, he will be waiting a long time. If your new executive waits (as per his training), your other employees will become suspicious. You’ll hear things like “What does that guy do all day long?” and “Why did he get so many options?” \\n\\n **2.** **Skill set mismatch** Running a large organization requires very different skills than creating and building an organization. When you run a large organization, you tend to become very good at tasks such as complex decision-making, prioritization, organizational design, process improvement, and organizational communication. When you are building an organization, there is no organization to design, there are no processes to improve, and communicating with the organization is simple. On the other hand, you have to be very adept at running a high-quality hiring process, have terrific domain expertise (you are personally responsible for quality control), know how to create process from scratch, and be extremely creative about initiating new directions and tasks.\"}],\"summary\":\"When you hire big company executives, you'll face two critical mismatches: rhythm and skill set. First, there's a rhythm mismatch; accustomed to a slower, more reactive pace involving waiting for emails, calls, and scheduled meetings, they may find themselves idle in your fast-paced company, raising suspicions among existing employees. Second, there's a skill set mismatch; while large organization leaders excel in complex decision-making, prioritization, and process improvement, building a company from scratch requires skills like high-quality hiring, profound domain expertise, and the creativity to initiate new directions and tasks—skills they often lack.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**HOW CAN YOU STOP THINGS FROM GOING HORRIBLY WRONG?**\",\"index\":697,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There are two key steps to avoiding disaster:\",\"index\":698,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**1.** Screen for devastating mismatches in the interview process.\",\"index\":699,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Take integration as seriously as interviewing.\",\"index\":700,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**1.** Screen for devastating mismatches in the interview process. \\n\\n **2.** Take integration as seriously as interviewing.\"}],\"summary\":\"To avoid disaster, be diligent in two crucial steps: first, during the interview process, screen meticulously for any potential devastating mismatches; second, treat the integration process with the same level of seriousness as the interview itself.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SCREEN FOR MISMATCHES**\",\"index\":701,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"How do you tell if the rhythm mismatch or the skill set mismatch will be too much to overcome? Here are some interview questions that I found very helpful:\",\"index\":702,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"How do you tell if the rhythm mismatch or the skill set mismatch will be too much to overcome? Here are some interview questions that I found very helpful:\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**What will you do in your first month on the job?**\",\"index\":703,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Beware of answers that overemphasize learning. This may indicate that the candidate thinks there is more to learn about your organization than there actually is. More specifically, he may think that your organization is as complex as his current organization.\",\"index\":704,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizab