th first principles. Bring them up to speed fast. If they don’t have any questions, consider firing them. If in thirty days you don’t feel that they are coming up to speed, definitely fire them.\\n\\n* *Put them in the mix.* Make sure that they initiate contact and interaction with their peers and other key people in the organization. Give them a list of people they need to know and learn from. Once they’ve done that, require a report from them on what they learned from each person.\",\"index\":715,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Integration is the most critical step when onboarding a new executive, necessitating a substantial investment of time. Here are key strategies to ensure successful integration: \\n\\n- *Force them to create:* Assign monthly, weekly, and even daily objectives to ensure immediate productivity. The rest of the company will be observing, and this proactive engagement is crucial to their assimilation.\\n- *Ensure they “get it”:* Executives must thoroughly understand the product, technology, customers, and market. Schedule daily meetings where they must bring questions about anything unclear and answer those questions in depth, starting from first principles. If they lack questions or fail to grasp the essentials within thirty days, consider letting them go.\\n- *Put them in the mix:* Encourage them to initiate interactions with peers and key individuals in the organization. Provide a list of people they need to learn from and require a report on their learnings from each person.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FINAL THOUGHTS**\",\"index\":716,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Nothing will accelerate your company’s development like hiring someone who has experience building a very similar company at larger scale. However, doing so can be fraught with peril. Make sure to pay attention to the important leading indicators of success and failure.\",\"index\":717,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":718,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":719,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Nothing accelerates your company’s growth like hiring someone with experience building a similar, larger-scale business. However, this can be perilous. Pay close attention to the crucial early signs of both success and failure.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Fast-forward six months and frustration arises as everyone questions why the underperforming executive with a large stock option package isn’t contributing, while hard-working employees receive less. The company falters, missing targets due to this idle, highly-paid executive. What went wrong? The crux lies in recognizing that big company executives operate vastly differently from those in startups. At Hewlett-Packard, managing thousands meant juggling numerous incoming demands and optimizing operations, typically handling only a few new initiatives quarterly. In contrast, startup executives must drive constant action with multiple daily initiatives to maintain momentum. Hiring big company executives creates two mismatches: rhythm and skill set. They’re used to a slower pace and reactive interruptions, making them idle in a fast-paced startup. Moreover, their skills in complex decision-making and process improvement don’t translate well to the high-quality hiring, domain expertise, and creativity needed in a startup. To avoid disaster, meticulously screen for potential mismatches and treat the integration process as seriously as the interview. Be wary of candidates overly focused on learning, reliant on interrupts, or driven by equity. Seek those proposing numerous initiatives and self-aware of differences between past experiences and current needs. Integration is key: force them to create with structured objectives, ensure they thoroughly understand the business, and encourage proactive interactions. T