le\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"The biggest difference between being a great functional manager and being a great general manager—and particularly a great CEO—is that as a general manager, you must hire and manage people who are far more competent at their jobs than you would be at their jobs. In fact, often you will have to hire and manage people to do jobs that you have never done. How many CEOs have been head of HR, engineering, sales, marketing, finance, and legal? Probably none.\",\"index\":721,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"So, with no experience, how do you hire someone good?\",\"index\":722,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The key difference between an outstanding functional manager and an exceptional general manager or CEO lies in the ability to hire and manage individuals who are far more skilled at their specific roles than you could ever be. As a general manager or CEO, you'll often need to hire experts for positions you've never personally worked in, such as HR, engineering, sales, marketing, finance, or legal. With no direct experience in these fields, the challenge becomes finding and managing top talent effectively. How do you hire someone good in such a situation?\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 1: KNOW WHAT YOU WANT**\",\"index\":723,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Step 1 is definitely the most important step in the process and also the one that gets skipped most often. As the great self-help coach Tony Robbins says, “If you don’t know what you want, the chances that you’ll get it are extremely low.” If you have never done the job, how do you know what to want?\",\"index\":724,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"First, you must realize how ignorant you are and resist the temptation to educate yourself simply by interviewing candidates. While the interview process can be highly educational, using that as the sole information source is dangerous. Doing so will make you susceptible to the following traps:\",\"index\":725,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* **Hiring on look and feel** It may seem silly to think that anyone would hire an executive based on the way they look and sound in an interview, but in my experience, look and feel are the top criteria for most executive searches. When you combine a CEO who doesn’t know what she wants and a board of directors that hasn’t thought much about the hire, what do you think the criteria will be?\\n\\n* **Looking for someone out of central casting** If I had followed this path, I would never have hired Mark Cranney and you probably would not be reading this now. This wrongheaded approach is the moral equivalent of looking for the Platonic ideal for a head of sales. You imagine what the perfect sales executive might be like, and then you attempt to match real-world candidates to your model. This is a bad idea for several reasons. First, you are not hiring an abstract executive to work at an arbitrary company. You must hire the right person for your company at this particular point in time. The head of sales at Oracle in 2010 would likely have failed in 1989. The VP of engineering at Apple might be exactly the wrong choice for Foursquare. The details and the specifics matter. Second, your imaginary model is almost certainly wrong. What is your basis for creating this model? Finally, it will be incredibly difficult to educate an interview team on such an abstract set of criteria. As a result, everybody will be looking for something different.\\n\\n* **Valuing lack of weakness rather than strength** The more experience you have, the more you realize that there is something seriously wrong with every employee in your company (including you). Nobody is perfect.\",\"index\":726,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The very best way to know what you want is to act in the role. Not just in title, but in real action. In my career, I’ve been acting VP of HR, CFO, and VP of sales. Often CEOs resist acting in functional roles, because they worry that they lack the appropriate knowledge. This worry is precisely why you should act—to get the appropriate knowledge. Indeed, acting is really the only way to get all the knowledge that you need to make the hire, because you are looking for the right executive for your company today, not a generic executive.\",\"index\":727,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In addition to acting in the role, it helps greatly to bring in domain experts. If you know a great head of sales, interview them first and learn what they think made them great. Figure out which of those strengths most directly match the needs of your company. If possible, include the domain expert in the interview process. However, be aware that the domain expert only has part of the knowledge necessary to make the hire. Specifically, she has very little knowledge of your company, how it works, and what its needs are. Therefore, you cannot defer the decision to the domain expert.\",\"index\":728,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Finally, be clear in your own mind about your expectations for this person upon joining your company. What will this person do in the first thirty days? What do you expect their motivation to be for joining? Do you want them to build a large organization right away or hire only one or two people over the next year?\",\"index\":729,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Step 1 is the most crucial yet often neglected part of the hiring process. As Tony Robbins says, “If you don’t know what you want, the chances that you’ll get it are extremely low.” It's essential to acknowledge your ignorance and avoid relying solely on candidate interviews for education, which can lead to pitfalls like hiring based on look and feel, or searching for someone out of central casting. These approaches are flawed because they ignore the specific needs of your company at this moment and rely on inaccurate, abstract criteria. Instead, the best way to determine what you want is to act in the role yourself, gaining hands-on experience and relevant knowledge. Additionally, consulting domain experts can offer valuable insights, but remember they don’t possess detailed knowledge about your company’s specific needs. Lastly, be explicit about your expectations for the new hire's initial contributions and their motivations for joining your company.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 2. RUN A PROCESS THAT FIGURES OUT THE RIGHT MATCH**\",\"index\":730,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"In order to find the right executive, you must now take the knowledge that you have gathered and translate it into a process that yields the right candidate. Here is the process that I like to use.\",\"index\":731,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In order to find the right executive, you must now take the knowledge that you have gathered and translate it into a process that yields the right candidate. Here is the process that I like to use.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Write down the strengths you want and the weaknesses that you are willing to tolerate.**\",\"index\":732,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In order to ensure completeness, I find it useful to include criteria from the following subdivisions when hiring executives:\",\"index\":733,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Will the executive be world-class at running the function?\\n\\n* Is the executive outstanding operationally?\\n\\n* Will the executive make a major contribution to the strategic direction of the company? This is the “are they smart enough?” criterion.\\n\\n* Will the executive be an effective member of the team? *Effective* is the key word. It’s possible for an executive to be well liked and totally ineffective with respect to the other members of the team. It’s also possible for an executive to be highly effective and profoundly influential while being totally despised. The latter is far better.\",\"index\":734,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"These functions do not carry equal weight for all positions. Make sure that you balance them appropriately. Generally, operational excellence is far more important for a VP of engineering or a VP of sales than for a VP of marketing or a CFO.\",\"index\":735,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When hiring executives, it's crucial to assess candidates based on four subdivisions: their ability to excel at running their function, their operational excellence, their potential to contribute significantly to the company's strategic direction, and their effectiveness as a team member. Effectiveness matters more than likability; an influential executive who isn't well-liked can be more valuable than a well-liked but ineffective one. These criteria need to be balanced appropriately, as operational excellence is generally more critical for roles like VP of engineering or VP of sales compared to a VP of marketing or a CFO.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Develop questions that test for the criteria (see the appendix).**\",\"index\":736,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"This effort is important even if you never ask the candidate any of the pre-prepared questions. By writing down questions that test for what you want, you will get to a level of specificity that will be extremely difficult to achieve otherwise. (See the appendix for an example of questions that I wrote for running the enterprise sales function and operational excellence.) Assemble an appropriate interview team and conduct the interviews.\",\"index\":737,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"This effort is important even if you never ask the candidate any of the pre-prepared questions. By writing down questions that test for what you want, you will get to a level of specificity that will be extremely difficult to achieve otherwise. (See the appendix for an example of questions that I wrote for running the enterprise sales function and operational excellence.) Assemble an appropriate interview team and conduct the interviews.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Assemble the interview team.**\",\"index\":738,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In assembling the team, you should keep two questions in mind:\",\"index\":739,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** Who will best help you figure out whether the candidate meets the criteria? These may be internal or external people. They can be board members, other executives, or just experts.\",\"index\":740,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Who do you need to support the decision once the executive is on board? This group is just as important as the first. No matter how great an executive is, they will have trouble succeeding if the people around them sabotage everything they do. The best way to avoid that is to understand any potential issues before the person is hired.\",\"index\":741,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Clearly, some people will be in both groups one and two. The opinions of both groups will be very important: Group one will help you determine the best candidate and group two will help you gauge how easily each candidate will integrate into your company. Generally, it’s best to have group two interview finalist candidates only.\",\"index\":742,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Next, assign questions to interviewers based on their talents. Specifically, make sure that the interviewer who asks the questions deeply understands what a good answer will sound like.\",\"index\":743,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As you conduct the interviews, be sure to discuss each interview with the interviewer. Use this time to drive to a common understanding of the criteria, so that you will get the best information possible.\",\"index\":744,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When assembling a hiring team, consider two critical questions: Who will best help determine if the candidate meets the criteria, and who will support the decision once the executive is hired? These could be internal or external people such as board members, other executives, or experts. Group one helps evaluate candidates, while group two ensures smooth integration and avoids internal sabotage. Some individuals will fall into both groups. Group one's insights help select the best candidate, and group two gauges how well each candidate will integrate with the company, usually interviewing only finalists. Assign interview questions to the most qualified interviewers who can discern good answers. After each interview, discuss the findings with the interviewer to align on the criteria and gather the best information possible.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Backdoor and front-door references.**\",\"index\":745,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For the final candidates, it’s critically important that the CEO conduct the reference checks herself. The references need to be checked against the same hiring criteria that you tested for during the interview process. Backdoor reference checks (checks from people who know the candidate, but were not referred by the candidate) can be an extremely useful way to get an unbiased view. However, do not discount the front-door references. While they clearly have committed to giving a positive reference (or they wouldn’t be on the list), you are not looking for positive or negative with them. You are looking for fit with your criteria. Often, the front-door references will know the candidate best and will be quite helpful in this respect.\",\"index\":746,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"For the final candidates, it’s critically important that the CEO conduct the reference checks herself. The references need to be checked against the same hiring criteria that you tested for during the interview process. Backdoor reference checks (checks from people who know the candidate, but were not referred by the candidate) can be an extremely useful way to get an unbiased view. However, do not discount the front-door references. While they clearly have committed to giving a positive reference (or they wouldn’t be on the list), you are not looking for positive or negative with them. You are looking for fit with your criteria. Often, the front-door references will know the candidate best and will be quite helpful in this respect.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When hiring executives, evaluate candidates based on their ability to excel at their function, operational excellence, strategic contribution potential, and team effectiveness. Effectiveness outweighs likability; a less likable yet influential executive is more valuable than a liked but ineffective one. Tailor these criteria to the specific role, prioritizing operational excellence more in roles like VP of engineering or sales. Writing out specific questions helps achieve necessary specificity even if they're not directly asked. Assemble a hiring team by considering who can best evaluate the candidate and who will support the decision post-hiring, involving internal or external stakeholders. The team should split into evaluators and integration supporters, assigning the best-suited interviewers to specific questions and discussing post-interview insights. For finalists, the CEO must personally conduct reference checks, using both backdoor and front-door references to assess the candidate against hiring criteria, focusing on fit rather than merely positive or negative feedback.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When hiring executives, evaluate candidates based on their ability to excel at their function, operational excellence, strategic contribution potential, and team effectiveness. Effectiveness outweighs likability; a less likable yet influential executive is more valuable than a liked but ineffective one. Tailor these criteria to the specific role, prioritizing operational excellence more in roles like VP of engineering or sales. Writing out specific questions helps achieve necessary specificity even if they're not directly asked. Assemble a hiring team by considering who can best evaluate the candidate and who will support the decision post-hiring, involving internal or external stakeholders. The team should split into evaluators and integration supporters, assigning the best-suited interviewers to specific questions and discussing post-interview insights. For finalists, the CEO must personally conduct reference checks, using both backdoor and front-door references to assess the candidate against hiring criteria, focusing on fit rather than merely positive or negative feedback.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**STEP 3: MAKE A LONELY DECISION**\",\"index\":747,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Despite many people being involved in the process, the ultimate decision should be made solo. Only the CEO has comprehensive knowledge of the criteria, the rationale for the criteria, all of the feedback from interviewers and references, and the relative importance of the various stakeholders. Consensus decisions about executives almost always sway the process away from strength and toward lack of weakness. It’s a lonely job, but somebody has to do it.\",\"index\":748,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":749,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":750,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"While many are part of the process, the final decision must be made by the CEO alone. As the only person fully aware of the criteria, the reasoning behind them, the feedback from interviewers and references, and the varying importance of stakeholders, the CEO is uniquely positioned to decide. Consensus decisions often dilute strong candidates in favor of ones with fewer weaknesses. It’s a solitary task, but it’s essential for ensuring the right choice.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Step 1 is the most crucial yet often neglected part of the hiring process. As Tony Robbins states, “If you don’t know what you want, the chances that you’ll get it are extremely low.” It's essential to avoid relying solely on candidate interviews for education and to act in the role yourself to gain hands-on experience and relevant knowledge. Consulting domain experts can offer valuable insights, but they might not be fully aware of your company's specific needs. Be explicit about your expectations for the new hire's initial contributions and their motivations for joining your team. When hiring executives, evaluate candidates based on their function, operational excellence, strategic potential, and team effectiveness, prioritizing effectiveness over likability. Tailor these criteria to the specific role, write out specific questions, and assemble a hiring team with evaluators and integration supporters. For finalists, the CEO must personally conduct reference checks, using both backdoor and front-door references to assess fit. While many contribute to the process, the final hiring decision is solely the CEO's responsibility, as they are uniquely positioned to decide based on comprehensive criteria and stakeholder feedback.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Step 1 is the most crucial yet often neglected part of the hiring process. As Tony Robbins states, “If you don’t know what you want, the chances that you’ll get it are extremely low.” It's essential to avoid relying solely on candidate interviews for education and to act in the role yourself to gain hands-on experience and relevant knowledge. Consulting domain experts can offer valuable insights, but they might not be fully aware of your company's specific needs. Be explicit about your expectations for the new hire's initial contributions and their motivations for joining your team. When hiring executives, evaluate candidates based on their function, operational excellence, strategic potential, and team effectiveness, prioritizing effectiveness over likability. Tailor these criteria to the specific role, write out specific questions, and assemble a hiring team with evaluators and integration supporters. For finalists, the CEO must personally conduct reference checks, using both backdoor and front-door references to assess fit. While many contribute to the process, the final hiring decision is solely the CEO's responsibility, as they are uniquely positioned to decide based on comprehensive criteria and stakeholder feedback.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[WHEN EMPLOYEES MISINTERPRET MANAGERS]()**\",\"index\":751,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Early on at Loudcloud, many people would do crazy things backed up by “Ben said.” Often I didn’t say any of it, but I definitely didn’t say it in the way they used it. The management principles I share here are connected to many of those experiences.\",\"index\":752,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I ran Opsware, we had the nonlinear quarter problem also known affectionately as the hockey stick. The hockey stick refers to the shape of the revenue graph over the course of a quarter. Our hockey stick was so bad that one quarter, we booked 90 percent of our new bookings on the last day of the quarter. Sales patterns like this make it difficult to plan the business and are particularly harrowing when you are, as we were, a public company.\",\"index\":753,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Naturally, I was determined to straighten out the hockey stick and bring some sanity to the business. I designed an incentive for salespeople to close deals in the first two months of the quarter by issuing bonuses for deals in those months. As a result, the next quarter became slightly more linear, and slightly smaller than anticipated—deals just moved from the third month to the first two of the following quarter.\",\"index\":754,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I ran a large engineering group at Netscape, I measured one of our engineering products on schedule, quality, and features. The team shipped a product with all the required features, on time and with very few bugs. Unfortunately, the product was mediocre, because none of the features were that great.\",\"index\":755,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I was at HP, we ran all the businesses by the numbers with extremely strict revenue and margin targets. Some divisions made their numbers, but did so by underfunding R&D. They dramatically weakened their long-term competitive position and set themselves up for future disaster.\",\"index\":756,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In all three cases, managers got what we asked for, but not what we wanted. How did this happen? Let’s take a look.\",\"index\":757,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Early at Loudcloud, people often misinterpreted or exaggerated my words, leading to some wild actions attributed to \\\"Ben said.\\\" At Opsware, we faced a severe nonlinear revenue issue, with 90% of bookings happening on the last day of the quarter, complicating business planning. To address this, I incentivized sales closures earlier in the quarter, leading to slightly more linear revenue but shifting deals rather than increasing them. At Netscape, my engineering team delivered a product with required features, on time, and with few bugs, but it was still mediocre because the features weren't impressive. At HP, strict adherence to revenue and margin targets led divisions to underfund R&D, weakening their long-term competitiveness. In each situation, managers achieved the targets but missed the underlying goals. How did these misalignments happen? Let's explore.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FLATTENING OUT THE HOCKEY STICK: THE WRONG GOAL**\",\"index\":758,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In retrospect, I should never have asked the team to flatten the quarters. If that is what I wanted, I had to be willing to—at least temporarily—accept smaller quarters. We had a fixed number of salespeople who were maximizing the size of each quarter. In order to deliver linear quarters, they had to modify their behavior and adjust their priorities. Unfortunately, I liked the old priority of maximizing revenue better.\",\"index\":759,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Given the situation, I was actually pretty lucky. Sun Tzu, in his classic work *The Art of War*, warns that giving the team a task that it cannot possibly perform is called crippling the army. In my case, I did not cripple the team, but I screwed up my priorities. The right thing to do would have been to make the hard decision up front, about what was more important, maximizing each quarter or increasing predictability. The instruction only made sense if the answer was the second one.\",\"index\":760,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In retrospect, I shouldn't have asked the team to flatten the quarters unless I was prepared to accept smaller quarters temporarily. Our fixed number of salespeople were maximizing the size of each quarter, but to achieve linear quarters, they needed to adjust their behavior and priorities. Unfortunately, I preferred the old approach of maximizing revenue. Despite this, I was relatively lucky—Sun Tzu's *The Art of War* warns that giving the team an impossible task is crippling, but I merely messed up my priorities. The right decision would have been to choose upfront between maximizing each quarter or increasing predictability; my instruction only made sense if the latter were more important.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FOCUSING TOO MUCH ON THE NUMBERS**\",\"index\":761,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the second example, I managed the team to a set of numbers that did not fully capture what I wanted. I wanted a great product that customers would love with high quality and on time—in that order.\",\"index\":762,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Unfortunately, the metrics that I set did not capture those priorities. At a basic level, metrics are incentives. By measuring quality, features, and schedule and discussing them at every staff meeting, my people focused intensely on those metrics to the exclusion of other goals. The metrics did not describe the real goals and I distracted the team as a result.\",\"index\":763,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Interestingly, I see this same problem play out in many consumer Internet startups. I often see teams that maniacally focus on their metrics around customer acquisition and retention. This usually works well for customer acquisition, but not so well for retention. Why?\",\"index\":764,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For many products, metrics often describe the customer acquisition goal in enough detail to provide sufficient management guidance. In contrast, the metrics for customer retention do not provide enough color to be a complete management tool. As a result, many young companies overemphasize retention metrics and do not spend enough time going deep enough on the actual user experience. This generally results in a frantic numbers chase that does not end in a great product. It’s important to supplement a great product vision with a strong discipline around the metrics, but if you substitute metrics for product vision, you will not get what you want.\",\"index\":765,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In my experience, managing a team to meet certain metrics did not fully capture my real goals of a high-quality, customer-loved, on-time product. Metrics are incentives, and by focusing solely on measuring quality, features, and schedule, the team became distracted from the true objectives. This issue is common in consumer Internet startups, where teams tend to maniacally focus on customer acquisition and retention metrics. While metrics often adequately describe customer acquisition goals, they fall short for customer retention, lacking depth in managing the user experience. Consequently, this leads to an overemphasis on metrics, resulting in a frantic numbers chase rather than the development of a great product. Balancing a strong product vision with disciplined metrics is crucial; substituting one for the other won't yield the desired outcomes.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**MANAGING STRICTLY BY NUMBERS IS LIKE PAINTING BY NUMBERS**\",\"index\":766,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Some things that you want to encourage will be quantifiable, and some will not. If you report on the quantitative goals and ignore the qualitative ones, you won’t get the qualitative goals, which may be the most important ones. Management purely by numbers is sort of like painting by numbers—it’s strictly for amateurs.\",\"index\":767,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At HP, the company wanted high earnings now and in the future. By focusing entirely on the numbers, HP got them now by sacrificing the future.\",\"index\":768,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Note that there were many numbers as well as more qualitative goals that would have helped:\",\"index\":769,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Was our competitive win rate increasing or declining?\\n\\n* Was customer satisfaction rising or falling?\\n\\n* What did our own engineers think of the products?\",\"index\":770,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"By managing the organization as though it were a black box, some divisions at HP optimized the present at the expense of their downstream competitiveness. The company rewarded managers for achieving short-term objectives in a manner that was bad for the company. It would have been better to take into account the white box. The white box goes beyond the numbers and gets into how the organization produced the numbers. It penalizes managers who sacrifice the future for the short term and rewards those who invest in the future even if that investment cannot be easily measured.\",\"index\":771,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Some goals you want to achieve will be quantifiable while others won't. If you only report on quantitative goals and overlook qualitative ones, you risk missing out on potentially crucial aims. Managing purely by numbers is like painting by numbers—specific to beginners. At HP, an exclusive focus on high current earnings resulted in sacrificing future prospects. Qualitative goals such as improving competitive win rates, boosting customer satisfaction, and gauging engineers' opinions about products were neglected. This led to some divisions optimizing short-term gains at the expense of future competitiveness. Instead of rewarding managers strictly on short-term results, HP needed to adopt a \\\"white box\\\" approach, considering how numbers were achieved and favoring those making long-term investments, even if these are harder to measure.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**CLOSING THOUGHT**\",\"index\":772,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It is easy to see that there are many ways for leaders to be misinterpreted. To get things right, you must recognize that anything you measure automatically creates a set of employee behaviors. Once you determine the result you want, you need to test the description of the result against the employee behaviors that the description will likely create. Otherwise, the side-effect behaviors may be worse than the situation you were trying to fix.\",\"index\":773,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":774,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":775,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Leadership often faces the challenge of misinterpretation. To navigate this, it's crucial to understand that whatever you measure influences employee behaviors. After identifying the desired outcome, you must test how your description of this result will shape employee actions. Without this step, the unintended behaviors could end up being more problematic than the original issue you aimed to address.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"In hindsight, I realize asking the team to flatten quarters without accepting temporary smaller ones was a mistake. Our salespeople maximized each quarter's size, but linear quarters required them to modify their behaviors and priorities, conflicting with my preference for maximum revenue. Although I avoided an impossible task as warned by Sun Tzu's *The Art of War*, I messed up my priorities. The correct choice was to decide between maximizing each quarter or ensuring predictability upfront. \\n\\nWhen managing the team, focusing solely on metrics did not align with my true goals of delivering a high-quality, loved, and timely product. Metrics can incentivize behavior, but in consumer Internet startups, this often leads to a frantic chase of numbers, distracting from the creation of great products. Balancing a robust product vision with disciplined metrics is essential, as focusing exclusively on quantitative goals neglects qualitative ones, missing key objectives. \\n\\nAt HP, an emphasis on high current earnings sacrificed future prospects, neglecting competitive win rates, customer satisfaction, and engineers' opinions. This focus on short-term gains compromised long-term competitiveness. Instead, HP should reward managers for long-term investments, even if harder to measure. Leaders must ensure measuring incentives aligns with desired outcomes and test these measurements to avoid unintended, problematic behaviors.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"In hindsight, I realize asking the team to flatten quarters without accepting temporary smaller ones was a mistake. Our salespeople maximized each quarter's size, but linear quarters required them to modify their behaviors and priorities, conflicting with my preference for maximum revenue. Although I avoided an impossible task as warned by Sun Tzu's *The Art of War*, I messed up my priorities. The correct choice was to decide between maximizing each quarter or ensuring predictability upfront. \\n\\nWhen managing the team, focusing solely on metrics did not align with my true goals of delivering a high-quality, loved, and timely product. Metrics can incentivize behavior, but in consumer Internet startups, this often leads to a frantic chase of numbers, distracting from the creation of great products. Balancing a robust product vision with disciplined metrics is essential, as focusing exclusively on quantitative goals neglects qualitative ones, missing key objectives. \\n\\nAt HP, an emphasis on high current earnings sacrificed future prospects, neglecting competitive win rates, customer satisfaction, and engineers' opinions. This focus on short-term gains compromised long-term competitiveness. Instead, HP should reward