ck process\",\"index\":782,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Like technical debt, management debt comes in too many different forms to elaborate entirely, but a few salient examples will help explain the concept. Here are three of the more popular types among startups: \\n\\n **1.** Putting two in the box \\n\\n **2.** Overcompensating a key employee, because she gets another job offer \\n\\n **3.** No performance management or employee feedback process\"}],\"summary\":\"Thanks to Ward Cunningham, the computer programmer who designed the first wiki, the metaphor \\\"technical debt\\\" is now well understood. Writing quick and dirty code can save time in the short term, but you'll eventually have to pay it back with interest. This trade-off can make sense, but ignoring it leads to serious trouble. Similarly, there's a parallel concept I'll call *management debt*. Management debt occurs when you make short-term management decisions that have costly, long-term consequences. While these trade-offs sometimes make sense, failing to account for them can lead to \\\"management bankruptcy.\\\" Like technical debt, it comes in many forms, but here are three common examples among startups: 1) Putting two people in the same role, 2) Overcompensating a critical employee due to a job offer, and 3) Lacking a performance management or employee feedback process.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**PUTTING TWO IN THE BOX**\",\"index\":783,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"What do you do when you have two outstanding employees who logically both fit in the same place on the organizational chart? Perhaps you have a world-class architect who is running engineering, but she does not have the experience to scale the organization to the next level. You also have an outstanding operational person who is not great technically. You want to keep both in the company, but you only have one position. So you get the bright idea to put “two in the box” and take on a little management debt. The short-term benefits are clear: you keep both employees, you don’t have to develop either because they will theoretically help each other develop, and you instantly close the skill set gap. Unfortunately, you will pay for those benefits with interest and at a very high rate.\",\"index\":784,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For starters, by doing this you will make every engineer’s job more difficult. If an engineer needs a decision made, which boss should she go to? If that boss decides, will the other boss be able to override it? If it’s a complex decision that requires a meeting, does she have to schedule both heads of engineering for the meeting? Who sets the direction for the organization? Will the direction actually get set if doing so requires a series of meetings?\",\"index\":785,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In addition, you have removed all accountability. If schedules slip, who is accountable? If engineering throughput becomes uncompetitive, who is responsible? If the operational head is responsible for the schedule slip and the technical head is responsible for throughput, what happens if the operational head thrashes the engineers to make the schedule and kills throughput? How would you know that she did that? The really expensive part about both of these things is that they tend to get worse over time. In the very short term you might mitigate their effects with extra meetings or by attempting to carve up the job in a clear way. However, as things get busy, those once-clear lines will fade and the organization will degenerate. Eventually, you’ll either make a lump-sum payment by making the hard decision and putting one in the box or your engineering organization will suck forever.\",\"index\":786,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When faced with two outstanding employees, both fitting the same spot on the organizational chart, putting \\\"two in the box\\\" might seem like a good short-term solution to keep both employees and close skill gaps. However, this approach quickly creates significant management debt. Engineers will struggle with decision-making, navigating conflicting directives, and scheduling meetings with both heads. Accountability issues arise, as it's unclear who is responsible for schedule slips or throughput problems. The initially manageable issues will, over time, deepen into inefficiencies and confusion, deteriorating the organization. Ultimately, to avoid ongoing chaos and inefficiency, a difficult decision must be made to place only one person in the position.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**OVERCOMPENSATING A KEY EMPLOYEE BECAUSE SHE GETS ANOTHER JOB OFFER**\",\"index\":787,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"An excellent engineer decides to leave the company because she gets a better offer. For various reasons, you were undercompensating her, but the offer from the other company pays more than any engineer in your company and the engineer in question is not your best engineer. Still, she is working on a critical project and you cannot afford to lose her. So you match the offer. You save the project, but you pile on the debt.\",\"index\":788,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Here’s how the payment will come due. You probably think that your counteroffer was confidential because you’d sworn her to secrecy. Let me explain why it was not. She has friends in the company. When she got the offer from the other company, she consulted with her friends. One of her best friends advised her to take the offer. When she decided to stay, she had to explain to him why she disregarded his advice or else lose personal credibility. So she told him and swore him to secrecy. He agreed to honor the secret but was incensed that she had to threaten to quit in order to get a proper raise. Furthermore, he was furious that you overcompensated her. So he told the story to a few of his friends, but kept her name confidential to preserve the secret. And now everyone in engineering knows that the best way to get a raise is to generate an offer from another company and then threaten to quit. It’s going to take a while to pay off that debt.\",\"index\":789,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"An excellent engineer left the company for a better offer, but you managed to retain her by matching the salary, even though she’s not your top engineer. This raised her compensation above anyone else in the company despite being previously underpaid. Believing the counteroffer to be confidential, you didn’t anticipate the consequences. The engineer consulted a friend about her original offer and later disclosed her reason for staying, swearing him to secrecy. However, he felt outraged by the situation and discreetly shared the story, sans her identity, with others. Now, everyone in engineering knows the best way to get a raise is to obtain an external offer and threaten to quit, creating a significant morale and financial issue for you to resolve over time.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**NO PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT OR EMPLOYEE FEEDBACK PROCESS**\",\"index\":790,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Your company now employs twenty-five people and you know that you should formalize the performance management process, but you don’t want to pay the price. You worry that doing so will make it feel like a “big company.” Moreover, you do not want your employees to be offended by the feedback, because you can’t afford to lose anyone right now. And people are happy, so why rock the boat? Why not take on a little management debt?\",\"index\":791,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"The first noticeable payments will be due when somebody performs below expectations:\",\"index\":792,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"CEO: “He was good when we hired him; what happened?”\",\"index\":793,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Manager: “He’s not doing the things that we need him to do.”\",\"index\":794,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"CEO: “Did we clearly tell him that?”\",\"index\":795,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Manager: “Maybe not clearly . . .”\",\"index\":796,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"The first noticeable payments will be due when somebody performs below expectations: \\n\\n CEO: “He was good when we hired him; what happened?” \\n\\n Manager: “He’s not doing the things that we need him to do.” \\n\\n CEO: “Did we clearly tell him that?” \\n\\n Manager: “Maybe not clearly . . .”\"},{\"content\":\"However, the larger payment will be a silent tax. Companies execute well when everybody is on the same page and everybody is constantly improving. In a vacuum of feedback, there is almost no chance that your company will perform optimally across either dimension. Directions with no corrections will seem fuzzy and obtuse. People rarely improve weakness they are unaware of. The ultimate price you will pay for not giving feedback: systematically crappy company performance.\",\"index\":797,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Your company has grown to 25 employees, and though you recognize the need for a formalized performance management process, you hesitate due to its potential costs and the fear it may make the environment feel too corporate. Additionally, you're concerned that the feedback might offend employees, risking turnover that you can't afford. However, neglecting this process is akin to taking on management debt, with consequences surfacing when someone underperforms and it’s realized that expectations were not clearly communicated. The more significant consequence is the silent tax, where the lack of feedback prevents optimal performance and continuous improvement. In an environment devoid of feedback, employees are unlikely to rectify unknown weaknesses, leading to subpar company performance overall.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**IN THE END**\",\"index\":798,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Every really good, really experienced CEO I know shares one important characteristic: They tend to opt for the hard answer to organizational issues. If faced with giving everyone the same bonus to make things easy or with sharply rewarding performance and ruffling many feathers, they’ll ruffle the feathers. If given the choice of cutting a popular project today, because it’s not in the long-term plans or you’re keeping it around for morale purposes and to appear consistent, they’ll cut it today. Why? Because they’ve paid the price of management debt, and they would rather not do that again.\",\"index\":799,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":800,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":801,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Every truly skilled and experienced CEO I know shares a key trait: they choose the hard answers to organizational challenges. When deciding between giving everyone the same bonus to keep things smooth or sharply rewarding performance and potentially upsetting others, they'll choose the latter. Faced with cutting a popular project today because it doesn't align with long-term plans or keeping it for morale and consistency, they'll cut it now. Why? Because they've experienced the costs of management debt and prefer to avoid that situation again.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When faced with two exceptional employees for the same position, placing \\\"two in the box\\\" might seem an attractive short-term fix to close skill gaps, but it quick