ings with compensation practices. Assess how quickly new hires become productive and understand their expectations, ensuring managers provide consistent, clear feedback and high-quality, timely performance reviews. Manage poor performers effectively while fostering a workplace where employees are excited, believe in the company’s mission, and stay engaged. Understand why employees quit and address factors leading to disengagement. To comprehensively understand the quality of your management team, hire an individual with world-class process design skills akin to a head of quality assurance, ensuring accurate measurement and control of management processes. This person should act as a diplomat, trusted to help improve the management team, only escalating issues to the CEO when necessary. They must possess deep industry knowledge, stay updated on compensation, benefits, and recruiting practices, and have the intellectual heft to be the CEO’s trusted adviser. They need the CEO's full backing to hold managers to high standards and an acute ability to perceive unspoken signs of declining management quality.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Achieving product/market fit is crucial for success, even for mismanaged companies, as a good company structure matters during inevitable problems and job satisfaction is key in tough times. My stern approach with an executive emphasized building a good company, as seen through my experience with Bill Campbell at GO Corporation, where former employees valued their experience despite financial failures. Proper training is essential for productivity, as Andy Grove stressed—it ensures clear expectations and skill development, preventing high attrition and inconsistent products. Avoid poaching from key relationships by following my Reflexive Principle of Employee Raiding, preserving respect and professionalism. Be wary of hiring big company executives for startups due to potential mismatches in rhythm and skill set, and ensure thorough integration to identify early success or failure. The hiring process should start with clear expectations, include CEO-led evaluations, and reference checks. Balance immediate goals with long-term vision to avoid metrics-driven distractions that compromise product quality and customer satisfaction, as HP’s short-term focus undermined future prospects. Align incentives with desired outcomes for sustainable success.\\n\\nWhen faced with two exceptional employees for the same position, avoid the \\\"two in the box\\\" approach as it creates management debt with unclear responsibility and decision-making inefficiencies. Counteroffers to retain mid-level engineers can harm morale and finances by setting a bad precedent. In small companies, a lack of formal performance management leads to underperformance and missed growth opportunities. Successful CEOs address management debt by rewarding performance, aligning projects, and conducting thorough, timely interviews. Attract talent with competitive benefits, salaries, and stock options, maintaining engagement through consistent feedback and performance reviews. Address poor performance decisively, understand why employees quit, and foster a mission-driven workplace. Consider hiring a skilled individual to design robust management processes, provide quality assurance, and advise the CEO while holding managers to high standards and detecting early signs of declining management quality.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Achieving product/market fit is crucial for success, even for mismanaged companies, as a good company structure matters during inevitable problems and job satisfaction is key in tough times. My stern approach with an executive emphasized building a good company, as seen through my experience with Bill Campbell at GO Corporation, where former employees valued their experience despite financial failures. Proper training is essential for productivity, as Andy Grove stressed—it ensures clear expectations and skill development, preventing high attrition and inconsistent products. Avoid poaching from key relationships by following my Reflexive Principle of Employee Raiding, preserving respect and professionalism. Be wary of hiring big company executives for startups due to potential mismatches in rhythm and skill set, and ensure thorough integration to identify early success or failure. The hiring process should start with clear expectations, include CEO-led evaluations, and reference checks. Balance immediate goals with long-term vision to avoid metrics-driven distractions that compromise product quality and customer satisfaction, as HP’s short-term focus undermined future prospects. Align incentives with desired outcomes for sustainable success.\\n\\nWhen faced with two exceptional employees for the same position, avoid the \\\"two in the box\\\" approach as it creates management debt with unclear responsibility and decision-making inefficiencies. Counteroffers to retain mid-level engineers can harm morale and finances by setting a bad precedent. In small companies, a lack of formal performance management leads to underperformance and missed growth opportunities. Successful CEOs address management debt by rewarding performance, aligning projects, and conducting thorough, timely interviews. Attract talent with competitive benefits, salaries, and stock options, maintaining engagement through consistent feedback and performance reviews. Address poor performance decisively, understand why employees quit, and foster a mission-driven workplace. Consider hiring a skilled individual to design robust management processes, provide quality assurance, and advise the CEO while holding managers to high standards and detecting early signs of declining management quality.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[— CHAPTER 6 —]()**\",\"index\":822,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**[CONCERNING THE GOING CONCERN]()**\",\"index\":823,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**[— CHAPTER 6 —]()** \\n\\n **[CONCERNING THE GOING CONCERN]()**\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“This ain’t for no fuck niggas\",\"index\":824,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you a real nigga then fuck with me.”\",\"index\":825,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**—TRINIDAD JAMES, “ALL GOLD EVERYTHING”**\",\"index\":826,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“This ain’t for no fuck niggas \\n\\n If you a real nigga then fuck with me.” \\n\\n **—TRINIDAD JAMES, “ALL GOLD EVERYTHING”**\"},{\"content\":\"**O**ne day in a staff meeting in the Loudcloud/Opsware days, someone brought up an issue that had been bothering him for some time. “This place is entirely too profane. It’s making many of the employees uncomfortable.” Others chimed in: “It makes the environment unprofessional. We need to put a stop to it.” Although the complaints were abstract, they were clearly directed at me since I was the biggest abuser of profanity in the company and perhaps in the industry. In those days, I directed the team with such urgency that it was rare for me to say more than a few sentences without an expletive injected somewhere.\",\"index\":827,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Part of it was intentional. I only had so much time with each employee and it was critically important that I be crystal clear in those moments. Nothing makes things clear like a few choice curse words. “That is not the priority” is radically weaker than “That is not the fucking priority.” When the CEO drops the F-bomb, it gets repeated. And that’s good if you want your message to spread throughout the company. (On the other hand, it’s extremely bad if you don’t want your employees talking like a bunch of gangsta rappers.) But part of it was also unintentional. At this point, I could barely control myself. This was not an easy company to run, and I’d developed CEO Tourette’s syndrome—the profanity was involuntary.\",\"index\":828,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Since the complaints seemed broad and deep, I had to take them seriously. I thought hard about it that night and considered the following.\",\"index\":829,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* In the technology business, some employees would be comfortable with profanity while others would not.\\n\\n* If we outlawed profanity, then some employees who used it would not come to work for us or quit once they got there because we would seem old-fashioned and prudish.\\n\\n* If we kept profanity, some people might leave.\\n\\n* My judgment was biased, because I was the main offender.\",\"index\":830,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After much consideration, I realized that the best technology companies of the day, Intel and Microsoft, were known to be highly profane places, so we’d be off culture with them and the rest of the modern industry if we stopped profanity. Obviously, that didn’t mean that we had to encourage it, but prohibiting it seemed both unrealistic and counterproductive. Attracting the very best engineers meant recruiting from highly profane environments. The choice was between optimizing for top talent or clean culture. Easy decision.\",\"index\":831,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I decided to keep the cursing, but I also needed to make a statement. People had complained and had run this issue all the way up the organization, and they deserved an explanation. Explaining things would be tricky, because profanity did not work in all contexts. We certainly could not tolerate profanity used to intimidate or sexually harass employees, so I needed to make the distinction clear. Approving profanity only in certain contexts was a tricky message to craft.\",\"index\":832,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"That night I watched a disturbing movie from the late 1970s called *Short Eyes*, which told the graphic story of a child molester who went to prison and confronted the one clear prison ethic: Child molesters must die. One of the characters in the movie was a young man referred to by the other inmates as “Cupcakes.”\",\"index\":833,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Hard to believe, but watching that movie, I found my solution.\",\"index\":834,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The next day, I gave the following speech at the all-company meeting:\",\"index\":835,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"“It has come to my attention that many people are uncomfortable with the amount of profanity that we use. Being the number-one abuser, these complaints have caused me to reflect on my own behavior as well as the company as a whole. As I see it, we have two choices: (a) we can ban profanity or (b) we can accept profanity. Anything in between is very unlikely to work. ‘Minimal profanity’ cannot be enforced. I’ve said before that we cannot win unless we attract the very best people in the world. In the technology industry, almost everybody comes from a culture that allows profanity. Therefore, banning profanity will likely limit our talent pool more than accepting profanity. As a result, we will allow profanity. However, this does not mean that you can use profanity to intimidate, sexually harass people, or do other bad things. In this way, profanity is no different from other language. For example, consider the word ‘cupcakes.’ It’s fine for me to say to Shannon, ‘Those cupcakes you baked look delicious.’ But it is not okay for me to say to Anthony, ‘Hey, Cupcakes, you look mighty fine in them jeans.’ ”\",\"index\":836,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"And that was all I said about that.\",\"index\":837,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After that day, I never heard another complaint about profanity and I don’t think we lost anybody because of the policy. Sometimes an organization doesn’t need a solution; it just needs clarity. Once I made it clear that cursing was okay—so long as it wasn’t used to intimidate or harass—nobody had a problem with it anymore. At least as far as I knew. Bottom line, the results of the policy were good: a comfortable work environment, low attrition, and no complaining. Sometimes the right policy is the one that the CEO can follow.\",\"index\":838,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":839,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**A**s a company grows, it will change. No matter how well you set your culture, keep your spirit, or slow-roll your growth, your company won’t be the same when it’s one thousand people as it was when it was ten people. But that doesn’t mean that it can’t be a good company when it reaches 1,000, 10,000, or even 100,000 employees. It will just be different. Making it good at scale means admitting that it must be different and embracing the changes that you’ll need to make to keep things from falling apart. This chapter explains some of the changes that you will need to make.\",\"index\":840,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":841,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":842,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"During the Loudcloud/Opsware days, concerns arose about excessive profanity in the workplace, particularly associated with me, and there was discomfort among employees about its use. Profanity served as a tool to convey urgency and clarity, but it also seemed unprofessional to some. Balancing the need to attract talent from profane environments like Intel and Microsoft with maintaining a professional atmosphere was a challenge. Reflecting on this during a company meeting, I concluded that while banning profanity might limit our talent pool, allowing it with boundaries would be better. I clarified that profanity would be allowed as long as it wasn't used to intimidate or harass, using examples like complimenting someone's actual cupcakes versus inappropriately calling someone 'Cupcakes.' This clear policy eliminated complaints and maintained a comfortable and productive work environment without high attrition. Successful scaling of a company involves understanding and implementing changes that align with both the industry culture and internal needs, ensuring the company remains a good place to work even as it grows.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[HOW TO MINIMIZE POLITICS IN YOUR COMPANY]()**\",\"index\":843,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"In all my years in business, I have yet to hear someone say, “I love corporate politics.” On the other hand, I meet plenty of people who complain bitterly about corporate politics—sometimes even in the companies they run. So, if nobody loves politics, why all the politics?\",\"index\":844,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Political behavior almost always starts with the CEO. Now you may be thinking, “I hate politics, I’m not political, but my organization is very political. I clearly didn’t cause this.” Sadly, you needn’t be political to create extreme political behavior in your organization. In fact, it’s often the least political CEOs who run the most ferociously political organizations. Apolitical CEOs frequently—and accidentally—encourage intense political behavior.\",\"index\":845,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"What do I mean by politics? I mean people advancing their careers or agendas by means other than merit and contribution. There may be other types of politics, but politics of this form seem to be the ones that really bother people.\",\"index\":846,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In all my years in business, I've never heard anyone say, \\\"I love corporate politics.\\\" Yet, many people—often even those leading the companies—bitterly complain about them. If nobody loves politics, why do they persist? Political behavior almost always starts with the CEO. You might think, \\\"I hate politics and I'm not political, but my organization is very political. I didn't cause this.\\\" Unfortunately, you don't have to be political to create a politically charged environment. In fact, it’s often the least political CEOs who inadvertently foster the most intense political behavior. By politics, I refer to people advancing their careers or agendas through means other than merit and contribution—this is the form of politics that truly bothers people.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**HOW IT HAPPENS**\",\"index\":847,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A CEO creates politics by encouraging and sometimes incentivizing political behavior—often unintentionally. As a very simple example, let’s consider executive compensation. When you are CEO, senior employees will come to you from time to time and ask for an increase in compensation. They may suggest that you are paying them far less than their current market value. They may even have a competitive offer in hand. Faced with this confrontation, if the request is reasonable, you might investigate the situation. You might even give the employee a raise. This may sound innocent, but you have just created a strong incentive for political behavior.\",\"index\":848,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Specifically, you will be rewarding behavior that has nothing to do with advancing your business. The employee will earn a raise by asking for one rather than as a result of your rewarding them for outstanding performance. Why is this bad? Let me count the ways:\",\"index\":849,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** The other ambitious members of your staff will immediately get the point and agitate for raises as well. Word always gets out. Note that neither this campaign nor the prior one need be correlated with actual performance. You will now spend time dealing with the political issues rather than actual performance issues. Importantly, if you have a competent board, you will not be able to give them all out-of-cycle raises, so your company executive raises will occur on a first-come, first-served basis.\",\"index\":850,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** The less aggressive (but perhaps more competent) members of your team will be denied off-cycle raises simply by being apolitical.\",\"index\":851,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** The object lesson for your staff and the company will be that the squeaky wheel gets the grease, and that the most politically astute employees get the raises. Get ready for a whole lot of squeaky wheels.\",\"index\":852,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Specifically, you will be rewarding behavior that has nothing to do with advancing your business. The employee will earn a raise by asking for one rather than as a result of your rewarding them for outstanding performance. Why is this bad? Let me count the ways: \\n\\n **1.** The other ambitious members of your staff will immediately get the point and agitate for raises as well. Word always gets out. Note that neither this campaign nor the prior one need be correlated with actual performance. You will now spend time dealing with the political issues rather than actual performance issues. Importantly, if you have a competent board, you will not be able to give them all out-of-cycle raises, so your company executive raises will occur on a first-come, first-served basis. \\n\\n **2.** The less aggressive (but perhaps more competent) members of your team will be denied off-cycle raises simply by being apolitical. \\n\\n **3.** The object lesson for your staff and the company will be that the squeaky wheel gets the grease, and that the most politically astute employees get the raises. Get ready for a whole lot of squeaky wheels.\"},{\"content\":\"Now let’s move on to a more complicated example. Your CFO comes to you and says that he wants to continue developing as a manager. He says that he would like to eventually become a COO and would like to know what skills he must demonstrate in order to earn that position in your company. Being a positive leader, you would like to encourage him to pursue his dream. You tell him that you think that he’d be a fine COO someday and that he should work to develop a few more skills. In addition, you tell him that he’ll need to be a strong enough leader, such that other executives in the company will want to work for him. A week later, one of your other executives comes to you in a panic. She says that the CFO just asked her if she’d work for him. She says that he said you are grooming him to be the COO and that’s his final step. Did that just happen? Welcome to the big time.\",\"index\":853,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, you may unintentionally foster political behavior by how you handle certain situations, such as executive compensation and career development aspirations. For instance, when senior employees request raises by citing market value or competitive offers, granting their request, even if reasonable, incentivizes others to engage in similar behavior regardless of actual performance, creating a culture where political maneuvering overshadows true merit. This dynamic can lead to time-consuming political issues, non-performance-based raises, resentment among the less aggressive yet potentially more competent team members, and the perception that being politically savvy is key to advancement. A more complex scenario involves a CFO expressing ambitions to become the COO and asking you for guidance on the required skills. When encouraged, the CFO might prematurely assert his future role, causing chaos and uncertainty among other executives. This highlights the intricacies and potential pitfalls of navigating leadership aspirations within the company.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**HOW TO MINIMIZE POLITICS**\",\"index\":854,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Minimizing politics often feels totally unnatural. It’s counter to excellent management practices such as being open-minded and encouraging employee development.\",\"index\":855,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The difference between managing executives and managing more junior employees can be thought of as the difference between being in a fight with someone with no training and being in a ring with a professional boxer. If you are in a fight with a regular person, then you can do natural things and they won’t get you into much trouble. For example, if you want to take a step backward, you can pick your front foot up first. If you do this against a professional boxer, you will get your block knocked off. Professional boxers train for years to take advantage of small errors in technique. Lifting your front foot first to take a step backward will take you slightly off balance for a split second and that’s all your opponent will need.\",\"index\":856,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Similarly, if you manage a junior employee and they ask you about their career development, you can say what comes naturally and generally get away with it. As we saw above, things change when you deal with highly ambitious, seasoned professionals. In order to keep from getting knocked out by corporate politics, you need to refine your technique.\",\"index\":857,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Minimizing politics often feels unnatural and goes against excellent management practices like being open-minded and encouraging employee development. Managing executives versus junior employees is akin to a fight between an untrained person and a professional boxer. Natural actions may suffice with junior staff, such as straightforward discussions about career development, without much risk. However, with highly ambitious, seasoned professionals, minor missteps can be exploited, much like a boxer taking advantage of a slight balance error. Thus, refined techniques are essential to navigate the complexities and avoid being sidelined by corporate politics.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE TECHNIQUE**\",\"index\":858,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"As I developed as a CEO, I found two key techniques to be useful in minimizing politics.\",\"index\":859,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** Hire people with the right kind of ambition. The cases that I described above might involve people who are ambitious but not necessarily inherently political. All cases are not like this. The surest way to turn your company into the political equivalent of the U.S. Senate is to hire people with the wrong kind of ambition. As defined by Andy Grove, the right kind of ambition is ambition for the company’s success with the executive’s own success only coming as a by-product of the company’s victory. The wrong kind of ambition is ambition for the executive’s personal success regardless of the company’s outcome.\",\"index\":860,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Build strict processes for potentially political issues and do not deviate. Certain activities attract political behavior. These activities include:\",\"index\":861,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Performance evaluation and compensation\\n\\n* Organizational design and territory\\n\\n* Promotions\",\"index\":862,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"As I developed as a CEO, I found two key techniques to be useful in minimizing politics. \\n\\n **1.** Hire people with the right kind of ambition. The cases that I described above might involve people who are ambitious but not necessarily inherently political. All cases are not like this. The surest way to turn your company into the political equivalent of the U.S. Senate is to hire people with the wrong kind of ambition. As defined by Andy Grove, the right kind of ambition is ambition for the company’s success with the executive’s own success only coming as a by-product of the company’s victory. The wrong kind of ambition is ambition for the executive’s personal success regardless of the company’s outcome. \\n\\n **2.** Build strict processes for potentially political issues and do not deviate. Certain activities attract political behavior. These activities include: \\n\\n * Performance evaluation and compensation\\n\\n* Organizational design and territory\\n\\n* Promotions\"},{\"content\":\"Let’s examine each case and how you might build and execute a process that insulates the company from bad behavior and politically motivated outcomes.\",\"index\":863,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**Performance evaluation and compensation** Often companies defer putting performance management and compensation processes in place. This doesn’t mean that they don’t evaluate employees or give pay raises; it just means they do so in an ad hoc manner that’s highly vulnerable to political machinations. By conducting well-structured, regular performance and compensation reviews, you will ensure that pay and stock increases are as fair as possible. This is especially important for executive compensation, since doing so will also serve to minimize politics. In the example above, the CEO should have had an airtight performance and compensation policy and simply told the executive that his compensation would be evaluated with everyone else’s. Ideally, the executive compensation process should involve the board of directors. This will help ensure good governance and make exceptions even more difficult.\",\"index\":864,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**Organizational design and territory** If you manage ambitious people, from time to time they will want to expand their scope of responsibility. In the example above, the CFO wanted to become the COO. In other situations, the head of marketing might want to run sales and marketing or the head of engineering may want to run engineering and product management. When someone raises an issue like this with you, you must be very careful about what you say, because everything that you say can be turned into political cannon fodder. Generally, it’s best to say nothing at all. At most, you might ask “why?” but if you do so be sure not to react to the reasons. If you indicate what you are thinking, that information will leak, rumors will spread, and you plant the seeds for all kinds of unproductive discussions. You should evaluate your organizational design on a regular basis and gather the information that you need to decide without tipping people off to what you plan to do. Once you decide, you should immediately execute the reorg: Don’t leave time for leaks and lobbying.\",\"index\":865,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Promotions** Every time your company gives someone a promotion, everyone else at that person’s organizational level evaluates the promotion and judges whether merit or political favors yielded it. If the latter, then the other employees generally react in one of three ways:\",\"index\":866,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** They sulk and feel undervalued.\",\"index\":867,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** They outwardly disagree, campaign against the person, and undermine them in their new position.\",\"index\":868,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** They attempt to copy the political behavior that generated the unwarranted promotion.\",\"index\":869,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Clearly, you don’t want any of these behaviors in your company. Therefore, you must have a formal, visible, defensible promotion process that governs every employee promotion. Often this process must be different for people on your own staff. (The general process may involve various managers who are familiar with the employee’s work; the executive process should include the board of directors.) The purpose of the process is twofold. First, it will give the organization confidence that the company at least attempted to base the promotion on merit. Second, the process will produce the information necessary for your team to explain the promotion decisions you made.\",\"index\":870,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**Promotions** Every time your company gives someone a promotion, everyone else at that person’s organizational level evaluates the promotion and judges whether merit or political favors yielded it. If the latter, then the other employees generally react in one of three ways: \\n\\n **1.** They sulk and feel undervalued. \\n\\n **2.** They outwardly disagree, campaign against the person, and undermine them in their new position. \\n\\n **3.** They attempt to copy the political behavior that generated the unwarranted promotion. \\n\\n Clearly, you don’t want any of these behaviors in your company. Therefore, you must have a formal, visible, defensible promotion process that governs every employee promotion. Often this process must be different for people on your own staff. (The general process may involve various managers who are familiar with the employee’s work; the executive process should include the board of directors.) The purpose of the process is twofold. First, it will give the organization confidence that the company at least attempted to base the promotion on merit. Second, the process will produce the information necessary for your team to explain the promotion decisions you made.\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Be careful with “he said, she said”** Once your organization grows to a significant size, members of your team will from time to time complain about each other. Sometimes this criticism will be extremely aggressive. Be careful about how you listen and the message that it sends. Simply by hearing them out without defending the employee in question, you will send the message that you agree. If people in the company think that you agree that one of your executives is less than stellar, that information will spread quickly and without qualification. As a result, people will stop listening to the executive in question and the executive will soon become ineffective.\",\"index\":871,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There are two distinct types of complaints that you will receive:\",\"index\":872,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** Complaints about an executive’s behavior\",\"index\":873,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Complaints about an executive’s competency or performance\",\"index\":874,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Generally, the best way to handle the first type of complaint is to get the complaining executive and the targeted executive in the room together and have them explain themselves. Usually, simply having this meeting will resolve the conflict and correct the behavior and improve the relationship (if it was actually broken). Do not attempt to address behavioral issues without both executives in the room. Doing so will invite manipulation and politics.\",\"index\":875,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Complaints of the second type are both more rare and more complex. If one of your executives summons the courage to complain about the competency of one of their peers, then there is a good chance that either the complainer or the targeted executive has a major problem. If you receive this type of complaint, you will generally have one of two reactions: they will be telling you something that you already know, or they’ll be telling you shocking news.\",\"index\":876,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If they are telling you something that you already know, then the big news is that you have let the situation go too far. Whatever your reasons for attempting to rehabilitate the wayward executive, you have taken too long and now your organization has turned on them. You must resolve the situation quickly. Almost always, this means firing the executive. While I’ve seen executives improve their performance and skill sets, I’ve never seen one lose the support of the organization and then regain it.\",\"index\":877,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"On the other hand, if the complaint is new news, then you must immediately stop the conversation and make clear to the complaining executive that you in no way agree with their assessment. You do not want to cripple the other executive before you reevaluate his performance. You do not want the complaint to become a self-fulfilling prophecy. Once you’ve shut down the conversation, you must quickly reassess the employee in question. If you find he is doing an excellent job, you must figure out the complaining executive’s motivations and resolve them. Do not let an accusation of this magnitude fester. If you find that the employee is doing a poor job, there will be time to go back and get the complaining employee’s input, but you should be on a track to remove the poor performer at that point.\",\"index\":878,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As CEO, you must consider the systemic incentives that result from your words and actions. While it may feel good in the moment to be open, responsive, and action oriented, be careful not to encourage all the wrong things.\",\"index\":879,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**Be careful with “he said, she said”** Once your organization grows to a significant size, members of your team will from time to time complain about each other. Sometimes this criticism will be extremely aggressive. Be careful about how you listen and the message that it sends. Simply by hearing them out without defending the employee in question, you will send the message that you agree. If people in the company think that you agree that one of your executives is less than stellar, that information will spread quickly and without qualification. As a result, people will stop listening to the executive in question and the executive will soon become ineffective. \\n\\n There are two distinct types of complaints that you will receive: \\n\\n **1.** Complaints about an executive’s behavior \\n\\n **2.** Complaints about an executive’s competency or performance \\n\\n Generally, the best way to handle the first type of complaint is to get the complaining executive and the targeted executive in the room together and have them explain themselves. Usually, simply having this meeting will resolve the conflict and correct the behavior and improve the relationship (if it was actually broken). Do not attempt to address behavioral issues without both executives in the room. Doing so will invite manipulation and politics. \\n\\n Complaints of the second type are both more rare and more complex. If one of your executives summons the courage to complain about the competency of one of their peers, then there is a good chance that either the complainer or the targeted executive has a major problem. If you receive this type of complaint, you will generally have one of two reactions: they will be telling you something that you already know, or they’ll be telling you shocking news. \\n\\n If they are telling you something that you already know, then the big news is that you have let the situation go too far. Whatever your reasons for attempting to rehabilitate the wayward executive, you have taken too long and now your organization has turned on them. You must resolve the situation quickly. Almost always, this means firing the executive. While I’ve seen executives improve their performance and skill sets, I’ve never seen one lose the support of the organization and then regain it. \\n\\n On the other hand, if the complaint is new news, then you must immediately stop the conversation and make clear to the complaining executive that you in no way agree with their assessment. You do not want to cripple the other executive before you reevaluate his performance. You do not want the complaint to become a self-fulfilling prophecy. Once you’ve shut down the conversation, you must quickly reassess the employee in question. If you find he is doing an excellent job, you must figure out the complaining executive’s motivations and resolve them. Do not let an accusation of this magnitude fester. If you find that the employee is doing a poor job, there will be time to go back and get the complaining employee’s input, but you should be on a track to remove the poor performer at that point. \\n\\n As CEO, you must consider the systemic incentives that result from your words and actions. While it may feel good in the moment to be open, responsive, and action oriented, be careful not to encourage all the wrong things.\"},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":880,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":881,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As I evolved as a CEO, I discovered two crucial techniques for minimizing workplace politics: hiring people with the right kind of ambition and establishing strict, unwavering processes for potentially political issues such as performance evaluation and compensation, organizational design and territory, and promotions. The right ambition, as defined by Andy Grove, aligns personal success with the company's success, unlike the harmful ambition prioritizing personal gain regardless of the company's outcome. It's vital to implement structured performance management and compensation reviews, and involve the board in executive evaluations to ensure fairness and minimize political maneuvering. Regularly reassess organizational design without tipping off employees to prevent unproductive discussions, and execute changes swiftly to avoid leaks and lobbying. Promotions should follow a transparent and defensible process to maintain organizational confidence and meritocracy. When handling complaints, address behavior issues directly with both parties involved to avoid manipulation, and reassess competence concerns promptly to prevent undermining effective executives or letting performance issues fester. Always consider the systemic incentives your actions create, being cautious not to encourage the wrong behaviors while striving for responsiveness and openness.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, your handling of situations like executive compensation and career development aspirations can unintentionally foster political behavior. Granting raises based on market value or competitive offers may encourage others to engage in similar political maneuvers, overshadowing true merit and leading to time-consuming political issues, non-performance-based raises, and resentment among competent yet less aggressive team members. Navigating leadership aspirations, such as a CFO aiming to become COO, can also create chaos among executives if not managed carefully. Minimizing politics often conflicts with excellent management practices like being open-minded and encouraging development. While straightforward discussions work for junior staff, seasoned professionals require refined techniques to avoid exploitation of minor missteps. Two crucial techniques I discovered to minimize workplace politics are hiring individuals with the right ambition—aligned with the company's success—and establishing strict, unwavering processes for performance evaluation, compensation, organizational design, territory, and promotions. Structured reviews, board involvement in executive evaluations, regular reassessment of organizational design, swift execution of changes, transparent promotion processes, and direct handling of behavior issues are essential. Always consider the systemic incentives your actions create to avoid encouraging the wrong behaviors while striving to maintain responsiveness and openness.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, your handling of situations like executive compensation and career development aspirations can unintentionally foster political behavior. Granting raises based on market value or competitive offers may encourage others to engage in similar political maneuvers, overshadowing true merit and leading to time-consuming political issues, non-performance-based raises, and resentment among competent yet less aggressive team members. Navigating leadership aspirations, such as a CFO aiming to become COO, can also create chaos among executives if not managed carefully. Minimizing politics often conflicts with excellent management practices like being open-minded and encouraging development. While straightforward discussions work for junior staff, seasoned professionals require refined techniques to avoid exploitation of minor missteps. Two crucial techniques I discovered to minimize workplace politics are hiring individuals with the right ambition—aligned with the company's success—and establishing strict, unwavering processes for performance evaluation, compensation, organizational design, territory, and promotions. Structured reviews, board involvement in executive evaluations, regular reassessment of organizational design, swift execution of changes, transparent promotion processes, and direct handling of behavior issues are essential. Always consider the systemic incentives your actions create to avoid encouraging the wrong behaviors while striving to maintain responsiveness and openness.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[THE RIGHT KIND OF AMBITION]()**\",\"index\":882,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"When hiring a management team, most startups focus almost exclusively on IQ, but a bunch of high-IQ people with the wrong kind of ambition won’t work. I have already stressed that you should strive to hire people with the right kind of ambition. As I’ve talked about these ideas in the last few years, I have received a mixed response. Some think it’s good advice, while others question it.\",\"index\":883,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At a macro level, a company will be most successful if the senior managers optimize for the company’s success (think of this as a global optimization) as opposed to their own personal success (local optimization). No matter how well the CEO designs the personal incentive programs, they will never be perfect. In addition, career incentives like promotions and territory ownership fall outside the scope of bonus plans and other a priori management tools. In an equity-based compensation structure, optimizing for the company’s success should yield better results for individuals as well. As my Opsware head of sales Mark Cranney used to say, “Two percent of zero is zero.”\",\"index\":884,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"It is particularly important that managers have the right kind of ambition, because anything else will be exceptionally demotivating for their employees. As an employee, why would I want to work long hours to advance the career of my manager? If the manager cares more about his career than the company, then that’s what I’d be doing. Nothing motivates a great employee more than a mission that’s so important that it supersedes everyone’s personal ambition. As a result, managers with the right kind of ambition tend to be radically more valuable than those with the wrong kind. For a complete explanation of the dangers of managers with the wrong kind of ambition, I strongly recommend Dr. Seuss’s management masterpiece *Yertle the Turtle*.\",\"index\":885,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When hiring a management team, focusing solely on IQ won't ensure success; it’s crucial to seek individuals with the right kind of ambition. A company thrives when senior managers prioritize the company's overall success (global optimization) instead of their personal gains (local optimization). Despite well-designed personal incentive programs, they can never be perfect, and aspects like promotions and territory ownership are beyond these incentives' control. Aligning with company success through equity-based compensation benefits individuals too, as succinctly put by Mark Cranney: “Two percent of zero is zero.” Managers with the right ambition are essential because they inspire employees to work diligently for a greater mission, rather than just advancing a manager's career. Managers driven by the company’s goals become significantly more valuable, and for further understanding, Dr. Seuss’s *Yertle the Turtle* provides a brilliant perspective on the pitfalls of the wrong kind of ambition.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SCREENING FOR THE RIGHT KIND OF AMBITION**\",\"index\":886,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As with any complex character trait, there is no way to perfectly screen for the right kind of ambition in an interview, but hopefully some of these thoughts will prove useful.\",\"index\":887,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At a macro level, everybody views the world through her own personal prism. When interviewing candidates, it’s helpful to watch for small distinctions that indicate whether they view the world through the “me” prism or the “team” prism.\",\"index\":888,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"People who view the world through the “me” prism might describe a prior company’s failure in an interview as follows: “My last job was my e-commerce play. I felt that it was important to round out my résumé.” Note the use of *my* to personalize the company in a way that it’s unlikely that anyone else at the company would agree with. In fact, the other employees in the company might even be offended by this usage. People with the right kind of ambition would not likely use the word *play* to describe their effort to work as a team to build something substantial. Finally, people who use the “me” prism find it natural and obvious to speak in terms of “building out my résumé” while people who use the “team” prism find such phrases to be somewhat uncomfortable and awkward, because they clearly indicate an individual goal that is separate from the team goal.\",\"index\":889,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"On the other hand, people who view the world purely through the team prism will very seldom use the words *I* or *me* even when answering questions about their accomplishments. Even in an interview, they will deflect credit to others on their previous team. They will tend to be far more interested in how your company will win than in how they will be compensated or what their career path will be. When asked about a previously failed company, they will generally feel such great responsibility that they will describe in detail their own misjudgments and bad decisions.\",\"index\":890,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When we hired the head of worldwide sales for Opsware, using this screen proved to be quite valuable. Since this was a sales position, I should mention (in reference to the commenter above) that ambition for the company above one’s own goals is particularly important for the head of sales. The reasons are many:\",\"index\":891,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* The local incentives in sales are particularly strong and difficult to balance without the right kind of leadership.\\n\\n* The sales organization is the face of the company to the outside world. If that group optimizes for itself, your company will have a major problem.\\n\\n* In high-tech companies, fraud generally starts in sales due to managers attempting to perfect the ultimate local optimization.\",\"index\":892,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Throughout our interview process, we met with a lot of candidates who took sole credit for landing extremely large deals, achieving impressive goals, and generating company success. Invariably, the candidates who claimed the most credit for deals would have the most difficult time describing the details of how the deal was actually won and orchestrated. During reference checks, others involved in the deals would tell a very different story.\",\"index\":893,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I spoke to Mark Cranney, on the other hand, it was difficult to get him to discuss his personal accomplishments. In fact, some of the other interviewers felt that Mark was standoffish and even obnoxious in the way he bristled at certain questions. One interviewer complained, “Ben, I know that he increased the size of the Nike deal from one million to five million, because our contact at Nike told me that, but Mark wouldn’t go into any detail on it.” When I interviewed Mark, he really only wanted to discuss how his old company won. He went into great detail about how his team diagnosed weaknesses versus the competition and how he worked with another executive to advance the product. He then talked about how he worked with the CEO to revise the way the sales force was trained and organized.\",\"index\":894,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When the conversation turned to Opsware, Mark had already interviewed sales reps at our number-one competitor’s company and knew what deals they were in. He relentlessly questioned me on how we were going to win the deals that they were in and how we planned to get into the deals that we weren’t in. He wanted to know the strengths and weaknesses of everyone else on the team. He wanted to know the game plan for winning. The topics of his potential compensation and career advancement didn’t come up until the very end of the process. And then he only wanted assurances that compensation was performance- and not politically based. It was clear that Mark was all about the team and its success.\",\"index\":895,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"During Mark’s tenure, sales increased more than tenfold, and our market capitalization increased twentyfold. More to the point, voluntary attrition in the sales organization was extremely low, customers were managed fairly and honestly, and our legal and finance teams often commented that first and foremost, Mark protected the company.\",\"index\":896,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Screening for the right ambition during job interviews involves examining how candidates perceive their accomplishments. Individuals who focus on \\\"me\\\" often prioritize their own résumé, which can indicate a self-centered outlook. In contrast, those with a \\\"team\\\" perspective attribute successes to collective efforts and prioritize the company's goals. This distinction is vital for roles demanding a balance between local and broader objectives, such as head of sales. At Opsware, this approach led us to hire Mark Cranney, who stood out by emphasizing his team's strategies over self-promotion. Unlike other candidates, Mark had thoroughly researched our top competitor, questioned our strategy, and focused on success rather than personal gain. His compensation was only discussed last, insisting it be performance-based. Mark's dedication resulted in a tenfold increase in sales, a twentyfold rise in market capitalization, low voluntary attrition, and high commendations for fairness and integrity from customers and the legal and finance teams.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FINAL THOUGHT**\",\"index\":897,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"While it may work to have individual employees who optimize for their own careers, counting on senior managers to do all the right things for all the wrong reasons is a dangerous idea.\",\"index\":898,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":899,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":900,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Relying on senior managers to consistently make the best decisions for the organization, despite possibly being driven by self-serving motives, poses significant risks. While having employees focus on personal career growth can be effective, expecting senior leaders to always align with the company's best interests for self-centered reasons is a perilous strategy.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Screening for the right ambition during job interviews requires evaluating how candidates view their achievements. Those who focus on \\\"me\\\" often highlight their résumé and personal gains, signaling self-centeredness. In contrast, candidates with a \\\"team\\\" mindset attribute successes to collective efforts and prioritize the company's goals. This distinction is crucial for roles like head of sales that demand balancing local and broader objectives. At Opsware, this led us to hire Mark Cranney, who stressed his team’s strategies and success over self-promotion. Mark’s thorough competitor research, strategic questioning, and insistence on performance-based compensation showcased his focus on company success. His commitment propelled a tenfold sales increase, a twentyfold rise in market capitalization, and strong commendations for fairness and integrity from internal and external stakeholders. Relying on senior managers driven by self-interest is risky since their decisions might not always align with the organization’s best interests, highlighting the importance of a team-focused ambition.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Screening for the right ambition during job interviews requires evaluating how candidates view their achievements. Those who focus on \\\"me\\\" often highlight their résumé and personal gains, signaling self-centeredness. In contrast, candidates with a \\\"team\\\" mindset attribute successes to collective efforts and prioritize the company's goals. This distinction is crucial for roles like head of sales that demand balancing local and broader objectives. At Opsware, this led us to hire Mark Cranney, who stressed his team’s strategies and success over self-promotion. Mark’s thorough competitor research, strategic questioning, and insistence on performance-based compensation showcased his focus on company success. His commitment propelled a tenfold sales increase, a twentyfold rise in market capitalization, and strong commendations for fairness and integrity from internal and external stakeholders. Relying on senior managers driven by self-interest is risky since their decisions might not always align with the organization’s best interests, highlighting the importance of a team-focused ambition.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[TITLES AND PROMOTIONS]()**\",\"index\":901,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Often when I meet with startups, the employees have no job titles. This makes sense, because everybody is just working to build the company. Roles needn’t be clearly defined and, in fact, can’t be, because everyone does a little bit of everything. In an environment like this there are no politics and nobody is jockeying for position or authority. It’s rather nice. So why do all organizations eventually create job titles and what is the proper way to manage them? (Thanks to Mark Zuckerberg for contributing to my thinking on this subject.)\",\"index\":902,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Often when I meet with startups, the employees have no job titles. This makes sense, because everybody is just working to build the company. Roles needn’t be clearly defined and, in fact, can’t be, because everyone does a little bit of everything. In an environment like this there are no politics and nobody is jockeying for position or authority. It’s rather nice. So why do all organizations eventually create job titles and what is the proper way to manage them? (Thanks to Mark Zuckerberg for contributing to my thinking on this subject.)\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHY DO TITLES MATTER?**\",\"index\":903,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Two important factors drive all companies to eventually create job titles:\",\"index\":904,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** *Employees want them.* While you may plan to work at your company forever, at least some of your employees need to plan for life after your company. When your head of sales interviews for her next job, she won’t want to say that despite the fact that she ran a global sales force with hundreds of employees, her title was “Dude.”\",\"index\":905,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** *Eventually, people need to know who is who.* As companies grow, everybody won’t know everybody else. Importantly, employees won’t know what each person does and whom they should work with to get their jobs done. Job titles provide an excellent shorthand for describing roles in the company. In addition, customers and business partners can also make use of this shorthand to figure out how to best work with your company.\",\"index\":906,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Two important factors drive all companies to eventually create job titles: \\n\\n **1.** *Employees want them.* While you may plan to work at your company forever, at least some of your employees need to plan for life after your company. When your head of sales interviews for her next job, she won’t want to say that despite the fact that she ran a global sales force with hundreds of employees, her title was “Dude.” \\n\\n **2.** *Eventually, people need to know who is who.* As companies grow, everybody won’t know everybody else. Importantly, employees won’t know what each person does and whom they should work with to get their jobs done. Job titles provide an excellent shorthand for describing roles in the company. In addition, customers and business partners can also make use of this shorthand to figure out how to best work with your company.\"},{\"content\":\"Beyond these core reasons, employees will use titles to calibrate their value and compensation against their colleagues. If an employee with a title of Junior Engineer believes that she is a far better programmer than her counterpart with the title Senior Architect, this will indicate to her that she may be underpaid and undervalued. Because titles will be used to calculate relative value, they must be managed carefully.\",\"index\":907,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Two critical factors drive companies to establish job titles: employees' needs and organizational clarity. First, employees desire titles to facilitate future career moves, as exemplified by a head of sales who wouldn't want to downplay her extensive role in a job interview. Second, job titles are crucial for organizational structure, especially as the company grows, helping employees, customers, and business partners understand roles and responsibilities. Moreover, titles play a crucial role in how employees gauge their value and compensation relative to their peers, necessitating careful management to ensure fairness and accurate representation of roles.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE DANGERS: THE PETER PRINCIPLE AND THE LAW OF CRAPPY PEOPLE**\",\"index\":908,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The basics seem obvious, so why does almost every company eventually make serious mistakes regarding titles? If you have ever worked in a company, you have probably thought to yourself about some overly promoted executive: “How did he get to be a vice president? I wouldn’t let him manage a lemonade stand.”\",\"index\":909,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"One challenge is the Peter Principle. Coined by Dr. Laurence J. Peter and Raymond Hull in their 1969 book of that name, the Peter Principle holds that in a hierarchy, members are promoted so long as they work competently. Sooner or later they are promoted to a position at which they are no longer competent (their “level of incompetence”), and there they remain being unable to earn further promotions. As Andy Grove points out in his management classic *High Output Management*, the Peter Principle is unavoidable, because there is no way to know a priori at what level in the hierarchy a manager will be incompetent.\",\"index\":910,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Another challenge is a phenomenon that I call the *Law of Crappy People*. The Law of Crappy People states: *For any title level in a large organization, the talent on that level will eventually converge to the crappiest person with the title.*\",\"index\":911,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The rationale behind the law is that the other employees in the company with lower titles will naturally benchmark themselves against the crappiest person at the next level. For example, if Jasper is the worst vice president in the company, then all of the directors will benchmark themselves against Jasper and demand promotions as soon as they reach his low level of competency.\",\"index\":912,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As with the Peter Principle, the best that you can do is to mitigate the Law of Crappy People and that mitigation will be critically important to the quality of your company.\",\"index\":913,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Almost every company ends up making serious mistakes with titles, often leading you to question how certain executives were promoted despite seeming unqualified. This issue is partly due to the Peter Principle, which suggests that employees within a hierarchy are promoted based on their competence until they reach a level where they become incompetent, as they can no longer manage efficiently. Another contributing factor is what I call the *Law of Crappy People*. This law states that within a large organization, the talent at any given title level will eventually deteriorate to match the least competent person holding that title. This occurs as employees benchmark themselves against the lowest-performing individual at the next level and seek promotions upon reaching that person’s level of competence. Mitigating these challenges is crucial to maintaining the quality of your company.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**PROMOTION PROCESS**\",\"index\":914,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The best way to mitigate both the Peter Principle and the Law of Crappy People is with a properly constructed and highly disciplined promotion process. Ideally, the promotion process should yield a result similar to the very best karate dojos. In top dojos, in order to achieve the next level (for example, being promoted from a brown belt to a black belt), you must defeat an opponent in combat at that level. This guarantees that a new black belt is never a worse fighter than the worst current black belt.\",\"index\":915,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Frustratingly, there is no exact analogue to a fistfight in business, so how can we preserve quality without actual combat?\",\"index\":916,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"To begin, start with an extremely crisp definition not only of the responsibilities at each level but also of the skill required to perform the duties. When describing the skills, avoid the generic characterizations such as “must be competent at managing a P&L” or “must have excellent management skills.” In fact, the best leveling tools get extremely specific and even name names: “should be a superstar recruiter—as good as Jenny Rogers.”\",\"index\":917,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Next, define a formal process for all promotions. One key requirement of the process should be that promotions will be leveled across groups. If you let a manager or a single chain of command determine promotions unilaterally, then it’s possible that, for example, HR will have five vice presidents and Engineering only one. One way to level across groups is to hold a regular promotions council that reviews every significant promotion in the company. When a manager wishes to promote an employee, she will submit that employee for review with an explanation of why she believes her employee satisfies the skill criteria required for the level. The committee should then compare the employee with both the level’s skill description and the skills of the other employees at that level to determine whether to approve the promotion. In addition to ensuring fairness and level quality, this process will serve to educate your entire management team on the skills and accomplishments of the employees being submitted for promotion.\",\"index\":918,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"To mitigate the Peter Principle and the Law of Crappy People, implement a well-structured and disciplined promotion process akin to the rigorous standards in top karate dojos. In these dojos, advancing to the next belt requires defeating an opponent at that level, ensuring new black belts are never inferior to existing ones. Although there's no direct business equivalent to a fistfight, you can maintain quality by defining clear, detailed responsibilities and skill requirements at each level, avoiding generic terms. Furthermore, establish a formal, cross-group promotion process to prevent imbalance and ensure fairness. Regular promotion councils should review each significant promotion, with managers submitting candidates for evaluation against skill criteria and peer comparison to maintain high standards and educate the management team on employee achievements.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**ANDREESSEN VS. ZUCKERBERG: HOW BIG SHOULD THE TITLES BE?**\",\"index\":919,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Should your company make Vice President the top title or should you have Chief Marketing Officers, Chief Revenue Officers, Chief People Officers, and Chief Snack Officers? There are two schools of thought regarding this, one represented by Marc Andreessen and the other by Mark Zuckerberg.\",\"index\":920,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Andreessen argues that people ask for many things from a company: salary, bonus, stock options, span of control, and titles. Of those, title is by far the cheapest, so it makes sense to give the highest titles possible. The hierarchy should have Presidents, Chiefs, and Senior Executive Vice Presidents. If it makes people feel better, let them feel better. Titles cost nothing. Better yet, when competing for new employees with other companies, using Andreessen’s method you can always outbid the competition in at least one dimension.\",\"index\":921,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At Facebook, by contrast, Mark Zuckerberg purposely deploys titles that are significantly lower than the industry standard. Senior Vice Presidents at other companies must take title haircuts down to Directors or Managers at Facebook. Why does he do this? First, he guarantees that every new employee gets releveled as they enter his company. In this way, he avoids accidentally giving new employees higher titles and positions than better-performing existing employees. This boosts morale and increases fairness. Second, it forces all the managers of Facebook to understand and internalize Facebook’s leveling system, which serves the company extremely well in their own promotion and compensation processes.\",\"index\":922,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"He also wants titles to be meaningful and reflect who has influence in the organization. As a company grows quickly, it’s important to provide organizational clarity wherever possible and that gets more difficult if there are fifty VPs and ten Chiefs.\",\"index\":923,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Next, he finds that businesspeople often carry inflated titles versus their engineering counterparts. While he recognizes that big titles help them out externally with getting meetings, he still wants to have an organization where the product people and engineers form the cultural core, so he strives to keep this in check as well.\",\"index\":924,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Does Facebook ever miss out on a new hire due to its low titles? Yes, definitely. But one might argue that they miss out on precisely the employees they don’t want. In fact, both the hiring and onboarding processes at Facebook have been carefully designed to encourage the right kind of employees to select themselves in and the wrong ones to select themselves out.\",\"index\":925,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"So which method is better, Andreessen’s or Zuckerberg’s? The answer is that it depends. Facebook has so many advantages in recruiting employees that being disciplined about absolute title levels does not significantly impair its ability to attract the very best talent. Your company might not have these advantages, so lofty titles may be a good tactic. In either scenario, you should still run a highly disciplined internal leveling and promotion process.\",\"index\":926,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Deciding whether to use Vice Presidents or more specialized titles like Chief Marketing Officers and Chief Revenue Officers depends on your company's circumstances. Marc Andreessen advocates for giving high titles freely since they’re cost-effective and can make employees feel valued, while also providing a competitive edge in attracting talent. In contrast, Mark Zuckerberg at Facebook intentionally uses lower-than-industry-standard titles to ensure fair leveling and maintain clarity in the organization. Zuckerberg believes this approach avoids giving new hires undue seniority, promotes fairness, and keeps titles meaningful, particularly valuing the core influence of product people and engineers. Although Facebook might miss out on some candidates due to its conservative title structure, this helps filter for the right cultural fit. Ultimately, the best method varies by company; Facebook's strong recruiting advantages allow it to maintain stringent title discipline without hindering talent attraction, something other companies may need to compensate for with more impressive titles. Regardless of which strategy you choose, maintaining a disciplined internal leveling and promotion process is crucial.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FINAL THOUGHT**\",\"index\":927,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"You might think that so much time spent on promotions and titles places too much importance and focus on silly formalisms. The opposite is true. Without a well thought out, disciplined process for titles and promotions, your employees will become obsessed with the resulting inequities. If you structure things properly, nobody other than you will spend much time thinking about titles other than Employee of the Month.\",\"index\":928,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":929,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":930,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"You might think that spending so much time on promotions and titles emphasizes silly formalisms, but the opposite is true. Without a well-thought-out, disciplined process for titles and promotions, employees will fixate on the resulting inequities. Structure things properly, and no one but you will worry much about titles, except maybe Employee of the Month.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Job titles are essential for addressing both employees' needs and organizational clarity. Employees rely on titles for career mobility, and a clear hierarchy helps everyone understand roles and responsibilities, ensuring fairness and accurate compensation evaluation. Companies often err in title assignments, leading to incompetence due to the Peter Principle and the *Law of Crappy People*, where standards deteriorate to the level of the least competent individual. Mitigating this requires a disciplined promotion process, establishing clear responsibilities and skill requirements, and a formal, cross-group promotion review by regular councils. The choice between grand titles like Vice Presidents and more specific ones like Chief Marketing Officers varies by company. Marc Andreessen suggests giving high titles freely to make employees feel valued and attract talent, while Mark Zuckerberg favors modest titles for clarity and fairness. Facebook's strong recruiting allows it to maintain this discipline without losing competitiveness, a balance other companies may need to achieve with more impressive titles. Ultimately, a disciplined title and promotion process prevents fixations on inequities and maintains organizational efficiency.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Job titles are essential for addressing both employees' needs and organizational clarity. Employees rely on titles for career mobility, and a clear hierarchy helps everyone understand roles and responsibilities, ensuring fairness and accurate compensation evaluation. Companies often err in title assignments, leading to incompetence due to the Peter Principle and the *Law of Crappy People*, where standards deteriorate to the level of the least competent individual. Mitigating this requires a disciplined promotion process, establishing clear responsibilities and skill requirements, and a formal, cross-group promotion review by regular councils. The choice between grand titles like Vice Presidents and more specific ones like Chief Marketing Officers varies by company. Marc Andreessen suggests giving high titles freely to make employees feel valued and attract talent, while Mark Zuckerberg favors modest titles for clarity and fairness. Facebook's strong recruiting allows it to maintain this discipline without losing competitiveness, a balance other companies may need to achieve with more impressive titles. Ultimately, a disciplined title and promotion process prevents fixations on inequities and maintains organizational efficiency.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[WHEN SMART PEOPLE ARE BAD EMPLOYEES]()**\",\"index\":931,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"In business, intelligence is always a critical element in any employee, because what we do is difficult and complex and the competitors are filled with extremely smart people. However, intelligence is not the only important quality. Being effective in a company also means working hard, being reliable, and being an excellent member of the team.\",\"index\":932,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I was a CEO, this was one of the most difficult lessons for me to learn. I felt that it was my job to create an environment where brilliant people of all backgrounds, personality types, and work styles would thrive. And I was right. That was my job. Companies where people with diverse backgrounds and work styles can succeed have significant advantages in recruiting and retaining top talent over those that don’t. Still, you can take it too far. And I did.\",\"index\":933,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Here are three examples of the smartest people in the company being the worst employees.\",\"index\":934,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In business, intelligence is essential due to the complexity of our work and the highly skilled competition. However, it's not the only critical quality—hard work, reliability, and teamwork are equally important. When I was a CEO, I had to learn the hard way that creating an environment where brilliant people from all backgrounds could thrive was crucial, and I succeeded in that. Companies that foster such diversity have significant advantages in recruiting and retaining top talent. But you can overdo it, as I did. Let me illustrate this with three examples of the smartest employees being the worst performers.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**EXAMPLE 1: THE HERETIC**\",\"index\":935,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Any sizable company produces some number of strategies, projects, processes, promotions, and other activities that don’t make sense. No large organization achieves perfection. As a result, a company needs lots of smart, super-engaged employees who can identify its particular weaknesses and help it improve them.\",\"index\":936,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"However, sometimes a really smart employee develops an agenda other than improving the company. Rather than identifying weaknesses so that he can fix them, he looks for faults to build his case. Specifically, he builds his case that the company is hopeless and run by a bunch of morons. The smarter the employee, the more destructive this type of behavior can be. Simply put, it takes a really smart person to be maximally destructive, because otherwise nobody else will listen to him.\",\"index\":937,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Why would a smart person try to destroy the company that he works for? There are actually many reasons. Here are a few:\",\"index\":938,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** *She is disempowered.* She feels that she cannot access the people in charge and, as a result, complaining is her only vehicle to get the truth out.\",\"index\":939,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** *She is fundamentally a rebel.* She will not be happy unless she is rebelling; this can be a deep personality trait. Sometimes these people actually make better CEOs than employees.\",\"index\":940,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** *She is immature and naive.* She cannot comprehend that the people running the company do not know every minute detail of the operation and therefore they are complicit in everything that’s broken.\",\"index\":941,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Why would a smart person try to destroy the company that he works for? There are actually many reasons. Here are a few: \\n\\n **1.** *She is disempowered.* She feels that she cannot access the people in charge and, as a result, complaining is her only vehicle to get the truth out. \\n\\n **2.** *She is fundamentally a rebel.* She will not be happy unless she is rebelling; this can be a deep personality trait. Sometimes these people actually make better CEOs than employees. \\n\\n **3.** *She is immature and naive.* She cannot comprehend that the people running the company do not know every minute detail of the operation and therefore they are complicit in everything that’s broken.\"},{\"content\":\"Often, it’s very difficult to turn these kinds of cases around. Once an employee takes a public stance, the social pressure for him to be consistent is enormous. If he tells fifty of his closest friends that the CEO is the stupidest person on the planet, then reversing that position will cost him a great amount of credibility the next time he complains. Most people are not willing to take the hit to their credibility.\",\"index\":942,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In any sizable company, there's always room for improvement across strategies, projects, and processes, necessitating smart, engaged employees to identify and address weaknesses. However, sometimes smart employees develop agendas that are counterproductive, focusing on highlighting faults to depict the company as hopeless and poorly managed. Such behavior is particularly destructive because intelligent critiques often gain more attention. A smart employee might act this way due to feelings of disempowerment, a rebellious personality, or immaturity and naivety, which can lead them to wrongly assume that management is aware of, yet ignoring, all operational flaws. Turning these situations around is challenging; once an employee publicly criticizes, the social pressure to maintain that stance for credibility purposes is substantial, deterring them from reversing their position.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**EXAMPLE 2: THE FLAKE**\",\"index\":943,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Some brilliant people can be totally unreliable. At Opsware, we once hired an unequivocal genius—Arthur (not his real name) was an engineer in an area of the product where a typical new hire would take three months to become fully productive. Arthur got fully up to speed in two days. On his third day, we gave him a project that was scheduled to take one month. Arthur completed the project in three days with nearly flawless quality. More specifically, he completed the project in seventy-two hours. Seventy-two nonstop hours: No stops, no sleep, no nothing but coding. In his first quarter on the job, he was the best employee that we had and we immediately promoted him.\",\"index\":944,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Then Arthur changed. He would miss days of work without calling in. Then he would miss weeks of work. When he finally showed up, he apologized profusely, but the behavior didn’t stop. His work product also degraded. He became sloppy and unfocused. I could not understand how such a stellar employee could go so haywire. His manager wanted to fire him, because the team could no longer count on Arthur for anything. I resisted. I knew that the genius was still in him and I wanted us to find it. We never did. It turned out that Arthur was bipolar and had two significant drug problems: (1) He did not like taking his bipolar medication and (2) he was addicted to cocaine. Ultimately, we had to fire Arthur, but even now, it pains me to think about what might have been.\",\"index\":945,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"One need not be bipolar to be a flake, but flaky behavior often has a seriously problematic root cause. Causes range from self-destructive streaks to drug habits to moonlighting for other employers. A company is a team effort and, no matter how high an employee’s potential, you cannot get value from him unless he does his work in a manner in which he can be relied upon.\",\"index\":946,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Some brilliant people can be totally unreliable. At Opsware, we hired a genius engineer, Arthur (not his real name), who got fully up to speed in just two days and completed a month-long project in seventy-two continuous hours, making him our best employee in his first quarter. However, Arthur's behavior changed; he began missing days and weeks of work without notice, and his performance deteriorated. Despite his initial brilliance, Arthur's unreliability stemmed from being bipolar and addicted to cocaine. Ultimately, we had to fire him, a decision that still pains me due to his untapped potential. Flaky behavior often has deep-rooted issues, and while a company thrives on team effort, no employee’s potential can be realized if they are not dependable.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**EXAMPLE 3: THE JERK**\",\"index\":947,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"This particular smart-bad-employee type can occur anywhere in the organization but is most destructive at the executive level. Most executives can be pricks, dicks, a-holes, or a variety of other profane nouns at times. Being dramatically impolite can be used to improve clarity or emphasize an important lesson. That’s not the behavior that I am talking about.\",\"index\":948,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When used consistently, asinine behavior can be crippling. As a company grows, its biggest challenge always becomes communication. Keeping a huge number of people on the same page executing the same goals is never easy. If a member of your staff is a raging jerk, it may be impossible. Some people are so belligerent in their communication style that people just stop talking when they are in the room. If every time anyone brings up an issue with the marketing organization, the VP of marketing jumps down their throats, then guess what topic will never come up? This behavior can become so bad that nobody brings up any topic when the jerk is in the room. As a result, communication across the executive staff breaks down and the entire company slowly degenerates. Note that this only happens if the jerk in question is unquestionably brilliant. Otherwise, nobody will care when she attacks them. The bite only has impact if it comes from a big dog. If one of your big dogs destroys communication on your staff, you need to send her to the pound.\",\"index\":949,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"This smart-but-bad employee type can surface anywhere in the organization but is most damaging at the executive level. While most executives can occasionally be difficult or rude to make a point, I'm talking about consistent, crippling behavior. As a company grows, communication becomes its biggest challenge. Keeping a large group aligned on the same goals is tough, and an overly belligerent staff member can make it impossible. If someone like a VP of marketing reacts aggressively to concerns, people will avoid discussing key issues. This leads to a breakdown in communication and, over time, the entire company will suffer. This only becomes a problem if the jerk is exceptionally brilliant, since their attacks carry weight. If one of your top executives is destroying communication, it's time to let them go.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHEN DO YOU HOLD THE BUS?**\",\"index\":950,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The great football coach John Madden was once asked whether he would tolerate a player like Terrell Owens on his team. Owens was both one of the most talented players in the game and one of the biggest jerks. Madden answered, “If you hold the bus for everyone on the team, then you’ll be so late you’ll miss the game, so you can’t do that. The bus must leave on time. However, sometimes you’ll have a player that’s so good that you hold the bus for him, but only him.”\",\"index\":951,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Phil Jackson, the coach who has won the most NBA championships, was once asked about his famously flaky superstar Dennis Rodman, “Since Dennis Rodman is allowed to miss practice, does this mean other star players like Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen can miss practice, too?” Jackson replied, “Of course not. There is only room for one Dennis Rodman on this team. In fact, you really can only have a very few Dennis Rodmans in society as a whole; otherwise, we would degenerate into anarchy.”\",\"index\":952,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"You may find yourself with an employee who fits one of the above descriptions but nonetheless makes a massive positive contribution to the company. You may decide that you will personally mitigate the employee’s negative attributes and keep her from polluting the overall company culture. That’s fine, but remember: You can only hold the bus for her.\",\"index\":953,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":954,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":955,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"John Madden once responded to whether he'd tolerate a player like Terrell Owens by saying, “If you hold the bus for everyone, you’ll miss the game. But sometimes a player is so good you hold the bus for him, but only him.” Similarly, Phil Jackson, when asked about Dennis Rodman’s allowances, said, “Of course not. There is only room for one Dennis Rodman. You can only have very few Rodmans in society; otherwise, we'd degenerate into anarchy.” If you have an employee who fits these descriptions but makes a significant positive contribution, you may decide to manage their negative attributes. However, remember: you can only hold the bus for her.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"In any sizable company, improvement across strategies, projects, and processes requires smart, engaged employees to identify and address weaknesses. However, some intelligent individuals may focus on highlighting faults to depict the company as hopeless, often due to feelings of disempowerment, rebelliousness, or immaturity. This public criticism can lead to significant social pressure to maintain their stance, making it challenging to reverse. Instances like this are damaging, especially at the executive level, as they hinder communication and alignment on company goals. An example from Opsware involved a genius engineer, Arthur, whose initial brilliance was overshadowed by unreliability due to bipolar disorder and cocaine addiction, eventually leading to his dismissal despite his potential. This \\\"smart-but-bad\\\" employee can surface anywhere in the organization but is most harmful at the executive level, where poor behavior from someone exceptionally brilliant can destroy company communication. Legendary coaches John Madden and Phil Jackson recognized that while you might hold the bus for a standout individual, excessive tolerance can lead to broader issues. In essence, you may choose to manage their negative attributes if their contribution is significant, but remember, you can only hold the bus for her.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"In any sizable company, improvement across strategies, projects, and processes requires smart, engaged employees to identify and address weaknesses. However, some intelligent individuals may focus on highlighting faults to depict the company as hopeless, often due to feelings of disempowerment, rebelliousness, or immaturity. This public criticism can lead to significant social pressure to maintain their stance, making it challenging to reverse. Instances like this are damaging, especially at the executive level, as they hinder communication and alignment on company goals. An example from Opsware involved a genius engineer, Arthur, whose initial brilliance was overshadowed by unreliability due to bipolar disorder and cocaine addiction, eventually leading to his dismissal despite his potential. This \\\"smart-but-bad\\\" employee can surface anywhere in the organization but is most harmful at the executive level, where poor behavior from someone exceptionally brilliant can destroy company communication. Legendary coaches John Madden and Phil Jackson recognized that while you might hold the bus for a standout individual, excessive tolerance can lead to broader issues. In essence, you may choose to manage their negative attributes if their contribution is significant, but remember, you can only hold the bus for her.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[OLD PEOPLE]()**\",\"index\":956,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Your startup is going well and as your business expands you hear the dreaded words from someone on your board: “You need to hire some senior people. Some real ‘been there, done that’ executives to help you get the company to the next level.” Really? Is now the time? If so, where do I begin? And once I get them, what do I do with them? And how will I know if they are doing a good job?\",\"index\":957,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The first question you might ask is “Why do I need senior people at all? Won’t they just ruin the culture with their fancy clothes, political ambitions, and need to go home to see their families?” To some extent, the answer to all of those may be “yes,” which is why this question must be taken quite seriously. However, bringing in the right kind of experience at the right time can mean the difference between bankruptcy and glory.\",\"index\":958,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Let’s go back to the first part of the question. Why hire a senior person? The short answer is *time*. As a technology startup, from the day you start until your last breath, you will be in a furious race against time. No technology startup has a long shelf life. Even the best ideas become terrible ideas after a certain age. How would Facebook go if Zuckerberg started it last week? At Netscape, we went public when we were fifteen months old. Had we started six months later, we would have been late to a market with thirty-seven other browser companies. Even if nobody beats you to the punch, no matter how beautiful your dream most employees will lose faith after the first five or six years of not achieving it. Hiring someone who has already done what you are trying to do can radically speed up your time to success.\",\"index\":959,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"But CEO, beware: Hiring senior people into a startup is kind of like an athlete taking performance-enhancing drugs. If all goes well, you will achieve incredible new heights. If all goes wrong, you will start degenerating from the inside out.\",\"index\":960,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In order to make all go well, if you are considering hiring a senior person do not chase an abstract rationale like “adult supervision” or “becoming a real company.” A weak definition of what you are looking for will lead to a bad outcome. The proper reason to hire a senior person is *to acquire knowledge and experience in a specific area*.\",\"index\":961,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For example, as a technical founder, you probably do not have terrific knowledge of how to build a worldwide sales channel, how to create an invincible brand, or how to identify and negotiate ecosystem-altering business development deals. Acquiring a world-class senior person can dramatically accelerate your company’s ability to succeed in these areas.\",\"index\":962,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"One good test for determining whether to go with outside experience versus internal promotion is to figure out whether you value inside knowledge or outside knowledge more for the position. For example, for engineering managers the comprehensive knowledge of the code base and engineering team is usually more important and difficult to acquire than knowledge of how to run scalable engineering organizations. As a result, you might very well value the knowledge of your own organization more than that of the outside world.\",\"index\":963,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In hiring someone to sell your product to large enterprises, the opposite is true. Knowing how your target customers think and operate, knowing their cultural tendencies, understanding how to recruit and measure the right people in the right regions of the world to maximize your sales—these things turn out to be far more valuable than knowing your own company’s product and culture. This is why when the head of engineering gets promoted from within, she often succeeds. When the head of sales gets promoted from within, she almost always fails. Asking yourself, “Do I value internal or external knowledge more for this position?” will help you determine whether to go for experience or youth.\",\"index\":964,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As your startup grows, hiring senior executives might seem like a smart move, but it’s crucial to assess the timing and actual need. Senior hires can save you valuable time, especially in the fast-paced tech startup environment where speed and sustained employee belief in the vision are paramount. Experienced executives can navigate challenges swiftly, boosting success, but hiring them comes with risks, akin to performance-enhancing drugs in sports: potentially elevating your company or causing internal issues if mishandled. To avoid pitfalls, hire for specific expertise—like building a global sales channel or creating a strong brand—rather than vague reasons like \\\"adult supervision.\\\" Evaluate if the role's success depends more on internal company knowledge or external industry insights. For roles requiring intimate knowledge of target customers, cultural nuances, and regional recruitment, external knowledge often trumps internal familiarity. Thus, promoted heads of engineering frequently succeed, while promoted heads of sales often falter. Ask yourself, “Do I value internal or external knowledge more for this role?” to determine whether to prioritize experience or youth.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**ONCE THEY ARRIVE**\",\"index\":965,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Bringing senior people on board can be fraught with peril, as I have outlined in the sections “Why It’s Hard to Bring Big Company Execs into Little Companies” and “Hiring Executives: If You’ve Never Done the Job, How Do You Hire Somebody Good?” (see pages 119 and 124)*.*\",\"index\":966,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Equally difficult is managing them effectively once they come on board. Senior people pose several important challenges:\",\"index\":967,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *They come with their own culture.* They will bring the habits, the communication style, and values from the company they grew up in. It’s very unlikely these will match your environment exactly.\\n\\n* *They will know how to work the system.* Because senior people come from larger environments, they usually develop the skills to navigate and be effective in those environments. These skills may seem political and unusual in your environment.\\n\\n* *You don’t know the job as well as they do.* In fact, you are hiring them precisely because you don’t know how to do the job. So how do you hold them accountable for doing a good job?\",\"index\":968,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In order to prevent the internal degeneration mentioned earlier, it’s important to be aware of the above issues and then employ appropriate countermeasures to make sure they don’t metastasize.\",\"index\":969,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"First, you should demand cultural compliance. It’s fine that people come from other company cultures. It’s true that some of those cultures will have properties that are superior to your own. But this is your company, your culture, and your way of doing business. Do not be intimidated by experience on this issue; stick to your guns and stick to your culture. If you want to expand your culture to incorporate some of the new thinking, that’s fine, but do so explicitly—do not drift. Next, watch for politically motivated tactics and do not tolerate them.\",\"index\":970,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Perhaps most important, set a high and clear standard for performance. If you want to have a world-class company, you must make sure that the people on your staff—be they young or old—are world-class. It is not nearly enough that someone on your staff can do the job better than you can, because you are incompetent at the job—that’s why you hired them in the first place.\",\"index\":971,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Be careful not to set a low bar because you have not done the work to know what good is. For example, I’ve seen many a young CEO excited about her company’s competency in marketing and PR because she got a bunch of positive stories on her launch. That’s not a high PR standard. Anybody can get reporters to write nice things about a sweet, cuddly baby of a company. Only world-class PR people can deal with gangly, pimple-ridden, teenage companies. World-class PR people can turn around negative stories. World-class PR people can turn chicken shit into chicken salad. Turning chicken shit into chicken salad requires long-term, trusted relationships, deep know-how, and the confidence to make use of both appropriately. PR kids don’t have any of the three.\",\"index\":972,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"One excellent way to develop a high standard is to interview people who you see doing a great job in their field. Find out what their standard is and add it to your own. Once you determine a high yet achievable performance bar, hold your executive to that high standard even if you have no idea how they might achieve it. It’s not your job to figure out how to create an incredible brand, tilt the playing field by cutting a transformational deal, or achieve a sales goal that nobody thought possible—that’s what you are paying them to do. That’s why you hired them.\",\"index\":973,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Finally, you’ll need your new executive to be more than just a goal achiever. She will need to be well rounded and part of the team. Bill Campbell developed an excellent methodology for measuring executives in a balanced way that will help you achieve this. He breaks performance down into four distinct areas:\",\"index\":974,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** **Results against objectives** Once you’ve set a high standard, it will be straightforward to measure your executive against that standard.\",\"index\":975,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** **Management** Even if an executive does a superb job achieving her goals, that doesn’t mean she is building a strong and loyal team. It’s important to understand how well she is managing, even if she is hitting her goals.\",\"index\":976,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** **Innovation** It’s quite possible for an executive to hit her goal for the quarter by ignoring the future. For example, a great way for an engineering manager to hit her goals for features and dates is by building a horrible architecture, which won’t even support the next release. This is why you must look beyond the black-box results and into the sausage factory to see how things get made.\",\"index\":977,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**4.** **Working with peers** This may not be intuitive at first, but executives must be effective at communicating, supporting, and getting what they need from the other people on your staff. Evaluate them along this dimension.\",\"index\":978,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Finally, you’ll need your new executive to be more than just a goal achiever. She will need to be well rounded and part of the team. Bill Campbell developed an excellent methodology for measuring executives in a balanced way that will help you achieve this. He breaks performance down into four distinct areas: \\n\\n **1.** **Results against objectives** Once you’ve set a high standard, it will be straightforward to measure your executive against that standard. \\n\\n **2.** **Management** Even if an executive does a superb job achieving her goals, that doesn’t mean she is building a strong and loyal team. It’s important to understand how well she is managing, even if she is hitting her goals. \\n\\n **3.** **Innovation** It’s quite possible for an executive to hit her goal for the quarter by ignoring the future. For example, a great way for an engineering manager to hit her goals for features and dates is by building a horrible architecture, which won’t even support the next release. This is why you must look beyond the black-box results and into the sausage factory to see how things get made. \\n\\n **4.** **Working with peers** This may not be intuitive at first, but executives must be effective at communicating, supporting, and getting what they need from the other people on your staff. Evaluate them along this dimension.\"}],\"summary\":\"Hiring senior executives presents unique challenges, especially when bringing big company professionals into smaller organizations. These individuals come with ingrained cultures and can navigate large systems adeptly, sometimes appearing overly political. Because you're hiring them for their expertise, holding them accountable can be daunting. To address these issues, enforce strict cultural compliance and be wary of political maneuvers. Crucially, set high performance standards to maintain a top-tier team, avoiding the temptation to lower expectations due to your unfamiliarity with their role. World-class performance, such as in PR, involves more than just positive press—it's about crisis management and relationship building. To establish a high benchmark, learn from top industry professionals and apply their standards. Hold your executive to these ambitious goals, understanding their role is to achieve the exceptional. Ensure they are not only goal-oriented but also team players, by evaluating them on four fronts: delivering results, effective management, driving innovation, and working well with peers.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**AW, MAN, YOU SOLD YOUR SOUL**\",\"index\":979,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Hiring the first senior people into your company may feel like selling your soul, and if you are not careful, you may well end up selling the soul of your company. But if you want to make something from nothing, you have to take risks and you have to win your race against time. This means acquiring the very best talent, knowledge, and experience even if it requires dealing with some serious age diversity.\",\"index\":980,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":981,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":982,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Hiring the first senior people into your company can feel like selling your soul, and without caution, you might end up selling the soul of your company too. However, if you aim to create something from nothing, you need to take risks and beat the clock. This involves securing top-tier talent, knowledge, and experience, even if it means navigating significant age diversity.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Hiring senior executives from big companies into smaller organizations poses unique challenges due to ingrained cultures and adeptness in navigating large systems, sometimes appearing overly political. To address this, enforce strict cultural compliance and be vigilant against political maneuvers. Set high performance standards, avoiding the temptation to lower expectations due to unfamiliarity with the role. Aim for world-class performance in areas like PR, which involves crisis management and relationship building, by learning from top industry professionals and holding your executive to these high standards. Evaluate them on delivering results, effective management, driving innovation, and working well with peers. While hiring your first senior executives can feel like selling your soul, risking the company’s ethos, it’s essential to take these risks to create something significant. This includes securing top-tier talent despite significant age diversity, ensuring you beat the clock and build a high-performing team.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Hiring senior executives from big companies into smaller organizations poses unique challenges due to ingrained cultures and adeptness in navigating large systems, sometimes appearing overly political. To address this, enforce strict cultural compliance and be vigilant against political maneuvers. Set high performance standards, avoiding the temptation to lower expectations due to unfamiliarity with the role. Aim for world-class performance in areas like PR, which involves crisis management and relationship building, by learning from top industry professionals and holding your executive to these high standards. Evaluate them on delivering results, effective management, driving innovation, and working well with peers. While hiring your first senior executives can feel like selling your soul, risking the company’s ethos, it’s essential to take these risks to create something significant. This includes securing top-tier talent despite significant age diversity, ensuring you beat the clock and build a high-performing team.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[ONE-ON-ONE]()**\",\"index\":983,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"After I first wrote about one-on-ones, people flooded me with feedback about one-on-ones. About half the responders chastised me, saying that one-on-ones were useless and that I shouldn’t put so much emphasis on them. The other half wanted to know how to run more effective one-on-ones. It seems to me that both groups are likely talking about two sides of the same coin.\",\"index\":984,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Perhaps the CEO’s most important operational responsibility is designing and implementing the communication architecture for her company. The architecture might include the organizational design, meetings, processes, email, yammer, and even one-on-one meetings with managers and employees. Absent a well-designed communication architecture, information and ideas will stagnate, and your company will degenerate into a bad place to work. While it is quite possible to design a great communication architecture without one-on-one meetings, in most cases one-on-ones provide an excellent mechanism for information and ideas to flow up the organization and should be part of your design.\",\"index\":985,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Generally, people who think one-on-one meetings are a bad idea have been victims of poorly designed ones. The key to a good one-on-one meeting is the understanding that it is the *employee’s* meeting rather than the manager’s meeting. This is the free-form meeting for all the pressing issues, brilliant ideas, and chronic frustrations that do not fit neatly into status reports, email, and other less personal and intimate mechanisms.\",\"index\":986,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you are an employee, how do you get feedback from your manager on an exciting but only 20 percent formed idea that you’re not sure is relevant, without sounding like a fool? How do you point out that a colleague you do not know how to work with is blocking your progress without throwing her under the bus? How do you get help when you love your job but your personal life is melting down? Through a status report? On email? Yammer? Asana? Really? For these and other important areas of discussions, one-on-ones can be essential.\",\"index\":987,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you like structured agendas, then the employee should set the agenda. A good practice is to have the employee send you the agenda in advance. This will give her a chance to cancel the meeting if nothing is pressing. It also makes clear that it is her meeting and will take as much or as little time as she needs. During the meeting, since it’s the employee’s meeting, the manager should do 10 percent of the talking and 90 percent of the listening. Note that this is the opposite of most one-on-ones.\",\"index\":988,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"While it’s not the manager’s job to set the agenda or do the talking, the manager should try to draw the key issues out of the employee. The more introverted the employee, the more important this becomes. If you manage engineers, drawing out issues will be an important skill to master.\",\"index\":989,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Some questions that I’ve found to be very effective in one-on-ones:\",\"index\":990,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* If we could improve in any way, how would we do it?\\n\\n* What’s the number-one problem with our organization? Why?\\n\\n* What’s not fun about working here?\\n\\n* Who is really kicking ass in the company? Whom do you admire?\\n\\n* If you were me, what changes would you make?\\n\\n* What don’t you like about the product?\\n\\n* What’s the biggest opportunity that we’re missing out on?\\n\\n* What are we not doing that we should be doing?\\n\\n* Are you happy working here?\",\"index\":991,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the end, the most important thing is that the best ideas, the biggest problems, and the most intense employee life issues make their way to the people who can deal with them. One-on-ones are a time-tested way to do that, but if you have a better one, go ahead with your bad self.\",\"index\":992,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":993,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":994,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When I first discussed one-on-ones, feedback was polarized—some found them pointless, while others wanted to enhance their effectiveness. This highlights their dual potential to either improve or hinder communication. As a CEO, crafting a well-structured communication system, including one-on-ones, is essential. Mismanagement typically undermines these meetings; they should be the employee's platform to discuss issues, share undeveloped ideas, seek help with colleague challenges, or address personal matters affecting work. If you prefer structure, let the employee set and share the agenda in advance and allow them to cancel if unnecessary. Managers should primarily listen, creating a comfortable space for employees, especially introverts, to raise important topics. Mastering this balance is crucial, particularly when managing engineers. Key questions to ask during one-on-ones include:\\n\\n- If we could improve in any way, how would we do it?\\n- What’s the number-one problem with our organization? Why?\\n- What’s not fun about working here?\\n- Who is really kicking ass in the company? Whom do you admire?\\n- If you were me, what changes would you make?\\n- What don’t you like about the product?\\n- What’s the biggest opportunity that we’re missing out on?\\n- What are we not doing that we should be doing?\\n- Are you happy working here?\\n\\nThe goal is to ensure that the best ideas and the most pressing issues reach the right people who can address them, making one-on-ones a proven tool for this purpose. Feel free to use a better approach if you have one.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[PROGRAMMING YOUR CULTURE]()**\",\"index\":995,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Ask ten founders about company culture and what it means and you’ll get ten different answers. It’s about office design, it’s about screening out the wrong kinds of employees, it’s about values, it’s about fun, it’s about alignment, it’s about finding like-minded employees, it’s about being cultlike.\",\"index\":996,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"So what is culture? Does culture matter? If so, how much time should you spend on it?\",\"index\":997,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Let’s start with the second question first. The primary thing that any technology startup must do is build a product that’s at least ten times better at doing something than the current prevailing way of doing that thing. Two or three times better will not be good enough to get people to switch to the new thing fast enough or in large enough volume to matter. The second thing that any technology startup must do is to *take the market*. If it’s possible to do something ten times better, it’s also possible that you won’t be the only company to figure that out. Therefore, you must take the market before somebody else does. Very few products are ten times better than the competition’s, so unseating the *new* incumbent is much more difficult than unseating the old one.\",\"index\":998,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you fail to do both of those things, your culture won’t matter one bit. The world is full of bankrupt companies with world-class cultures. Culture does not make a company.\",\"index\":999,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"So, why bother with culture at all? Three reasons:\",\"index\":1000,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** It matters to the extent that it can help you achieve the above goals.\",\"index\":1001,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** As your company grows, culture can help you preserve your key values, make your company a better place to work, and help it perform better in the future.\",\"index\":1002,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** Perhaps most important, after you and your people go through the inhuman amount of work that it will take to build a successful company, it will be an epic tragedy if your company culture is such that even you don’t want to work there.\",\"index\":1003,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"So, why bother with culture at all? Three reasons: \\n\\n **1.** It matters to the extent that it can help you achieve the above goals. \\n\\n **2.** As your company grows, culture can help you preserve your key values, make your company a better place to work, and help it perform better in the future. \\n\\n **3.** Perhaps most important, after you and your people go through the inhuman amount of work that it will take to build a successful company, it will be an epic tragedy if your company culture is such that even you don’t want to work there.\"}],\"summary\":\"Ask ten founders about company culture and you’ll get ten different answers: office design, screening out the wrong kinds of employees, values, fun, alignment, finding like-minded employees, even being cultlike. \\n\\nSo, what is culture, and does it matter? Critically, any technology startup must first build a product that’s ten times better than the existing solution to rapidly gain adoption. Secondly, it must take the market quickly, as competition is inevitable. Without achieving these goals, culture is irrelevant—many bankrupt companies had world-class cultures. Culture matters because it helps achieve these goals, preserves core values, enhances the workplace as your company scales, and prevents the tragic outcome of creating a successful business where even you don't want to work.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**CREATING A COMPANY CULTURE**\",\"index\":1004,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When I refer to company culture, I am not referring to other important activities like company values and employee satisfaction. Specifically, I am writing about designing a way of working that will:\",\"index\":1005,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Distinguish you from competitors\\n\\n* Ensure that critical operating values persist such as *delighting* *customers* or *making beautiful products*\\n\\n* Help you identify employees who fit with your mission\",\"index\":1006,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Culture means lots of other things in other contexts, but the above will be plenty to discuss here.\",\"index\":1007,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When you start implementing your culture, keep in mind that most of what will be retrospectively referred to as your company’s culture will not have been designed into the system, but rather will have evolved over time based on your behavior and the behavior of your early employees. As a result, you will want to focus on a small number of cultural design points that will influence a large number of behaviors over a long period of time.\",\"index\":1008,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In his bestselling book *Built to Last*, Jim Collins wrote that one of the things that long-lasting companies he studied have in common is a “cult-like culture.” I found this description to be confusing because it seems to imply that as long as your culture is weird enough and you are rabid enough about it, you will succeed on the cultural front.\",\"index\":1009,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"That’s related to the truth, but not actually true. In reality, Collins was right that a properly designed culture often ends up looking cultlike in retrospect, but that’s not the initial design principle. You needn’t think hard about how you can make your company seem bizarre to outsiders. However, you do need to think about how you can be provocative enough to change what people do every day.\",\"index\":1010,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ideally, a cultural design point will be trivial to implement but have far-reaching behavioral consequences. Key to this kind of mechanism is shock value. If you put something into your culture that is so disturbing that it always creates a conversation, it will change behavior. As we learned in *The Godfather*, ask a Hollywood mogul to give someone a job and he might not respond. Put a horse’s head in his bed and unemployment will drop by one. Shock is a great mechanism for behavioral change.\",\"index\":1011,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Here are three examples:\",\"index\":1012,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**Desks made out of doors** Very early on, Jeff Bezos, founder and CEO of Amazon.com, envisioned a company that made money by delivering value *to* rather than extracting value *from* its customers. In order to do that, he wanted to be both the price leader and customer service leader for the long run. You can’t do that if you waste a lot of money. Jeff could have spent years auditing every expense and raining hell on anybody who overspent, but he decided to build frugality into his culture. He did it with an incredibly simple mechanism: All desks at Amazon.com for all time would be built by buying cheap doors from Home Depot and nailing legs to them. These door desks are not great ergonomically, nor do they fit with Amazon.com’s $150 billion–plus market capitalization, but when a shocked new employee asks why she must work on a makeshift desk constructed out of random Home Depot parts, the answer comes back with withering consistency: “We look for every opportunity to save money so that we can deliver the best products for the lowest cost.” If you don’t like sitting at a door, then you won’t last long at Amazon.\",\"index\":1013,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**Ten dollars per minute** When we started Andreessen Horowitz, Marc and I wanted the firm to treat entrepreneurs with great respect. We remembered how psychologically brutal the process of building a company was. We wanted the firm to respect the fact that in the bacon-and-egg breakfast of a startup, we were with the chicken and the entrepreneur was the pig: We were involved, but she was committed. We thought that one way to communicate respect would be to always be on time to meetings with entrepreneurs. Rather than make them wait in our lobby for thirty minutes while we attended to more important business like so many venture capitalists that we visited, we wanted our people to be on time, prepared, and focused. Unfortunately, anyone who has ever worked anywhere knows that this is easier said than done. In order to shock the company into the right behavior, we instituted a ruthlessly enforced ten-dollar-per-minute fine for being late to a meeting with an entrepreneur. So, for example: You are on a really important call and will be ten minutes late? No problem, just bring one hundred dollars to the meeting and pay your fine. When new employees come on board, they find this shocking, which gives us a great opportunity to explain in detail why we respect entrepreneurs. If you don’t think entrepreneurs are more important than venture capitalists, we can’t use you at Andreessen Horowitz.\",\"index\":1014,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**Move fast and break things** Mark Zuckerberg believes in innovation and he believes there can be no great innovation without great risk. So, in the early days of Facebook, he deployed a shocking motto: *Move fast and break things.* Did the CEO really want us to break things? I mean, he’s telling us to break things! A motto that shocking forces everyone to stop and think. When they think, they realize that if you move fast and innovate, you will break things. If you ask yourself, “Should I attempt this breakthrough? It will be awesome, but it may cause problems in the short term,” you have your answer. If you’d rather be right than innovative, you won’t fit in at Facebook.\",\"index\":1015,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Here are three examples: \\n\\n **Desks made out of doors** Very early on, Jeff Bezos, founder and CEO of Amazon.com, envisioned a company that made money by delivering value *to* rather than extracting value *from* its customers. In order to do that, he wanted to be both the price leader and customer service leader for the long run. You can’t do that if you waste a lot of money. Jeff could have spent years auditing every expense and raining hell on anybody who overspent, but he decided to build frugality into his culture. He did it with an incredibly simple mechanism: All desks at Amazon.com for all time would be built by buying cheap doors from Home Depot and nailing legs to them. These door desks are not great ergonomically, nor do they fit with Amazon.com’s $150 billion–plus market capitalization, but when a shocked new employee asks why she must work on a makeshift desk constructed out of random Home Depot parts, the answer comes back with withering consistency: “We look for every opportunity to save money so that we can deliver the best products for the lowest cost.” If you don’t like sitting at a door, then you won’t last long at Amazon. \\n\\n **Ten dollars per minute** When we started Andreessen Horowitz, Marc and I wanted the firm to treat entrepreneurs with great respect. We remembered how psychologically brutal the process of building a company was. We wanted the firm to respect the fact that in the bacon-and-egg breakfast of a startup, we were with the chicken and the entrepreneur was the pig: We were involved, but she was committed. We thought that one way to communicate respect would be to always be on time to meetings with entrepreneurs. Rather than make them wait in our lobby for thirty minutes while we attended to more important business like so many venture capitalists that we visited, we wanted our people to be on time, prepared, and focused. Unfortunately, anyone who has ever worked anywhere knows that this is easier said than done. In order to shock the company into the right behavior, we instituted a ruthlessly enforced ten-dollar-per-minute fine for being late to a meeting with an entrepreneur. So, for example: You are on a really important call and will be ten minutes late? No problem, just bring one hundred dollars to the meeting and pay your fine. When new employees come on board, they find this shocking, which gives us a great opportunity to explain in detail why we respect entrepreneurs. If you don’t think entrepreneurs are more important than venture capitalists, we can’t use you at Andreessen Horowitz. \\n\\n **Move fast and break things** Mark Zuckerberg believes in innovation and he believes there can be no great innovation without great risk. So, in the early days of Facebook, he deployed a shocking motto: *Move fast and break things.* Did the CEO really want us to break things? I mean, he’s telling us to break things! A motto that shocking forces everyone to stop and think. When they think, they realize that if you move fast and innovate, you will break things. If you ask yourself, “Should I attempt this breakthrough? It will be awesome, but it may cause problems in the short term,” you have your answer. If you’d rather be right than innovative, you won’t fit in at Facebook.\"},{\"content\":\"Prior to figuring out the exact form of your company’s shock therapy, be sure that your mechanism agrees with your values. For example, Jack Dorsey will never make his own desks out of doors at Square because at Square, beautiful design trumps frugality. When you walk into Square, you can feel how seriously they take design.\",\"index\":1016,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When discussing company culture, I refer to creating a unique work environment that differentiates you from competitors, upholds core values such as customer delight and product beauty, and helps identify employees who align with your mission. Culture naturally evolves from the behaviors of founders and early employees, and impactful cultural points can shape ongoing behavior. Jim Collins in _Built to Last_ suggests that successful companies have a \\\"cult-like culture,\\\" which isn’t about bizarreness but rather driving daily behavior changes. Effective cultural points should be simple yet bring significant shifts, often through shock value. For instance, Jeff Bezos instilled frugality at Amazon by using door desks to convey cost-saving for customer benefit. At Andreessen Horowitz, employees are fined ten dollars per minute for being late to meetings with entrepreneurs, stressing punctuality and respect. Mark Zuckerberg’s \\\"Move fast and break things\\\" at Facebook promotes innovation over caution. When designing your culture, ensure the shock aligns with your values—like Jack Dorsey's focus on design excellence at Square, where makeshift desks would be inappropriate.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHY DOGS AT WORK AND YOGA AREN’T CULTURE**\",\"index\":1017,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Startups today do all kinds of things to distinguish themselves. Many great, many original, many quirky, but most of them will not define the company’s culture. Yes, yoga may make your company a better place to work for people who like yoga. It may also be a great team-building exercise for people who like yoga. Nonetheless, it’s not culture. It will not establish a core value that drives the business and helps promote it in perpetuity. It is not specific with respect to what your business aims to achieve. Yoga is a perk.\",\"index\":1018,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Somebody keeping a pit bull in her cube may be shocking. The lesson learned—that animal lovers are welcome or that employees can live however they want—may provide some societal value, but it does not connect to your business in a distinguishing way. Every smart company values its employees. Perks are good, but they are not culture.\",\"index\":1019,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Startups today try various things to stand out, from great and original ideas to quirky tactics, but most of these efforts won't define the company's culture. Take yoga, for instance—it may improve the workplace for yoga enthusiasts and serve as a team-building exercise, but it doesn’t establish a core business value or perpetuate its goals. Yoga is simply a perk. Similarly, allowing someone to keep a pit bull in her cube might be surprising and suggest that animal lovers or individual lifestyles are welcome, but this doesn’t uniquely connect to the business's distinguishing attributes. Valuing employees is a given for any smart company. Ultimately, perks are beneficial, but they do not equate to culture.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE POINT OF IT ALL**\",\"index\":1020,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the later section “How to Evaluate CEOs” (see page 235), I describe the CEO job as knowing what to do and getting the company to do what you want. Designing a proper company culture will help you get your company to do what you want in certain important areas for a very long time.\",\"index\":1021,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1022,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1023,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"In the \\\"How to Evaluate CEOs\\\" section (page 235), I explain that a CEO's job boils down to knowing what to do and ensuring the company executes it effectively. By designing a robust company culture, you can steer your company to achieve your goals consistently over the long term in critical areas.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"When discussing company culture, I emphasize creating a distinctive work environment that sets you apart from competitors. This involves upholding core values like customer delight and product beauty and helps in identifying employees aligned with your mission. Culture organically stems from the founders' and early employees' behaviors, influencing ongoing company actions. According to Jim Collins in _Built to Last_, successful companies have a \\\"cult-like culture,\\\" not one of oddity but one that changes daily behaviors. Effective cultural points should be simple yet impactful, often using shock value, like Jeff Bezos's door desks to highlight frugality or Andreessen Horowitz fining employees for being late to stress punctuality. Mark Zuckerberg’s \\\"Move fast and break things\\\" at Facebook fosters innovation. When shaping your culture, ensure the shock aligns with your values, such as Jack Dorsey's emphasis on design excellence at Square. Startups may employ various methods to stand out, but not all will define their core culture. For example, offering yoga or allowing pets at work are perks, not cultural foundations. Valuing employees is standard for any competent company but doesn't define culture. Ultimately, a CEO's role, as I discuss on page 235 