, then at some point you have to scale. People in startup land often talk about the magic of how few people built the original Google or the original Facebook, but today’s Google employs twenty thousand people and today’s Facebook employs more than fifteen hundred people. So, if you want to do something that matters, then you are going to have to learn the black art of scaling a human organization.\",\"index\":1025,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Often board members give entrepreneurs two bits of advice regarding scale:\",\"index\":1026,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** Get a mentor.\",\"index\":1027,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Find some “been there, done that” executives who already know how to scale.\",\"index\":1028,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Often board members give entrepreneurs two bits of advice regarding scale: \\n\\n **1.** Get a mentor. \\n\\n **2.** Find some “been there, done that” executives who already know how to scale.\"},{\"content\":\"These answers, while fine as far as they go, have some important limitations. First, if you don’t know anything about scaling an organization, then it will be very difficult for you to evaluate people for that job. Imagine trying to find a killer engineer if you’d never written a single program. Second, many investor-board members don’t know anything about scaling a company, either, and can be suckers for people who have the experience but not the skills. If you’ve ever worked in a large organization, you know that there are plenty of people with experience running them but none of the requisite skills to run them well.\",\"index\":1029,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"This advice is still good, but the right way to pick both the best mentors and best employees is by first learning the basics; then you can apply the myriad of scaling techniques in the management literature depending on the context.\",\"index\":1030,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"If you want to build an important company, you must eventually scale. While it's inspiring to hear how a few people built the original Google or Facebook, today's Google and Facebook employ thousands. To create something significant, you need to master the intricate process of scaling a human organization. Board members often advise entrepreneurs to get a mentor and hire experienced executives who know how to scale. However, these suggestions have limitations. If you lack knowledge about scaling, evaluating potential hires becomes challenging, akin to finding a top engineer without programming experience. Many investor-board members may also lack scaling insight and can be misled by experienced yet unskilled individuals. The advice is still valuable, but the key is first learning the basics of scaling yourself. This foundation enables you to discern the best mentors and employees, and apply various scaling techniques effectively from management literature.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE BASIC IDEA: GIVE GROUND GRUDGINGLY**\",\"index\":1031,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"When an organization grows in size, things that were previously easy become difficult. Specifically, the following things that cause no trouble when you are small become big challenges as you grow:\",\"index\":1032,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* Communication\\n\\n* Common knowledge\\n\\n* Decision making\",\"index\":1033,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"When an organization grows in size, things that were previously easy become difficult. Specifically, the following things that cause no trouble when you are small become big challenges as you grow: \\n\\n * Communication\\n\\n* Common knowledge\\n\\n* Decision making\"},{\"content\":\"In order to get a clear understanding of the problem, let’s start with the boundary condition. Imagine a company of one employee. That employee writes and tests all the code, does all the marketing and sales, and manages herself. She has complete knowledge of everything in the company, makes all the decisions, needn’t communicate with anyone, and is totally aligned with herself. As the company grows, things will only get worse in each dimension.\",\"index\":1034,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"On the other hand, if the company doesn’t expand, then it will never be much of a company, so the challenge is to grow but degrade as slowly as possible.\",\"index\":1035,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"There is a great analogue to this concept in American football. An offensive lineman’s job is to protect the quarterback from onrushing defensive linemen. If the offensive lineman attempts to do this by holding his ground, the defensive lineman will easily run around him and crush the quarterback. As a result, offensive linemen are taught to lose the battle slowly or *to give ground grudgingly*. They are taught to back up and allow the defensive lineman to advance, but just a little at a time.\",\"index\":1036,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When you scale an organization, you will also need to give ground grudgingly. Specialization, organizational structure, and process all complicate things and implementing them will feel like you are moving away from common knowledge and quality communication. It is very much like the offensive lineman taking a step backward. You will lose ground, but you will prevent your company from descending into chaos.\",\"index\":1037,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As an organization grows, challenges like communication, common knowledge, and decision-making, which are straightforward when the company is small, become increasingly complex. For instance, in a one-employee company, the individual manages everything seamlessly without the need for communication or alignment issues. However, as the company expands, these aspects worsen, though without expansion, it remains limited in scope. The goal is to grow while minimizing these difficulties. This concept is akin to an offensive lineman in American football who is trained to \\\"give ground grudgingly\\\" to protect the quarterback, allowing the opponent to advance slowly rather than quickly overrunning them. Similarly, as a company scales, embracing specialization, organizational structure, and process can feel like losing ground in terms of knowledge and communication, yet this careful retreat prevents chaos and sustains growth.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**HOW TO DO IT**\",\"index\":1038,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At the point when adding people into the company feels like more work than the work that you can offload to the new employees, the defensive lineman has run around you and you probably need to start giving ground grudgingly.\",\"index\":1039,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"At the point when adding people into the company feels like more work than the work that you can offload to the new employees, the defensive lineman has run around you and you probably need to start giving ground grudgingly.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SPECIALIZATION**\",\"index\":1040,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The first scale technique to implement is specialization. In startups, everybody starts out as a jack-of-all-trades. For example, engineers write code, manage the build system, test the product, and, increasingly, deploy it and operate it. This works well in the beginning because everybody knows everything and the need to communicate is minimized; there are no complicated handoffs, because there is nobody to hand anything to. As the company grows, it becomes increasingly difficult to add new engineers, because the learning curve starts to get super-steep. Getting a new engineer up to speed starts to become more difficult than doing the work yourself. At this point, you need to specialize.\",\"index\":1041,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"By dedicating people and teams to such tasks as the build environment, the test environment, and operations, you will create some complexity—handoffs across groups, potentially conflicting agendas, and specialized rather than common knowledge. In order to mitigate these issues, you will need to consider other scale techniques like *organizational design* and *process*.\",\"index\":1042,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The first scale technique to implement in a growing startup is specialization. Initially, everyone operates as a jack-of-all-trades—engineers write code, manage the build system, test the product, and handle deployment and operations. This works well when the team is small, as communication is straightforward and there are no handoffs. However, as the company expands, the learning curve for new engineers becomes steep, making it harder to onboard them than to do the work directly. At this growth stage, it's essential to start specializing. Dedicate teams to specific tasks like the build environment, testing, and operations. While this introduces complexity through handoffs, conflicting agendas, and specialized versus common knowledge, it can be managed by incorporating other scale techniques such as organizational design and process improvements.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**ORGANIZATIONAL DESIGN**\",\"index\":1043,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The first rule of organizational design is that all organizational designs are bad. With any design, you will optimize communication among some parts of the organization at the expense of other parts. For example, if you put product management in the engineering organization, you will optimize communication between product management and engineering at the expense of communication between product management and marketing. As a result, as soon as you roll out the new organization, people will find fault with it and they will be right.\",\"index\":1044,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Nonetheless, at some point the monolithic design of one huge organization runs out of gas and you will need to split things into smaller subgroups. At the most basic level, you’ll want to consider giving the groups that you’ve specialized their own managers as they grow. You may want a QA manager, for example. After that, things become more complex. Do client engineering and server engineering have their own groups or do you organize by use cases and include all technical components? When you get really big, you’ll need to decide whether to organize the entire company around functions (for example, sales, marketing, product management, engineering) or around missions—self-contained business units that contain multiple functions.\",\"index\":1045,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Your goal is to choose the least of all evils. Think of the organizational design as the communications architecture for your company. If you want people to communicate, the best way to accomplish that is to make them report to the same manager. By contrast, the further away people are in the organizational chart, the less they will communicate. The organizational design is also the architecture for how the company communicates with the outside world. For example, you might want to organize your sales force by product to maximize communication with the relevant product groups and maximize the product competency of the sales force. If you do that, then you will do so at the expense of simplicity for customers who buy multiple products and will now have to deal with multiple salespeople.\",\"index\":1046,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"With this in mind, here are the basic steps to organizational design:\",\"index\":1047,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** *Figure out what needs to be communicated.* Start by listing the most important knowledge and who needs to have it. For example, knowledge of the product architecture must be understood by engineering, QA, product management, marketing, and sales.\",\"index\":1048,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** *Figure out what needs to be decided.* Consider the types of decisions that must get made on a frequent basis: feature selection, architectural decisions, how to resolve support issues. How can you design the organization to put the maximum number of decisions under the domain of a designated manager?\",\"index\":1049,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** *Prioritize the most important communication and decision paths.* Is it more important for product managers to understand the product architecture or the market? Is it more important for engineers to understand the customer or the architecture? Keep in mind that these priorities will be based on today’s situation. If the situation changes, then you can reorganize.\",\"index\":1050,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**4.** *Decide who’s going to run each group.* Notice that this is the fourth step, not the first. You want to optimize the organization for the people—for the people doing the work—not for the managers. Most large mistakes in organizational design come from putting the individual ambitions of the people at the top of the organization ahead of the communication paths for the people at the bottom of the organization. Making this step four will upset your managers, but they will get over it.\",\"index\":1051,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**5.** *Identify the paths that you did not optimize.* As important as picking the communication paths that you will optimize is identifying the ones that you will not. Just because you deprioritized them doesn’t mean they are unimportant. If you ignore them entirely, they will surely come back to bite you.\",\"index\":1052,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**6.** *Build a plan for mitigating the issues identified in step five.* Once you’ve identified the likely issues, you will know the processes you will need to build to patch the impending cross-organizational challenges.\",\"index\":1053,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"With this in mind, here are the basic steps to organizational design: \\n\\n **1.** *Figure out what needs to be communicated.* Start by listing the most important knowledge and who needs to have it. For example, knowledge of the product architecture must be understood by engineering, QA, product management, marketing, and sales. \\n\\n **2.** *Figure out what needs to be decided.* Consider the types of decisions that must get made on a frequent basis: feature selection, architectural decisions, how to resolve support issues. How can you design the organization to put the maximum number of decisions under the domain of a designated manager? \\n\\n **3.** *Prioritize the most important communication and decision paths.* Is it more important for product managers to understand the product architecture or the market? Is it more important for engineers to understand the customer or the architecture? Keep in mind that these priorities will be based on today’s situation. If the situation changes, then you can reorganize. \\n\\n **4.** *Decide who’s going to run each group.* Notice that this is the fourth step, not the first. You want to optimize the organization for the people—for the people doing the work—not for the managers. Most large mistakes in organizational design come from putting the individual ambitions of the people at the top of the organization ahead of the communication paths for the people at the bottom of the organization. Making this step four will upset your managers, but they will get over it. \\n\\n **5.** *Identify the paths that you did not optimize.* As important as picking the communication paths that you will optimize is identifying the ones that you will not. Just because you deprioritized them doesn’t mean they are unimportant. If you ignore them entirely, they will surely come back to bite you. \\n\\n **6.** *Build a plan for mitigating the issues identified in step five.* Once you’ve identified the likely issues, you will know the processes you will need to build to patch the impending cross-organizational challenges.\"},{\"content\":\"These six steps should get you pretty far. When we examine advanced organizational design, we’ll also need to consider trade-offs such as speed versus cost, how to roll out organizational changes, and how often you should reorganize.\",\"index\":1054,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The first rule of organizational design is that all designs are inherently flawed, as optimizing communication for one part of the organization invariably comes at the expense of another. This reality necessitates breaking down large monolithic structures into specialized subgroups with their own managers as they grow. You’ll need to make crucial decisions on whether to organize by function or mission, aiming to minimize communication barriers by having people report to the same manager. Organizational design dictates both internal and external communication, such as organizing a sales force by product to maximize synergy with product groups, albeit at the cost of customer simplicity.\\n\\nTo tackle organizational design, follow these steps: \\n\\n1. Determine what essential knowledge needs to be communicated and to whom.\\n2. Identify frequent decision-making processes and how to align them under designated managers.\\n3. Prioritize critical communication and decision pathways based on current needs.\\n4. Decide on group leadership after setting communication paths, focusing on those doing the work rather than managerial ambitions.\\n5. Recognize and address the communication paths you deprioritize to prevent future issues.\\n6. Develop plans to mitigate cross-organizational challenges identified in the previous step.\\n\\nThese guidelines will help you manage many of the inherent issues in organizational design, with advanced considerations including speed versus cost and the frequency of reorganizations for future discussions.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**PROCESS**\",\"index\":1055,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The purpose of process is communication. If there are five people in your company, you don’t need process, because you can just talk to each other. You can hand off tasks with a perfect understanding of what’s expected, you pass important information from one person to another, and you can maintain high-quality transactions with no bureaucratic overhead. With four thousand people, communication becomes more difficult. Ad hoc, point-to-point communication no longer works. You need something more robust—a communication bus or, to use the conventional term for human communication buses, a process.\",\"index\":1056,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A process is a formal, well-structured communication vehicle. It can be a heavily engineered Six Sigma process or it can be a well-structured regular meeting. The size of the process should be scaled up or down to meet the needs of the communication challenge that it facilitates.\",\"index\":1057,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When communication in an organization spans across organizational boundaries, processes will help ensure that the communication happens and that it happens with quality. If you are looking for the first process to implement in your company, consider the interview process. It usually runs across organizational boundaries (the hiring group, human resources—or wherever the recruiter lives, and supporting groups), involves people from outside the company (the candidate), and is critically important to the success of the company.\",\"index\":1058,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Who should design a process? The people who are already doing the work in an ad hoc manner. They know what needs to be communicated and to whom. Naturally they will be the right group to formalize the existing process and make it scalable.\",\"index\":1059,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When should you start implementing processes? While that varies depending on your situation, keep in mind that it’s much easier to add new people to old processes than new processes to old people. Formalize what you are doing to make it easy to onboard new people.\",\"index\":1060,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Much has been written about process design, so I won’t repeat that here. I have found the “The Basics of Production,” the first chapter of Andy Grove’s *High Output Management*, to be particularly helpful. For new companies, here are a few things to keep in mind:\",\"index\":1061,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Focus on the output first.* What should the process produce? In the case of the interview process, an outstanding employee. If that’s the goal, what’s the process to get there?\\n\\n* *Figure out how you’ll know if you are getting what you want at each step.* Are you getting enough candidates? Are you getting the right candidates? Will your interview process find the right person for the job? Once you select the person, will they accept the job? Once they accept the job, will they become productive? Once they become productive, will they stay with your company? How will you measure each step?\\n\\n* *Engineer accountability into the system.* Which organization and which individual is responsible for each step? What can you do to increase the visibility of their performance?\",\"index\":1062,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Much has been written about process design, so I won’t repeat that here. I have found the “The Basics of Production,” the first chapter of Andy Grove’s *High Output Management*, to be particularly helpful. For new companies, here are a few things to keep in mind: \\n\\n * *Focus on the output first.* What should the process produce? In the case of the interview process, an outstanding employee. If that’s the goal, what’s the process to get there?\\n\\n* *Figure out how you’ll know if you are getting what you want at each step.* Are you getting enough candidates? Are you getting the right candidates? Will your interview process find the right person for the job? Once you select the person, will they accept the job? Once they accept the job, will they become productive? Once they become productive, will they stay with your company? How will you measure each step?\\n\\n* *Engineer accountability into the system.* Which organization and which individual is responsible for each step? What can you do to increase the visibility of their performance?\"}],\"summary\":\"The purpose of process is communication. With a small team of five, you can handle tasks and information flow directly without formal procedures. But with four thousand people, effective communication requires a robust system—a process. Processes are structured communication channels, ranging from Six Sigma methodologies to well-organized meetings, and should be scaled according to the communication needs. They ensure quality communication across organizational boundaries, crucial for tasks like the interview process, which involves multiple departments and external candidates. Processes should be designed by those currently performing the tasks, as they understand the communication needs best. Start implementing processes early, as it’s easier to introduce new people into existing processes. Focus first on what the process should produce, measure each step's effectiveness, and build in accountability, making sure each step is clearly assigned and performance is visible. For more on process design, Andy Grove’s *High Output Management* offers valuable insights.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FINAL THOUGHT**\",\"index\":1063,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The process of scaling a company is not unlike the process of scaling a product. Different sizes of company impose different requirements on the company’s architecture. If you address those requirements too early, your company will seem heavy and sluggish. If you address those requirements too late, your company may melt down under the pressure. Be mindful of your company’s true growth rate as you add architectural components. It’s good to anticipate growth, but it’s bad to overanticipate growth.\",\"index\":1064,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1065,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1066,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Scaling a company mirrors scaling a product, with each stage of growth imposing specific architectural needs. Addressing these needs prematurely can make the company feel cumbersome, while addressing them too late can cause operational collapse. As you add required components, remain mindful of your company's actual growth rate. Anticipating growth is wise, but overanticipating can be detrimental.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As your organization grows, challenges in communication, common knowledge, and decision-making become more complex, similar to an offensive lineman in football who must \\\"give ground grudgingly.\\\" Initially, everyone wears many hats, but as onboarding becomes tougher, specialization is essential. This introduces complexity but prevents chaos and fosters growth. The first rule of organizational design acknowledges inherent flaws; optimizing one part often compromises another, so breaking down large structures into specialized subgroups with managers is crucial. Steps include prioritizing essential knowledge communication, aligning decision-making under managers, and recognizing deprioritized communication paths. Processes, key to structured communication, scale with your team size to ensure quality across departments. Start early, focus on outcomes, measure effectiveness, and maintain accountability. As your company grows, balance timely architectural needs to avoid operational collapse while avoiding premature over-structuring.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As your organization grows, challenges in communication, common knowledge, and decision-making become more complex, similar to an offensive lineman in football who must \\\"give ground grudgingly.\\\" Initially, everyone wears many hats, but as onboarding becomes tougher, specialization is essential. This introduces complexity but prevents chaos and fosters growth. The first rule of organizational design acknowledges inherent flaws; optimizing one part often compromises another, so breaking down large structures into specialized subgroups with managers is crucial. Steps include prioritizing essential knowledge communication, aligning decision-making under managers, and recognizing deprioritized communication paths. Processes, key to structured communication, scale with your team size to ensure quality across departments. Start early, focus on outcomes, measure effectiveness, and maintain accountability. As your company grows, balance timely architectural needs to avoid operational collapse while avoiding premature over-structuring.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[THE SCALE ANTICIPATION FALLACY]()**\",\"index\":1067,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The other day I was talking to a couple of friends of mine, one a VC and the other a CEO. During the meeting, we discussed one of the executives at the CEO’s company. The executive in question performs exceptionally but lacks experience managing at larger scale. My friend the VC innocently advised the CEO to carefully consider whether the executive would scale to meet the company’s needs in the future. I responded swiftly, aggressively, and loudly, saying, “That’s a horrible idea and makes no sense at all.” Both of my friends were startled at my outburst. Normally I am disciplined enough to refrain from letting my feelings pass straight through my mouth without stopping at my brain for review. Why the outburst? Here is my answer.\",\"index\":1068,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As CEO, you must constantly evaluate all the members of your team. However, evaluating people against the future needs of the company based on a theoretical view of how they will perform is counterproductive, for the following reasons:\",\"index\":1069,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* *Managing at scale is a learned skill rather than a natural ability.* Nobody comes out of the womb knowing how to manage a thousand people. Everybody learns at some point.\\n\\n* *It’s nearly impossible to make the judgment in advance.* How do you tell in advance if an executive can scale? Was it obvious that Bill Gates would learn how to scale when he was a Harvard dropout? How do you go about making that decision?\\n\\n* *The act of judging people in advance will retard their development.* If you make a judgment that someone is incapable of doing something such as running a larger organization, will it make sense to teach them those skills or even point out the anticipated deficiencies? Probably not. You’ve already decided they can’t do it.\\n\\n* *Hiring scalable execs too early is a bad mistake.* There is no such thing as a great executive. There is only a great executive for a specific company at a specific point in time. Mark Zuckerberg is a phenomenal CEO for Facebook. He would not be a good CEO for Oracle. Similarly, Larry Ellison does a terrific job at Oracle but he would not be the right person to manage Facebook. If you judge your team in advance and have a high sense of urgency, you will bring in executives who can manage at high scale in advance of needing them. Unfortunately, you will probably ignore their ability to do the job for the next twelve months, which is the only relevant measure. As a result, you will swap out good executives for worse ones.\\n\\n* *You still have to make the judgment at the actual point in time when you hit the higher level of scale.* Even if you avoid the trap of hiring a scalable executive too early or retarding the new executive’s development, you still haven’t actually bought yourself anything by making the prejudgment. Regardless of what you decided at point in time A, you still have to evaluate the situation with far better data at point in time B.\\n\\n* *It’s no way to live your life or run an organization.* Deciding (with woefully incomplete data) that someone who works their butt off, does a terrific job, and loyally contributes to your mission won’t be with you three years from now takes you to a dark place. It’s a place of information hiding, dishonesty, and stilted communication. It’s a place where prejudice substitutes for judgment. It’s a place where judgment replaces teaching. It’s a place where teamwork becomes internal warfare. Don’t go there.\\\\\\n        So, if you don’t prejudge people’s ability to scale, how do you make the judgment? You should evaluate your team at least once a quarter on all dimensions. Two keys can help you avoid the scale anticipation trap:\\n\\n* *Don’t separate scale from the rest of the evaluation.* The relevant question isn’t whether an executive can scale; it’s whether the executive can do the job at the current scale. You should evaluate holistically and this will prevent you from separating out scale, which often leads to an unwise prediction of future performance.\\n\\n* *Make the judgment on a relative rather than an absolute scale.* Asking yourself whether an executive is great can be extremely difficult to answer. A better question: For this company at this exact point in time, does there exist an executive who I can hire who will be better? If my biggest competitor hires that person, how will that impact our ability to win?\\\\\\n       Predicting whether an executive can scale corrupts your ability to manage, is unfair, and doesn’t work.\",\"index\":1070,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The other day, I had a discussion with a VC and a CEO friend regarding an executive at the CEO’s company. Despite the executive's exceptional performance, the VC voiced concerns about their ability to manage at a larger scale. I responded harshly, arguing that it’s counterproductive to evaluate people based on theoretical future performance for several reasons: managing at scale is a learned skill; it’s almost impossible to judge this ability in advance; prejudging can hinder an executive’s development; hiring scalable execs too early can be disastrous; eventual judgment is still required at the actual point of scaling; and it fosters a toxic environment. Instead, CEOs should evaluate their team quarterly, focusing on current performance rather than future scaling abilities, and make comparisons relative to the current needs of the company. Predicting an executive’s scalability corrupts management practices, is unjust, and is ineffective.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, navigating executive compensation and career development is key to fostering a productive and fair work environment. Awarding raises based on market value rather than merit can create resentment and political behavior, leading to non-performance-based raises. To combat this, hire individuals whose ambitions align with the company's success and establish strict, clear processes for evaluations and promotions. During job interviews, prioritize team-oriented candidates who focus on the company's goals, much like the successful hiring of Mark Cranney at Opsware. Clear job titles and disciplined promotion processes prevent competence deterioration and ensure fairness. Intelligent employees should focus on improvements rather than fault-finding, especially at the executive level. When hiring senior executives from larger companies, enforce cultural compliance and high performance standards to avoid political behavior. Balancing age diversity and securing top-tier talent is essential for long-term success. Effective one-on-ones are crucial; they should be employee-driven, allowing them to set the agenda and providing a comfortable space to raise important topics. Focus on creating a distinct company culture with core values reflecting the founder's behaviors, not superficial perks. As the company grows, break down large structures into specialized subgroups, communicate essential knowledge, and ensure decision-making aligns with managerial responsibilities. Finally, evaluate teams quarterly based on current performance, avoiding premature judgments on scalability to foster growth and avoid a toxic environment.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, navigating executive compensation and career development is key to fostering a productive and fair work environment. Awarding raises based on market value rather than merit can create resentment and political behavior, leading to non-performance-based raises. To combat this, hire individuals whose ambitions align with the company's success and establish strict, clear processes for evaluations and promotions. During job interviews, prioritize team-oriented candidates who focus on the company's goals, much like the successful hiring of Mark Cranney at Opsware. Clear job titles and disciplined promotion processes prevent competence deterioration and ensure fairness. Intelligent employees should focus on improvements rather than fault-finding, especially at the executive level. When hiring senior executives from larger companies, enforce cultural compliance and high performance standards to avoid political behavior. Balancing age diversity and securing top-tier talent is essential for long-term success. Effective one-on-ones are crucial; they should be employee-driven, allowing them to set the agenda and providing a comfortable space to raise important topics. Focus on creating a distinct company culture with core values reflecting the founder's behaviors, not superficial perks. As the company grows, break down large structures into specialized subgroups, communicate essential knowledge, and ensure decision-making aligns with managerial responsibilities. Finally, evaluate teams quarterly based on current performance, avoiding premature judgments on scalability to foster growth and avoid a toxic environment.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[— CHAPTER 7 —]()**\",\"index\":1071,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**[HOW TO LEAD EVEN WHEN YOU DON’T KNOW WHERE YOU ARE GOING]()**\",\"index\":1072,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**[— CHAPTER 7 —]()** \\n\\n **[HOW TO LEAD EVEN WHEN YOU DON’T KNOW WHERE YOU ARE GOING]()**\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“This for every ghetto in the hood\",\"index\":1073,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Nas the Don, Super Cat the Don Dada, understood.”\",\"index\":1074,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**—NAS, “THE DON”**\",\"index\":1075,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“This for every ghetto in the hood \\n\\n Nas the Don, Super Cat the Don Dada, understood.” \\n\\n **—NAS, “THE DON”**\"},{\"content\":\"**A**fter selling the Loudcloud business to EDS, we immediately plunged into a new crisis. Our investors could not understand how selling all of our revenue and all of our customers could possibly leave us with anything worth investing in. As a result, institutional investors sold all of their Opsware shares, and our stock price fell to $0.35 per share. This turned out to be a noteworthy price, because it computed to a market capitalization equal to half of the cash we had in the bank. This signaled that investors believed that the Opsware business had no value, and they further expected us to burn up half our cash before coming to our senses and returning the cash to investors. To make matters more miserable, I received a notice from NASDAQ informing me that if I did not get our stock price above $1 within the next ninety days, they would delist us and we would trade with the penny stocks.\",\"index\":1076,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I brought this cheery news to the board with three options:\",\"index\":1077,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**1.** *Reverse split.* We could reverse split the stock 10:1 and have ten times fewer shares and a ten times higher stock price.\",\"index\":1078,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** *Give in.* We could become a penny stock.\",\"index\":1079,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** *Hit the road.* I could go on the road and try to get enough people to buy so that the stock price would triple.\",\"index\":1080,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"**1.** *Reverse split.* We could reverse split the stock 10:1 and have ten times fewer shares and a 