e in the world. The conference is invitation-only and consistently attracts guests whom you will never find at any other conference. People like Bill Gates, Warren Buffett, and Rupert Murdoch are regulars. Allen & Company may attract more top-tier guests than all other business conferences combined—it’s that good.\",\"index\":1084,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Marc and I arrived at the Allen & Company office in Manhattan, located in the Coca-Cola building where Herb’s father, Herbert, had served on the board of directors for many years. If a single word could describe the Allen & Company office it would be *classy*. Beautifully decorated, yet not flashy, the office was both elegant and comfortable.\",\"index\":1085,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Like his office, Herb himself was both unassuming and classy. He opened the meeting by complimenting Ron, saying that any referral from Ron was personally important to him. Marc and I then carefully took Herb through the story of Loudcloud—how we had sold the services business to EDS, retaining the software and the key people, and had secured a $20 million a year software license. Beyond that, we had a totally clean balance sheet and were surely worth more than $0.35 per share. Herb listened attentively to the entire presentation and then said, “I’d like to be helpful. I’ll see what I can do.” I had no idea if he meant, as many in Silicon Valley would mean, “Screw off, I’m not buying a penny stock” or if he meant what he’d said. I soon found out.\",\"index\":1086,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Over the next couple of months, Allen & Company bought Opsware stock, Herb Allen personally bought Opsware stock, and several Allen & Company clients became major investors. This activity propelled the stock from $0.35 to $3 per share in a matter of months. We’d avoided delisting, rebuilt the shareholder base, and given employees hope. Everything was largely due to a single meeting with Herb Allen.\",\"index\":1087,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Years later I asked Herb why he believed in our company at a time when nobody else did. I pointed out that, at the time, Allen & Company wasn’t very involved in technology, let alone data center automation. Herb replied, “I didn’t understand anything about your business and I understood very little about your industry. What I saw was two guys come visit me when every other public company CEO and chairman was hiding under their desk. Not only did you come see me, but you were more determined and convinced you would succeed than guys running giant businesses. Investing in courage and determination was an easy decision for me.”\",\"index\":1088,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"That’s how Herb Allen does business. And that’s why, if given the chance, you’d be a fool not to do business with Herb.\",\"index\":1089,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1090,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**P**erhaps the most important thing that I learned as an entrepreneur was to focus on what I needed to get right and stop worrying about all the things that I did wrong or might do wrong. This section encapsulates the various parts of those lessons and provides guidance on how to get the important things right.\",\"index\":1091,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1092,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1093,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"After selling the Loudcloud business to EDS, our investors couldn’t see the value in remaining Opsware, leading to institutional investors dumping shares and driving our stock price down to $0.35 per share. This indicated a market cap worth half our bank cash, implying investors believed we would burn cash without generating value. Additionally, NASDAQ threatened to delist us unless our stock price exceeded $1 within ninety days. I presented the board with three options: reverse stock split, become a penny stock, or rally buyers to boost the stock price. The board discussed all options, with Andy noting reduced stigma around reverse splits and Marc suggesting delisting might be less critical in a digital era. However, I opposed a reverse split, seeing it as a sign of weakness, and aimed to avoid delisting, knowing it would restrict institutional investment. Marc and I sought advice from Ron Conway, leading us to meet Herb Allen of Allen & Company, who, despite limited industry knowledge, decided to help. His investments and those from Allen & Company clients propelled our stock to $3 per share in months, keeping us listed and rebuilding our shareholder base while reigniting employee hope. Herb’s belief in our courage underscored an essential lesson for entrepreneurs: prioritize what needs to go right over fears of potential mistakes.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[THE MOST DIFFICULT CEO SKILL]()**\",\"index\":1094,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"By far the most difficult skill I learned as CEO was the ability to manage my own psychology. Organizational design, process design, metrics, hiring, and firing were all relatively straightforward skills to master compared with keeping my mind in check. I thought I was tough going into it, but I wasn’t tough. I was soft.\",\"index\":1095,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Over the years, I’ve spoken to hundreds of CEOs, all with the same experience. Nonetheless, very few people talk about it and I have never read anything on the topic. It’s like the fight club of management: The first rule of the CEO psychological meltdown is don’t talk about the psychological meltdown.\",\"index\":1096,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\