running a company. This means that you will face a broad set of things that you don’t know how to do that require skills you don’t have. Nevertheless, everybody will expect you to know how to do them, because, well, you are the CEO. I remember when I first became CEO, an investor asked me to send him the “cap table.” I had a vague idea of what he meant, but I didn’t actually know what the format was supposed to look like or what should be included or excluded. It was a silly little thing and I had much bigger things to worry about, but everything is hard when you don’t actually know what you are doing. I wasted quite a bit of time sweating over that stupid spreadsheet.\",\"index\":1100,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Even if you know what you are doing, things go wrong. Things go wrong because building a multifaceted human organization to compete and win in a dynamic, highly competitive market turns out to be really hard. If CEOs were graded on a curve, the mean on the test would be 22 out of 100. This kind of mean can be psychologically challenging for a straight-A student. It is particularly challenging because nobody tells you that the mean is 22.\",\"index\":1101,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you manage a team of ten people, it’s quite possible to do so with very few mistakes or bad behaviors. If you manage an organization of one thousand people, it is quite impossible. At a certain size, your company will do things that are so bad that you never imagined that you’d be associated with that kind of incompetence. Seeing people fritter away money, waste each other’s time, and do sloppy work can make you feel bad. If you are the CEO, it may well make you sick.\",\"index\":1102,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"And to rub salt into the wound and make matters worse, it’s your fault.\",\"index\":1103,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"To become a CEO, one must possess a high sense of purpose and exceptional abilities, attracting people to work for her. Although nobody aims to be a poor CEO or run a dysfunctional organization, the journey is fraught with inevitable mistakes. The unique challenge of being a CEO is that the role itself is the only real training for the job; no prior experience can truly prepare you. As a new CEO, I remember grappling with a request for a \\\"cap table,\\\" something I vaguely understood but didn't know how to execute, wasting time on it despite more pressing issues. Even seasoned CEOs face failures because leading a complex organization in a competitive market is incredibly tough. If CEOs were graded, they’d score around 22 out of 100, which can be demoralizing. Managing larger teams introduces unavoidable mistakes and incompetency, leading to feelings of guilt and frustration since, ultimately, the CEO is responsible for everything that goes wrong.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**NOBODY TO BLAME**\",\"index\":1104,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"“You can’t blame Jazz musicians\",\"index\":1105,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"or David Stern with his NBA fashion issues.”\",\"index\":1106,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**—NAS, “HIP HOP IS DEAD”**\",\"index\":1107,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"“You can’t blame Jazz musicians \\n\\n or David Stern with his NBA fashion issues.” \\n\\n **—NAS, “HIP HOP IS DEAD”**\"},{\"content\":\"When people in my company would complain about one thing or another being broken, such as the expense reporting process, I would joke that it was all my fault. The joke was funny, because it wasn’t really a joke. Every problem in the company was indeed my fault. As the founding CEO, every hire and every decision that the company ever made happened under my direction. Unlike a hired gun who comes in and blames all of the problems on the prior regime, there was literally nobody for me to blame.\",\"index\":1108,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If someone was promoted for all the wrong reasons, that was my fault. If we missed the quarterly earnings target, that was my fault. If a great engineer quit, that was my fault. If the sales team made unreasonable demands on the product organization, that was my fault. If the product had too many bugs, that was my fault. It kind of sucked to be me.\",\"index\":1109,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Being responsible for everything and getting a 22 on the test starts to weigh on your consciousness.\",\"index\":1110,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When people in my company would complain about something being broken, like the expense reporting process, I would joke that it was all my fault. The humor was in its truth because, as the founding CEO, every hire and decision fell under my direction. Unlike a hired leader who can blame the previous regime, I had no one else to blame. If someone was promoted for the wrong reasons, we missed earnings targets, a great engineer quit, the sales team pressured the product organization, or the product had too many bugs—it was all on me. This overwhelming responsibility and constant pressure start to weigh heavily on your conscience, and it kind of sucked to be me.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**TOO MUCH BROKEN STUFF**\",\"index\":1111,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Given this stress, CEOs often make one of the following two mistakes:\",\"index\":1112,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** They take things too personally.\",\"index\":1113,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** They do not take things personally enough.\",\"index\":1114,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Given this stress, CEOs often make one of the following two mistakes: \\n\\n **1.** They take things too personally. \\n\\n **2.** They do not take things personally enough.\"},{\"content\":\"In the first scenario, the CEO takes every issue incredibly seriously and personally and urgently moves to fix it. Given the volume of the issues, this motion usually results in one of two scenarios. If the CEO is outwardly focused, she ends up terrorizing the team to the point where nobody wants to work at the company anymore. If the CEO is inwardly focused, she ends up feeling so sick from all the problems that she can barely make it to work in the morning.\",\"index\":1115,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the second scenario, in order to dampen the pain of the rolling disaster that is the company, the CEO takes a Pollyannaish attitude: It’s not so bad. In this view, none of the problems is actually that bad and they needn’t be dealt with urgently. By rationalizing away the issues, the CEO feels better about herself. The problem is that she doesn’t actually fix any of the problems and the employees eventually become quite frustrated that the chief executive keeps ignoring the most basic problems and conflicts. Ultimately, the company turns to crap.\",\"index\":1116,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ideally, the CEO will be urgent yet not insane. She will move aggressively and decisively without feeling emotionally culpable. If she can separate the importance of the issues from how she feels about them, she will avoid demonizing her employees or herself.\",\"index\":1117,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"CEOs often make one of two critical mistakes when dealing with stress: taking things too personally or not personally enough. In the first scenario, they address every issue urgently and personally, which can either result in a toxic work environment if they're outward-focused, or in personal burnout if they're inward-focused. In the second scenario, they adopt an overly optimistic attitude, downplaying problems and failing to address them, which leads to frustration among employees and eventual company decline. The ideal CEO balances urgency with sanity, tackling issues decisively without emotional attachment, thus avoiding both terrorizing the team and personal distress.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**IT’S A LONELY JOB**\",\"index\":1118,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In your darkest moments as CEO, discussing fundamental questions about the viability of your company with your employees can have obvious negative consequences. On the other hand, talking to your board and outside advisers can be fruitless. The knowledge gap between you and them is so vast that you cannot actually bring them fully up to speed in a manner that’s useful in making the decision. You are all alone.\",\"index\":1119,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"At Loudcloud, when the dot-com bubble burst and subsequently sent most of our customers into bankruptcy, it crippled our business and devastated our balance sheet. Or rather, that was one interpretation. Another interpretation, and necessarily the official story for the company, was that we still had plenty of money in the bank and were signing up traditional enterprise customers at an impressive rate. Which interpretation was closer to the truth? In the absence of someone to talk to, that’s a question that I asked myself about three thousand times. (As an aside, asking oneself anything three thousand times turns out to be a bad idea.) In this case, I had two specific difficult questions:\",\"index\":1120,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** What if the official interpretation was wrong? What if I was misleading everyone from investors to employees? In that case, I should be removed from my position immediately.\",\"index\":1121,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** What if the official interpretation was right? What if I was grinding my brain into sawdust for no reason at all? What if I was taking the company off track by questioning my own direction? In that case, I should be removed from my position immediately.\",\"index\":1122,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"At Loudcloud, when the dot-com bubble burst and subsequently sent most of our customers into bankruptcy, it crippled our business and devastated our balance sheet. Or rather, that was one interpretation. Another interpretation, and necessarily the official story for the company, was that we still had plenty of money in the bank and were signing up traditional enterprise customers at an impressive rate. Which interpretation was closer to the truth? In the absence of someone to talk to, that’s a question that I asked myself about three thousand times. (As an aside, asking oneself anything three thousand times turns out to be a bad idea.) In this case, I had two specific difficult questions: \\n\\n **1.** What if the official interpretation was wrong? What if I was misleading everyone from investors to employees? In that case, I should be removed from my position immediately. \\n\\n **2.** What if the official interpretation was right? What if I was grinding my brain into sawdust for no reason at all? What if I was taking the company off track by questioning my own direction? In that case, I should be removed from my position immediately.\"},{\"content\":\"As is usually the case, there was no way to know which interpretation was right until much later. It turned out that neither was actually right. The new customers didn’t save us, but we figured out another way to survive and ultimately succeed. The key to getting to the right outcome was to keep from getting married to either the positive or the dark narrative.\",\"index\":1123,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"My friend Jason Rosenthal took over as CEO of Ning in 2010. As soon as he became CEO, he faced a cash crisis and had to choose among three difficult choices: (1) radically reduce the size of the company, (2) sell the company, or (3) raise money in a highly dilutive way.\",\"index\":1124,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Think about those choices:\",\"index\":1125,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**1.** Lay off a large set of talented employees whom he worked very hard to recruit and, as a result, likely severely damage the morale of the remaining people.\",\"index\":1126,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**2.** Sell out all of the employees whom he had been working side by side with for the past several years (Jason was promoted into the position) by selling the company without giving them a chance to perform or fulfill their mission.\",\"index\":1127,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"**3.** Drastically reduce the ownership position of the employees and make their hard work economically meaningless.\",\"index\":1128,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"Think about those choices: \\n\\n **1.** Lay off a large set of talented employees whom he worked very hard to recruit and, as a result, likely severely damage the morale of the remaining people. \\n\\n **2.** Sell out all of the employees whom he had been working side by side with for the past several years (Jason was promoted into the position) by selling the company without giving them a chance to perform or fulfill their mission. \\n\\n **3.** Drastically reduce the ownership position of the employees and make their hard work economically meaningless.\"},{\"content\":\"Choices like these cause migraine headaches. Tip to aspiring entrepreneurs: If you don’t like choosing between horrible and cataclysmic, don’t become CEO.\",\"index\":1129,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Jason sought advice from some of the best minds in the industry, but ultimately he was completely alone in the final decision. Nobody had the answer and whatever the answer, Jason was the one who had to live with the consequences. So far his decision to reduce staff by letting go of primarily the most recent hires has paid off. Revenue at Ning is soaring and team morale is high. If it had gone worse (or ultimately goes bad), it would be all Jason’s fault and it would be up to Jason to find a new answer. Whenever I see Jason, I like to say, “Welcome to the show.” Jason eventually sold Ning to Glam and went on to become CEO of Lytro.\",\"index\":1130,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"At times like this, it’s important to understand that nearly every company goes through life-threatening moments. My partner at Andreessen Horowitz, Scott Weiss, relayed that it’s so common that there is an acronym for it, WFIO, which stands for “We’re Fucked, It’s Over” (it’s pronounced “whiff-ee-yo”). As he describes it, every company goes through at least two and up to five of these episodes (although I’m pretty sure that I went through at least a dozen at Opsware). In all cases, WFIOs feel much worse than they are—especially for the CEO.\",\"index\":1131,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, grappling with your company's survival can be harrowing, especially during crises like the dot-com bubble burst we faced at Loudcloud. Despite projecting confidence and securing cash and customers, I endured relentless self-doubt. The real issue was neither overly optimistic nor pessimistic; we found alternative ways to survive. This ambiguity is exemplified by Jason Rosenthal’s tenure at Ning in 2010, where he faced brutal choices like extensive layoffs and possible equity dilution. Seeking advice from industry leaders, he ultimately made the hard decision to cut recent hires, resulting in soaring revenue and team morale. If his decision had failed, it would have been solely his burden. As Scott Weiss of Andreessen Horowitz puts it, these “We’re Fucked, It’s Over” (WFIO) moments, though terrifying, often seem worse than they are, particularly for the CEO.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**TECHNIQUES TO CALM YOUR NERVES**\",\"index\":1132,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The problem with psychology is that everybody’s is different. With that as a caveat, over the years I developed a few techniques for dealing with myself. I hope you find them useful, too.\",\"index\":1133,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"*Make some friends.* Although it’s nearly impossible to get high-quality advice on the tough decisions that you make, it is extremely useful from a psychological perspective to talk to people who have been through similarly challenging decisions.\",\"index\":1134,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"*Get it out of your head and onto paper.* When I had to explain to my board that, since we were a public company, I thought that it would be best if we sold all of our customers and all of our revenue and changed business, it was messing with my mind. In order to finalize that decision, I wrote down a detailed explanation of my logic. The process of writing that document separated me from my own psychology and enabled me to make the decision swiftly.\",\"index\":1135,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"*Focus on the road, not the wall.* When someone learns to drive a race car, one of the first lessons taught is that when you are going around a curve at 200 mph, do not focus on the wall; focus on the road. If you focus on the wall, you will drive right into it. If you focus on the road, you will follow the road. Running a company is like that. There are always a thousand things that can go wrong and sink the ship. If you focus too much on them, you will drive yourself nuts and likely crash your company. Focus on where you are going rather than on what you hope to avoid.\",\"index\":1136,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The problem with psychology is that everyone’s experience is unique, but over the years I've developed a few techniques that might be useful. *Make some friends.* While it’s tough to get high-quality advice on difficult decisions, it’s psychologically beneficial to discuss with people who have faced similar challenges. *Get it out of your head and onto paper.* When faced with explaining a drastic decision to my board, writing a detailed explanation helped clear my mind and finalize the decision. *Focus on the road, not the wall.* In race car driving, focusing on where you want to go rather than the obstacles helps avoid crashes. The same applies to running a company—focusing on your goals rather than the myriad potential problems helps avoid driving yourself nuts and crashing the company.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**DON’T PUNK OUT AND DON’T QUIT**\",\"index\":1137,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As CEO, there will be many times when you feel like quitting. I have seen CEOs try to cope with the stress by drinking heavily, checking out, and even quitting. In each case, the CEO has a marvelous rationalization about why it was okay for him to punk out or quit, but none of them will ever be great CEOs.\",\"index\":1138,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Great CEOs face the pain. They deal with the sleepless nights, the cold sweats, and what my friend the great Alfred Chuang (legendary cofounder and CEO of BEA Systems) calls “the torture.” Whenever I meet a successful CEO, I ask them how they did it. Mediocre CEOs point to their brilliant strategic moves or their intuitive business sense or a variety of othe