ar that it is easier for employees to go to one decision maker than two. It’s not really very complicated at all. Unfortunately, the clear and present social pressure often overwhelms the long-term benefits of organizing the company properly. Because the founders do not have the courage to decide who is in charge, every employee suffers the inconvenience of double approval.\",\"index\":1156,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"More important, decisions only get scarier as a company grows. When we decided to take Loudcloud public with only $2 million in revenue, it was not a hard choice intellectually—the alternative was to go bankrupt. It was nonetheless terrifying to do something that most employees, everyone in the press, and many investors thought was nuts.\",\"index\":1157,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"I tell my kids that the difference between a hero and a coward lies not in their feelings but in their actions. Both experience fear, but the hero pushes through it with discipline, while the coward does not. This idea resonates deeply in the business world. When my partners and I assess entrepreneurs, we seek brilliance and courage. Being a CEO has taught me that courage is often more crucial than intelligence in decision-making. Entrepreneurs frequently falter under social pressure, especially when avoiding tough decisions like establishing clear leadership roles. For instance, when founders pitch us and claim co-leadership, they fail to see the long-term inefficiency it creates. The fear of making difficult decisions doesn't wane as a company grows—it intensifies. An example from my experience is taking Loudcloud public with only $2 million in revenue; it was a rational choice under dire circumstances, yet terrifying due to widespread skepticism.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHEN MAKING THE RIGHT CHOICE REQUIRES INTELLIGENCE AND COURAGE**\",\"index\":1158,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Sometimes the decision itself is rather complicated, which makes the courage challenge even more difficult. CEOs possess a different set of data, knowledge, and perspective than anybody else in the company. Frequently, some of the employees and board members are more experienced and more intelligent than the CEO. The only reason the CEO can make a better decision is her superior knowledge.\",\"index\":1159,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"To make matters worse, when a CEO faces a particularly difficult decision, she may have only a slight preference for one choice over another—say 54 percent kill a product line, 46 percent keep it. If the really smart people on the board and on her staff take the other side, her courage will be severely tested. How can she kill the product when she is not even sure if she is making the right decision and everyone is against her? If she’s wrong, she will have been wrong in the face of advice from her top advisers. If she is right, will anybody even know?\",\"index\":1160,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Recently, a large company offered to buy one of our portfolio companies. The deal was lucrative and compelling given the portfolio company’s progress to date and revenue level. The founder/CEO (I’ll call him Hamlet—not his real name) thought that selling did not make sense due to the giant market opportunity that he was pursuing, but he still wanted to make sure that he made the best possible choice for investors and employees. Hamlet wanted to reject the offer, but only marginally. To complicate matters, most of the management team and the board thought the opposite. It did not help that the board and the management team were far more experienced than Hamlet. As a result, Hamlet spent many sleepless nights worrying about whether he was right. He realized that it was impossible to know. This did not help him sleep. In the end, Hamlet made the best and most courageous decision he could and did not sell the company. I believe that will prove to be the defining moment of his career.\",\"index\":1161,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Interestingly, as soon as Hamlet made the decision, the entire board and executive team immediately embraced the choice. Why? If they wanted to sell the company enough to advise the CEO to give up his dream, how could they reverse themselves so quickly? It turns out that the most important data point driving their earlier preference for selling the company was Hamlet’s initial ambivalence—the team supported the decision they *thought* the CEO wanted. Hamlet did not realize this and interpreted their desire to sell to be the result of a thorough analysis. Luckily for everybody involved, he had the courage to make the right decision.\",\"index\":1162,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The general problem can be seen in the social credit matrix below. The expected social rewards for making the crowd-influenced decision appear better than those for making the decision you think is right:\",\"index\":1163,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1164,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"<table><tbody><tr><td><p>&nbsp;</p></td><td><p><strong>You are right</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>You are wrong</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>You decide against the crowd.</strong></p></td><td><p>Few remember that you made the decision, but the company succeeds.</p></td><td><p>Everybody remembers the decision and you are downgraded, ostracized, or fired.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>You decide with the crowd.</strong></p><p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p></td><td><p>Everyone who advised you remembers the decision and the company succeeds.</p></td><td><p>You receive the minimum blame possible for getting it wrong, but the company suffers.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>\",\"index\":1165,\"type\":\"html\",\"summarizable\":false},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1166,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"On the surface, it appears that if the decision is a close call, it’s much safer to go with the crowd. In reality, if you fall into this trap, the crowd will influence your thinking and make a 70-30 decision seem like a 51-49 decision. This is why courage is critical.\",\"index\":1167,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Sometimes making decisions as a CEO is particularly challenging due to the unique perspective and knowledge they hold, which others in the company may lack. Despite often being surrounded by more experienced and intelligent board members and staff, a CEO's superior knowledge is their key to making better decisions. The difficulty is magnified when decisions have marginal preferences, like a 54-46 split on whether to kill a product line. This dilemma is exacerbated if the CEO's team, advocating the other choice, outnumbers her. Recently, a founder/CEO faced such a situation when deciding whether to sell his rapidly progressing portfolio company. Despite his marginal preference to reject the lucrative offer, most of his more experienced management team and board members favored selling. Hamlet, the pseudonymous CEO, endured sleepless nights but ultimately decided not to sell, a choice that will likely define his career. Interestingly, upon his decision, the board and executive team quickly supported him, revealing that their initial desire to sell was influenced by Hamlet's own ambivalence rather than thorough analysis. This illustrates the importance of courage in decision-making, as following the crowd can obscure genuine preferences and transform a clear decision into a contentious one.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**COURAGE, LIKE CHARACTER, CAN BE DEVELOPED**\",\"index\":1168,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In all the difficult decisions that I made through the course of running Loudcloud and Opsware, I never once felt brave. In fact, I often felt scared to death. I never lost those feelings, but after much practice I learned to ignore them. That learning process might also be called the *courage development process*.\",\"index\":1169,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In life, everybody faces choices between doing what’s popular, easy, and wrong versus doing what’s lonely, difficult, and right. These decisions intensify when you run a company, because the consequences get magnified a thousandfold. As in life, the excuses for CEOs making the wrong choice are always plentiful.\",\"index\":1170,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1171,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"<table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Life Excuse</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>CEO Excuse</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Other smart people made the same mistake.</p></td><td><p>It was a close call.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All my friends wanted to do it.</p></td><td><p>The team was against me and I couldn’t go against the team.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>All the cool kids are doing it.</p></td><td><p>It was industry best practice; I didn’t realize it was illegal.</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>It wasn’t perfect, so I decided not to compete.</p></td><td><p>We never achieved total product-market fit, so we never tried to sell our product.</p></td></tr></tbody></table>\",\"index\":1172,\"type\":\"html\",\"summarizable\":false},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1173,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Every time you make the hard, correct decision you become a bit more courageous and every time you make the easy, wrong decision you become a bit more cowardly. If you are CEO, these choices will lead to a courageous or cowardly company.\",\"index\":1174,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Throughout my journey with Loudcloud and Opsware, I never felt brave making difficult decisions; I often felt terrified. Over time, I learned to ignore these feelings, a process that might be called the *courage development process*. In life, we all face choices between what’s popular, easy, and wrong, versus what’s lonely, difficult, and right. For CEOs, these decisions are tougher and their consequences are magnified. Excuses for making the wrong choice are plentiful, but each hard, correct decision makes you a bit more courageous, while each easy, wrong decision makes you more cowardly. As a CEO, these choices will inevitably shape your company into one that is courageous or cowardly.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**LAST THOUGHT**\",\"index\":1175,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Over the past ten years, technological advances have dramatically lowered the financial bar for starting a new company, but the courage bar for building a great company remains as high as it has ever been.\",\"index\":1176,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1177,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1178,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Over the past decade, technological progress has significantly reduced the financial constraints of launching a new company. However, the courage required to build a truly great company remains as high as it has ever been.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Being a CEO involves making tough decisions due to their unique perspective and knowledge, often surpassing that of experienced board members and staff. The challenge intensifies with marginal decisions, such as trying to decide to kill a product line, especially when the CEO's slightly preferred choice conflicts with the majority's opinion. A recent example involved a founder/CEO, Hamlet, contemplating the sale of his successful company. Despite a strong inclination from his team to sell, Hamlet's marginal preference was to hold on. Hamlet endured sleepless nights but ultimately opted not to sell, a decision that may define his career. His team's initial desire to sell stemmed from his own uncertainty rather than a thorough analysis, highlighting the need for courage in leadership. My experiences with Loudcloud and Opsware taught me courage isn't about feeling brave but acting despite fear—a process I call the *courage development process*. CEOs face the dilemma of choosing between popular, easy, wrong paths and lonely, hard, right ones, with these choices shaping the company's character as either courageous or cowardly. Although technology has made starting a company easier, the courage needed to build a great one remains unchanged.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Being a CEO involves making tough decisions due to their unique perspective and knowledge, often surpassing that of experienced board members and staff. The challenge intensifies with marginal decisions, such as trying to decide to kill a product line, especially when the CEO's slightly preferred choice conflicts with the majority's opinion. A recent example involved a founder/CEO, Hamlet, contemplating the sale of his successful company. Despite a strong inclination from his team to sell, Hamlet's marginal preference was to hold on. Hamlet endured sleepless nights but ultimately opted not to sell, a decision that may define his career. His team's initial desire to sell stemmed from his own uncertainty rather than a thorough analysis, highlighting the need for courage in leadership. My experiences with Loudcloud and Opsware taught me courage isn't about feeling brave but acting despite fear—a process I call the *courage development process*. CEOs face the dilemma of choosing between popular, easy, wrong paths and lonely, hard, right ones, with these choices shaping the company's character as either courageous or cowardly. Although technology has made starting a company easier, the courage needed to build a great one remains unchanged.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[ONES AND TWOS]()**\",\"index\":1179,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Jim Collins, in his bestselling book *Good to Great*, demonstrates through massive research and comprehensive analysis that when it comes to CEO succession, internal candidates dramatically outperform external candidates. The core reason is knowledge. Knowledge of technology, prior decisions, culture, personnel, and more tends to be far more difficult to acquire than the skills required to manage a larger organization. Collins does not, however, explain why internal candidates sometimes fail as well. I will attempt to do so here. I will focus the discussion on two core skills for running an organization: First, knowing what to do. Second, getting the company to do what you know. While being a great CEO requires both skills, most CEOs tend to be more comfortable with one or the other. I call managers who are happier setting the direction of the company *Ones* and those who more enjoy making the company perform at the highest level *Twos.*\",\"index\":1180,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Jim Collins, in his bestselling book *Good to Great*, demonstrates through massive research and comprehensive analysis that when it comes to CEO succession, internal candidates dramatically outperform external candidates. The core reason is knowledge. Knowledge of technology, prior decisions, culture, personnel, and more tends to be far more difficult to acquire than the skills required to manage a larger organization. Collins does not, however, explain why internal candidates sometimes fail as well. I will attempt to do so here. I will focus the discussion on two core skills for running an organization: First, knowing what to do. Second, getting the company to do what you know. While being a great CEO requires both skills, most CEOs tend to be more comfortable with one or the other. I call managers who are happier setting the direction of the company *Ones* and those who more enjoy making the company perform at the highest level *Twos.*\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHAT ONES LIKE AND DON’T LIKE**\",\"index\":1181,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ones like spending most of their time gathering information from a broad variety of sources, from employees to customers to competitors. Ones love making decisions. Although they prefer to have comprehensive information when they make a decision, they comfortably make decisions with very little information when necessary. Ones have great strategic minds and enjoy nothing more than a good game of eight-dimensional chess against their best competitors.\",\"index\":1182,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Ones sometimes get bored with many of the important execution details required to run a company, such as process design, goal setting, structured accountability, training, and performance management.\",\"index\":1183,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Most founding CEOs tend to be Ones. When founding CEOs fail, a significant reason is that they never invested the time to be competent enough in the Two tasks to direct those activities effectively. The resulting companies become too chaotic to reach their full potential and the CEO ends up being replaced.\",\"index\":1184,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Ones thrive on gathering information from diverse sources, such as employees, customers, and competitors, and revel in making decisions, whether well-informed or based on limited data. They possess great strategic minds and excel in complex competitive scenarios. However, they often find the crucial execution details of running a company—like process design, goal setting, structured accountability, training, and performance management—tedious. Most founding CEOs are Ones, and their downfall frequently lies in failing to master these essential Two tasks. This lack of competence in directing such activities often leads to chaotic companies that can't reach their full potential, resulting in the replacement of the CEO.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHAT TWOS LIKE AND DON’T LIKE**\",\"index\":1185,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Twos, on the other hand, thoroughly enjoy the process of making the company run well. They insist upon super-clear goals and strongly prefer not to change goals or direction unless absolutely necessary.\",\"index\":1186,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Twos like to participate in strategic discussions but often have difficulty with the strategic thinking process itself. Where a One might be perfectly comfortable spending one day a week reading, studying, and thinking, doing so would make a Two very nervous, because it would not feel like work to them. A Two would get antsy at the thought of all the processes that might be improved, people who might be held accountable to achieving the standard, or sales calls that could be made while he was wasting time just thinking about strategy.\",\"index\":1187,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Big decisions worry Twos much more than they worry Ones. Circumstances often force both Ones and Twos to make critical decisions with insufficient data, but Ones generally feel fine about doing that and do not get overly anxious about the consequences. Twos, by contrast, can become highly agitated about such things and sometimes overcomplicate the decision-making process in order to provide a false feeling of thoroughness about the choice.\",\"index\":1188,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"CEOs who are Twos, despite their love of action, can sometimes bring decision making in a company to a halt.\",\"index\":1189,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Twos thoroughly enjoy making a company run efficiently, insisting on super-clear goals and disliking changes unless absolutely necessary. They like participating in strategic discussions but struggle with strategic thinking, finding it nerve-wracking and unproductive compared to actionable tasks like improving processes or making sales calls. Unlike Ones, who are comfortable making big decisions with insufficient data, Twos get highly anxious and may overcomplicate the decision-making process to feel thorough. This tendency can cause Twos, even as CEOs, to inadvertently bring decision-making in a company to a halt despite their love of action.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**YOU NEED BOTH CHARACTERISTICS TO BE A GOOD CEO**\",\"index\":1190,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"While people tend to be Ones or Twos, with discipline and hard work natural Twos can be competent at One tasks and Ones can be competent at Two tasks. If a CEO ignores the dimension of management she doesn’t like, she generally fails. Ones end up in chaos and Twos fail to pivot when necessary.\",\"index\":1191,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"While people tend to be Ones or Twos, with discipline and hard work natural Twos can be competent at One tasks and Ones can be competent at Two tasks. If a CEO ignores the dimension of management she doesn’t like, she generally fails. Ones end up in chaos and Twos fail to pivot when necessary.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**FUNCTIONAL ONES**\",\"index\":1192,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Often Two executives act as Ones for their functions, but Twos as members of the executive team. For example, the head of sales might easily make all the decisions that are local to the sales organization but prefer to take direction with respect to the overall company plans. This is the best kind of multilayer leadership possible, because directions are clear and decisions are made rapidly with precision.\",\"index\":1193,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Often Two executives act as Ones for their functions, but Twos as members of the executive team. For example, the head of sales might easily make all the decisions that are local to the sales organization but prefer to take direction with respect to the overall company plans. This is the best kind of multilayer leadership possible, because directions are clear and decisions are made rapidly with precision.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**HOW ORGANIZATIONS TEND TO BE CONSTRUCTED**\",\"index\":1194,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The primary purpose of the organizational hierarchy in a company is decision-making efficiency. It follows that most CEOs tend to be Ones. If the person at the top of the decision-making hierarchy doesn’t like making extremely complex decisions, the company’s processes will be slow and unwieldy.\",\"index\":1195,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"If you’re a One, it can be counterproductive to have another One on your staff, because she will want to set her own direction rather than follow yours. This kind of strategic contention can confuse the organization and send employees in opposing directions. As a result, many great One CEOs employ primarily Twos and Functional Ones on their staff.\",\"index\":1196,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The primary purpose of an organizational hierarchy is to enhance decision-making efficiency, which is why most CEOs are typically Ones. If the person at the top isn't adept at making complex decisions, the company's processes will become slow and cumbersome. For a One CEO, having another One on staff can be counterproductive, as it may lead to strategic conflicts and misdirection within the organization. Consequently, many effective One CEOs prefer to employ primarily Twos and Functional Ones, who can support the direction set by the CEO without causing internal confusion.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**WHAT HAPPENS AT SUCCESSION?**\",\"index\":1197,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"This brings us to the question of succession. Since most organizations are run by Ones and have a team of Twos (sometimes Functional Ones) reporting to them, replacing the CEO can be extremely tricky. Do you promote someone from the executive staff even though they are likely a Two? Microsoft did this in 2000 when they replaced Bill Gates, a prototypical One, with Steve Ballmer, literally his number two. Or do you reach deep into the organization and pull a One from a level lower where they are likely to exist? General Electric famously did this with Jack Welch in 1981. It was an incredibly bold move by GE—not only did they promote an executive two levels down in the organizational chart past all of his superiors, but in doing so they named the youngest CEO in the history of GE. It’s difficult for most board members to even conceive of the possibility that there is a One deep in the organization who is more qualified to run the company than anyone on the executive staff.\",\"index\":1198,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Both methods can be problematic. The first approach leaves the company in the charge of a Two. As the company faces forks in the road, decision making may slow down and the company may lose its edge. In addition, the natural Ones (in Microsoft’s case, stellar executives such as Paul Maritz and Brad Silverberg) will eventually leave.\",\"index\":1199,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In scenario two, by promoting someone past everyone on the executive team and making them CEO (as GE did), you will likely cause massive turnover of the executive staff. In fact, in very short order, almost none of the original GE executives remained under Welch. In a diversified conglomerate like GE, this kind of rough transition is possible. For companies in the highly dynamic technology business, the super-high-turnover scenario is more dangerous.\",\"index\":1200,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Succession in organizations, typically led by Ones with Twos reporting to them, can be tricky when replacing a CEO. Promoting an executive staff member, often a Two, can slow decision-making and result in the loss of natural Ones, as seen when Microsoft replaced Bill Gates with Steve Ballmer. Alternatively, reaching deep into the organization to elevate a One, like GE did with Jack Welch in 1981, can cause massive executive turnover. While GE managed this transition, it poses significant risks for dynamic tech companies due to potential instability and high turnover.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE BIG CONCLUSION**\",\"index\":1201,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The big conclusion will be a big disappointment for those looking for an answer. The answer is there is no easy answer. CEO transition is hard. If you bring people in from the outside, you lower your chances for success. If you promote from within, you must deal with the One-Two phenomenon. Ideally, you’ll promote a One and the rest of the executive team will be glad you did. Too bad things are rarely ideal.\",\"index\":1202,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1203,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1204,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The big conclusion is, unfortunately, a big disappointment for those seeking a simple answer: there is no easy answer. CEO transitions are challenging. Hiring from outside reduces the likelihood of success, while promoting from within brings the risk of the One-Two phenomenon. Ideally, you’ll promote a One, and the rest of the executive team will support this choice. However, the ideal scenario is rarely the reality.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Ones excel in gathering diverse information and making strategic decisions, but often struggle with essential operational tasks like process design, goal setting, and performance management, leading to potential chaotic company environments. Most founding CEOs are Ones, and their downfall often comes from failing to master these critical Two tasks, which are enjoyed by Twos who focus on clear goals and efficient company operations. However, Twos can overcomplicate decision-making when anxious, causing delays. While Ones and Twos can learn each other's tasks with discipline, ignoring either dimension of management can lead to failure. Ideally, Twos act as supportive executives within their functions, aiding rapid and precise decisions. Most CEOs are Ones to drive complex decisions efficiently, but having another One can cause strategic conflicts. Effective CEOs often employ Twos and Functional Ones to maintain clarity. CEO transitions are challenging; hiring externally minimizes success chances, while promoting internally risks the One-Two dynamics, as seen in high-profile examples like Microsoft and GE. The ultimate takeaway is that there is no simple solution—CEO transitions are inherently difficult, and success hinges on a delicate balance of leadership qualities and team support.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Ones excel in gathering diverse information and making strategic decisions, but often struggle with essential operational tasks like process design, goal setting, and performance management, leading to potential chaotic company environments. Most founding CEOs are Ones, and their downfall often comes from failing to master these critical Two tasks, which are enjoyed by Twos who focus on clear goals and efficient company operations. However, Twos can overcomplicate decision-making when anxious, causing delays. While Ones and Twos can learn each other's tasks with discipline, ignoring either dimension of management can lead to failure. Ideally, Twos act as supportive executives within their functions, aiding rapid and precise decisions. Most CEOs are Ones to drive complex decisions efficiently, but having another One can cause strategic conflicts. Effective CEOs often employ Twos and Functional Ones to maintain clarity. CEO transitions are challenging; hiring externally minimizes success chances, while promoting internally risks the One-Two dynamics, as seen in high-profile examples like Microsoft and GE. The ultimate takeaway is that there is no simple solution—CEO transitions are inherently difficult, and success hinges on a delicate balance of leadership qualities and team support.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[FOLLOW THE LEADER]()**\",\"index\":1205,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"There is no prototype for the perfect CEO. Radically different styles—think Steve Jobs, Bill Campbell, and Andy Grove—can all lead to great outcomes. Perhaps the most important attribute required to be a successful CEO is leadership. So what is leadership and how do we think about it in the context of the CEO job? Are great leaders born or made?\",\"index\":1206,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Most people define leadership in the same way that Supreme Court justice Potter Stewart famously defined pornography when he said, “I know it when I see it.” For our purposes, we can generalize this to be the measure of the quality of a leader: the quantity, quality, and diversity of people who want to follow her.\",\"index\":1207,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"So what makes people want to follow a leader? We look for three key traits:\",\"index\":1208,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* The ability to articulate the vision\\n\\n* The right kind of ambition\\n\\n* The ability to achieve the vision\",\"index\":1209,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"So what makes people want to follow a leader? We look for three key traits: \\n\\n * The ability to articulate the vision\\n\\n* The right kind of ambition\\n\\n* The ability to achieve the vision\"},{\"content\":\"Let’s take these in order.\",\"index\":1210,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"There is no single prototype for the perfect CEO, as exemplified by the radically different styles of leaders like Steve Jobs, Bill Campbell, and Andy Grove, all of whom achieved great outcomes. The most crucial attribute for a CEO is leadership. Leadership is often defined in a way similar to how Supreme Court Justice Potter Stewart described pornography: \\\"I know it when I see it.\\\" For CEOs, this translates to the measure of their leadership quality being the quantity, quality, and diversity of people who want to follow them. Three key traits that make people want to follow a leader are: the ability to articulate the vision, the right kind of ambition, and the ability to achieve the vision. Let’s break these down further.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE ABILITY TO ARTICULATE THE VISION: THE STEVE JOBS ATTRIBUTE**\",\"index\":1211,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Can the leader articulate a vision that’s interesting, dynamic, and compelling? More important, can the leader do this when things fall apart? More specifically, when the company gets to a point when it does not make financial sense for any employee to continue working there, will the leader be able to articulate a vision that’s compelling enough to make people stay?\",\"index\":1212,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I believe Jobs’s greatest achievement as a visionary leader was in getting so many super-talented people to continue following him at NeXT, long after the company lost its patina, and in getting the employees of Apple to buy into his vision when the company was weeks away from bankruptcy. It’s difficult to imagine any other leader being so compelling that he could accomplish these goals back-to-back, and this is why we call this one the Steve Jobs attribute.\",\"index\":1213,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Can the leader articulate a vision that's interesting, dynamic, and compelling, especially when things fall apart? Specifically, when the company reaches a point where it doesn't make financial sense for any employee to stay, will the leader's vision be compelling enough to make them stay? I believe Steve Jobs's greatest achievement as a visionary leader was getting so many talented people to continue following him at NeXT, long after the company lost its allure, and convincing Apple employees to buy into his vision when the company was weeks away from bankruptcy. It's hard to imagine any other leader being so compelling to accomplish these goals back-to-back, which is why we call this the Steve Jobs attribute.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE RIGHT KIND OF AMBITION: THE BILL CAMPBELL ATTRIBUTE**\",\"index\":1214,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"One of the biggest misperceptions in our society is that a prerequisite for becoming a CEO is to be selfish, ruthless, and callous. In fact, the opposite is true and the reason is obvious. The first thing that any successful CEO must do is get really great people to work for her. Smart people do not want to work for people who do not have their interests in mind and in heart.\",\"index\":1215,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Most of us have experienced this in our careers: a bright, ambitious, hardworking executive whom nobody good wants to work for and who, as a result, delivers performance far worse than one might imagine.\",\"index\":1216,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Truly great leaders create an environment where the employees feel that the CEO cares more about the employees than she cares about herself. In this kind of environment, an amazing thing happens: A huge number of employees believe it’s *their* company and behave accordingly. As the company grows large, these employees become quality control for the entire organization. They set the work standard that all future employees must live up to. As in, “Hey, you need to do a better job on that data sheet—you are screwing up my company.”\",\"index\":1217,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I call this characteristic the Bill Campbell attribute after the man who is the best I’ve ever seen at this. If you talk to people who worked in any of the many organizations that Bill has run, they refer to those organizations as “my organization” or “my company.” A huge part of why he has been so remarkably strong in this dimension of leadership is that he’s completely authentic. He would happily sacrifice his own economics, fame, glory, and rewards for his employees. When you talk to Bill, you get the feeling that he cares deeply about you and what you have to say, because he does. And all of that shows up in his actions and follow-through.\",\"index\":1218,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"One of the biggest misconceptions in our society is that being selfish, ruthless, and callous is a prerequisite for becoming a CEO. In reality, successful CEOs excel by attracting great people to work for them, and smart individuals prefer leaders who prioritize their interests. Many of us have seen bright executives performing poorly because no top talent wants to work for them. Truly great leaders create an environment where employees feel genuinely cared for, fostering a sense of ownership over the company. This leads to employees holding each other to high standards and contributing to the organization's overall quality. I call this the Bill Campbell attribute, named after the most exemplary leader I've known in this respect. Bill Campbell's authenticity and willingness to sacrifice his own gains for his employees create an atmosphere where people genuinely feel valued. His deep care and effective follow-through are evident in his actions, making his organizations feel personal to those who work there.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**THE ABILITY TO ACHIEVE THE VISION: THE ANDY GROVE ATTRIBUTE**\",\"index\":1219,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The final leg of our leadership stool is competence, pure and simple. If I buy into the vision and believe that the leader cares about me, do I think she can actually achieve the vision? Will I follow her into the jungle with no map forward or back and trust that she will get me out of there?\",\"index\":1220,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"I like to refer to this as the Andy Grove attribute. Andy Grove will always be my model of CEO competence. He earned a Ph.D. in electrical engineering, wrote the best management book I’ve ever read (*High Output Management*), and tirelessly refined his craft. Not only did he write exceptional books on management, but he taught management classes at Intel throughout his tenure.\",\"index\":1221,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In his classic book *Only the Paranoid Survive*, Grove tells how he led Intel through the dramatic transition from the memory business to the microprocessor business. In making that change he walked away from nearly all his revenue. He humbly credits others in the company with coming to the strategic conclusion before he did, but the credit for swiftly and successfully leading the company through the transition goes to Dr. Grove. Changing your primary business as a sixteen-year-old large, public company raises a lot of questions.\",\"index\":1222,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Andy describes an incident with one of his employees: “One of them attacked me aggressively, asking, ‘Does it mean that you can conceive of Intel without being in the memory business?’ I swallowed hard and said, ‘Yes, I guess I can.’ All hell broke loose.”\",\"index\":1223,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Despite shocking many of his best employees with this radical strategy, ultimately the company trusted Andy. They trusted him to rebuild their company around an entirely new business. That trust turned out to be very well placed.\",\"index\":1224,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"The final key to leadership is competence. If I believe in a leader's vision and know she cares about me, I need confidence in her ability to achieve that vision. This is what I call the Andy Grove attribute. Grove, my model of CEO competence, earned a Ph.D. in electrical engineering, authored the highly influential *High Output Management*, and continually honed his leadership skills. Grove's book *Only the Paranoid Survive* recounts how he led Intel's dramatic pivot from the memory business to the microprocessor business, a move that involved abandoning nearly all existing revenue. Despite employee shock and skepticism, his strategic acumen and decisive leadership earned their trust, successfully transitioning Intel into a new era.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**SO, ARE GREAT LEADERS BORN OR MADE?**\",\"index\":1225,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Let’s look at this one attribute at a time:\",\"index\":1226,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* **Articulating the vision** There is no question that some people are much better storytellers than others. However, it is also true that anybody can greatly improve in this area through focus and hard work. All CEOs should work on the vision component of leadership.\\n\\n* **Alignment of interests** I am not sure if the Bill Campbell attribute is impossible to learn, but I am pretty sure that it is impossible to teach. Of the three, this one most fits the bill “born not made.”\\n\\n* **Ability to achieve the vision** This attribute can absolutely be learned; perhaps this is why Andy Grove’s tolerance for incompetence was legendarily low. Indeed, the enemy of competence is sometimes confidence. A CEO should never be so confident that she stops improving her skills.\",\"index\":1227,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In the end, some attributes of leadership can be improved more than others, but every CEO should work on all three. Furthermore, each attribute enhances all three. If people trust you, they will listen to your vision even if it is less articulate. If you are super-competent, they will trust you and listen to you. If you can paint a brilliant vision, people will be patient with you as you learn the CEO skills and give you more leeway with respect to their interests.\",\"index\":1228,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"\",\"index\":1229,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\" \",\"index\":1230,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Let's break it down attribute by attribute:\\n\\n1. **Articulating the Vision**: While some people are naturally gifted storytellers, anyone can significantly improve in this area with determination and effort. All CEOs should focus on honing the vision component of their leadership skills.\\n\\n2. **Alignment of Interests**: This trait, reminiscent of Bill Campbell, may be seen as something innate rather than something that can be taught. It seems to be an attribute you are born with rather than one you can develop.\\n\\n3. **Ability to Achieve the Vision**: This is definitely a learnable skill, something exemplified by Andy Grove’s famous intolerance for incompetence. Confidence can sometimes undermine competence; hence, a CEO must continue to improve her skills and avoid overconfidence.\\n\\nUltimately, while some leadership attributes are more trainable than others, every CEO should strive to develop all three. Each attribute amplifies the effectiveness of the others—trust can make people listen to your vision, competence can foster trust, and a compelling vision can earn you the patience and trust of others as you grow your CEO skills.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Can the leader articulate a vision that's compelling when things fall apart? When financial viability is in question, can the leader's vision make employees stay? Steve Jobs exemplified this, convincing talented teams at NeXT and nearly bankrupt Apple to follow him. This unique ability is what I call the Steve Jobs attribute. Contrary to the myth that CEOs must be selfish and ruthless, successful leaders, like Bill Campbell, excel by making employees feel genuinely cared for and prioritizing their interests. A great leader fosters an environment of mutual high standards and ownership, known as the Bill Campbell attribute. Competence is also crucial; this is exemplified by Andy Grove, who led Intel's pivot from memory to microprocessors through strategic acumen, gaining employee trust and achieving the vision. Grove’s leadership underscores the importance of ongoing skill development, known as the Andy Grove attribute. \\n\\nBreaking it down: \\n1. **Articulating the Vision**: Essential and can be honed.\\n2. **Alignment of Interests**: Innate but critical for attracting top talent.\\n3. **Ability to Achieve the Vision**: Also learnable, requiring constant improvement.\\n\\nEvery CEO should strive to develop all three attributes, as they amplify each other: trust can make people listen to your vision, competence fosters trust, and a compelling vision earns patience and trust as you grow your skills.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"Can the leader articulate a vision that's compelling when things fall apart? When financial viability is in question, can the leader's vision make employees stay? Steve Jobs exemplified this, convincing talented teams at NeXT and nearly bankrupt Apple to follow him. This unique ability is what I call the Steve Jobs attribute. Contrary to the myth that CEOs must be selfish and ruthless, successful leaders, like Bill Campbell, excel by making employees feel genuinely cared for and prioritizing their interests. A great leader fosters an environment of mutual high standards and ownership, known as the Bill Campbell attribute. Competence is also crucial; this is exemplified by Andy Grove, who led Intel's pivot from memory to microprocessors through strategic acumen, gaining employee trust and achieving the vision. Grove’s leadership underscores the importance of ongoing skill development, known as the Andy Grove attribute. \\n\\nBreaking it down: \\n1. **Articulating the Vision**: Essential and can be honed.\\n2. **Alignment of Interests**: Innate but critical for attracting top talent.\\n3. **Ability to Achieve the Vision**: Also learnable, requiring constant improvement.\\n\\nEvery CEO should strive to develop all three attributes, as they amplify each other: trust can make people listen to your vision, competence fosters trust, and a compelling vision earns patience and trust as you grow your skills.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**[PEACETIME CEO/WARTIME CEO]()**\",\"index\":1231,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Bill Campbell always used to say to me, “Ben, you’re the best CEO that I work with.” This always seemed crazy to me, because he was working with Steve Jobs, Jeff Bezos, and Eric Schmidt at the time while my company was going straight into the wall. One day I called him on it and said, “Bill, why would you say that? Do results not count?” He said, “There are lots of good peacetime CEOs and lots of good wartime CEOs, but almost no CEOs that can function in both peacetime and in wartime. You’re a peacetime/wartime CEO.”\",\"index\":1232,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"By my calculation, I was a peacetime CEO for three days and wartime CEO for eight years. I still have a hard time shaking the wartime flashbacks. I’m not the only one who has experienced this. Dennis Crowley, the founder of Foursquare, told me that he thinks about this tension—between wartime and peacetime—every day. The same goes for a lot of tech companies.\",\"index\":1233,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"For instance, when Eric Schmidt stepped down as CEO of Google and founder Larry Page took over, much of the news coverage focused on Page’s ability to be the “face of Google” since Page is far more shy and introverted than the gregarious and articulate Schmidt. While an interesting issue, this analysis misses the main point. Schmidt was much more than Google’s front man; as Google’s *peacetime* chief executive, he led the greatest technology business expansion in the last ten years. Larry Page, in contrast, seems to have determined that Google is moving into war and he clearly intends to be a *wartime* CEO. This has been a profound change for Google and the entire high-tech industry.\",\"index\":1234,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Bill Campbell always told me, \\\"Ben, you're the best CEO that I work with,\\\" which seemed absurd given he was also working with Steve Jobs, Jeff Bezos, and Eric Schmidt, while my company was struggling. When I questioned him about it, he explained that there are many great peacetime and wartime CEOs, but very few who excel in both scenarios. He considered me a peacetime/wartime CEO. Despite my skepticism, as I calculated being a peacetime CEO for just three days compared to eight years of wartime, the distinction resonated as I grappled with the ongoing pressure. Dennis Crowley of Foursquare shares this same tension between wartime and peacetime roles, a common theme in tech companies. For example, when Larry Page replaced Eric Schmidt as Google's CEO, media speculated about Page's ability to be Google's \\\"face\\\" due to his introverted nature compared to Schmidt's charisma. However, this overlooked Schmidt’s role as a peacetime leader who oversaw significant growth, while Page appears to be steering Google into a wartime phase, bringing profound changes to the company and the tech industry.\",\"type\":\"untitled\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**DEFINITIONS AND EXAMPLES**\",\"index\":1235,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Peacetime in business means those times when a company has a large advantage over the competition in its core market, and its market is growing. In times of peace, the company can focus on expanding the market and reinforcing the company’s strengths.\",\"index\":1236,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In wartime, a company is fending off an imminent existential threat. Such a threat can come from a wide range of sources, including competition, dramatic macroeconomic change, market change, supply chain change, and so forth. The great wartime CEO Andy Grove marvelously describes the forces that can take a company from peacetime to wartime in his book *Only the Paranoid Survive*.\",\"index\":1237,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"A classic peacetime mission is Google’s effort to make the Internet faster. Google’s position in the search market is so dominant that they determined that anything that makes the Internet faster accrues to their benefit since it enables users to do more searches. As the clear market leader, they focus more on expanding the market than dealing with their search competitors. In contrast, a classic wartime mission was Andy Grove’s drive to get out of the memory business in the mid-1980s due to an irrepressible threat from the Japanese semiconductor companies. In this mission, the competitive threat—which could have bankrupted the company—was so great that Intel had to exit its core business, which employed 80 percent of its staff.\",\"index\":1238,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"My greatest management discovery through the transition was that peacetime and wartime require radically different management styles. Interestingly, most management books describe peacetime CEO techniques and very few describe wartime. For example, a basic principle in most management books is that you should never embarrass an employee in a public setting. On the other hand, in a room filled with people, Andy Grove once said to an employee who entered the meeting late, “All I have in this world is time, and you are wasting my time.” Why such different approaches to management?\",\"index\":1239,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"In peacetime, leaders must maximize and broaden the current opportunity. As a result, peacetime leaders employ techniques to encourage broad-based creativity and contribution across a diverse set of possible objectives. In wartime, by contrast, the company typically has a single bullet in the chamber and must, at all costs, hit the target. The company’s survival in wartime depends upon strict adherence and alignment to the mission.\",\"index\":1240,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"When Steve Jobs returned to Apple, the company was weeks away from bankruptcy—a classic wartime scenario. He needed everyone to move with precision and follow his exact plan; there was no room for individual creativity outside the core mission. In stark contrast, as Google achieved dominance in the search market, Google’s management fostered peacetime innovation by enabling and even requiring every employee to spend 20 percent of their time on their own new projects.\",\"index\":1241,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Peacetime and wartime management techniques can both be highly effective when employed in the right situations, but they are very different. The peacetime CEO does not resemble the wartime CEO.\",\"index\":1242,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Peacetime in business occurs when a company has a significant advantage over its competition and its market is growing, allowing it to focus on expanding the market and reinforcing strengths. In contrast, wartime arises when a company faces imminent existential threats, such as competition, economic shifts, or supply chain issues, necessitating a focus on survival. Andy Grove's experiences, detailed in *Only the Paranoid Survive*, exemplify this. Google’s effort to make the Internet faster is a peacetime mission, leveraging its dominance to further benefit from an expanded market. Conversely, Andy Grove’s decision to exit Intel’s memory business in the 1980s due to Japanese competition is a classic wartime move aimed at survival. Through transitions from peacetime to wartime, I discovered that these periods require vastly different management styles. Peacetime leaders cultivate broad creativity and multiple objectives, while wartime leaders ensure strict adherence to a single, critical mission. Steve Jobs exemplified wartime leadership by steering Apple away from bankruptcy with a focused, precise plan, whereas Google’s peacetime management encouraged individual innovation with initiatives like the 20 percent project time. Both peacetime and wartime management techniques are effective when applied appropriately, but the leaders and their approaches differ significantly.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**PEACETIME CEO/WARTIME CEO**\",\"index\":1243,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"Peacetime CEO knows that proper protocol leads to winning. Wartime CEO violates protocol in order t