 deeper *why* questions that define the company's existence: why people should join, be excited to work, buy products, invest, and believe the world is better for the company’s existence. Articulating the company’s story effectively clarifies this context for everyone involved—employees, partners, customers, investors, and the press. Conversely, failing to tell the story often leads to confusion and misalignment. While the CEO doesn't have to create the vision or the story, she must be its guardian, ensuring it is clear and compelling. The story isn't just a mission statement but a comprehensive narrative that can take time to tell. A great example of this is Jeff Bezos's 1997 letter to Amazon shareholders, which effectively communicated Amazon's story and got all the stakeholders on the same page about the company’s purpose and direction.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**Decision making**\",\"index\":1314,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Some employees make products, some make sales; the CEO makes decisions. Therefore, a CEO can most accurately be measured by the speed and quality of those decisions. Great decisions come from CEOs who display an elite mixture of intelligence, logic, and courage.\",\"index\":1315,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As already noted, courage is particularly important, because every decision that a CEO makes is based on incomplete information. At the time of any given decision, the CEO will generally have less than 10 percent of the information typically present in the post hoc Harvard Business School case study. As a result, the CEO must have the courage to bet the company on a direction even though she does not know if the direction is right. The most difficult decisions (and often the most important) are difficult precisely because they will be deeply unpopular with the CEO’s most important constituencies (employees, investors, and customers).\",\"index\":1316,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"The best decision that I made in my career—to sell the Loudcloud business to EDS and become Opsware—would have lost by a landslide had I put it to a vote with my employees, my investors, or my customers.\",\"index\":1317,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"As CEO, there is never enough time to gather all information needed to make a decision. You must make hundreds of decisions big and small in the course of a typical week. You cannot simply stop all other activities to gather comprehensive data and do exhaustive analysis to make that single decision. Knowing this, you must continuously and systematically gather knowledge in the company’s day-to-day activities so that you will have as much information as possible when the decision point arrives.\",\"index\":1318,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"In order to prepare to make any decision, you must systematically acquire the knowledge of everything that might impact any decision that you might make. Questions such as:\",\"index\":1319,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"* What are the competitors likely to do?\\n\\n* What’s possible technically and in what time frame?\\n\\n* What are the true capabilities of the organization and how can you maximize them?\\n\\n* How much financial risk does this imply?\\n\\n* What will the issues be, given your current product architecture?\\n\\n* Will the employees be energized or despondent about this promotion?\",\"index\":1320,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"type\":\"clump\",\"summary\":\"In order to prepare to make any decision, you must systematically acquire the knowledge of everything that might impact any decision that you might make. Questions such as: \\n\\n * What are the competitors likely to do?\\n\\n* What’s possible technically and in what time frame?\\n\\n* What are the true capabilities of the organization and how can you maximize them?\\n\\n* How much financial risk does this imply?\\n\\n* What will the issues be, given your current product architecture?\\n\\n* Will the employees be energized or despondent about this promotion?\"},{\"content\":\"Great CEOs build exceptional strategies for gathering the required information continuously. They embed their quest for intelligence into all of their daily actions from staff meetings to customer meetings to one-on-ones. Winning strategies are built on comprehensive knowledge gathered in every interaction the CEO has with an employee, a customer, a partner, or an investor.\",\"index\":1321,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"Some employees make products, some make sales; the CEO makes decisions. The speed and quality of these decisions are the best measures of a CEO’s effectiveness. Great decisions stem from a blend of intelligence, logic, and courage—as complete information is never available. CEOs must often act with less than 10% of the information that might be available retrospectively in a case study. Courage is crucial because many impactful decisions will be unpopular with key stakeholders. My top decision—to sell Loudcloud to EDS and pivot to Opsware—would have been overwhelmingly opposed by employees, investors, and customers. Due to time constraints, a CEO can't pause operations for exhaustive analysis and must make decisions continually. Thus, a CEO must systematically gather knowledge through daily activities to be prepared for critical decision points. This involves understanding competitors, technical possibilities, organizational capabilities, financial risks, product architecture issues, and employee morale. Successful CEOs integrate their quest for intelligence into every interaction, collecting detailed information consistently to build winning strategies based on comprehensive knowledge.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, your primary role is setting the context for your team, giving their work meaning, aligning interests, enabling decision-making, and inspiring motivation. This context goes beyond structured goals and dives into the deeper \\\"why\\\" questions: why employees should join and be excited, why customers should buy your products, why investors should invest, and why the world is better with your company. Effectively communicating your company's story clarifies this context for everyone—employees, partners, customers, investors, and the press. Without a clear story, confusion and misalignment can arise. Even if the CEO doesn't create the vision, she must be its guardian, ensuring it is clear and compelling. This isn't just about a mission statement but a detailed narrative, as demonstrated by Jeff Bezos's impactful 1997 letter to Amazon shareholders. Additionally, a CEO's effectiveness is measured by their decision-making speed and quality. Great decisions require blending intelligence, logic, and courage, often with incomplete information. Tough decisions, like my choice to sell Loudcloud to EDS and pivot to Opsware, may be unpopular but necessary. CEOs must continually gather knowledge, understanding competitors, tech possibilities, organizational capabilities, financial risks, product issues, and employee morale to make well-informed decisions and develop winning strategies.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, your primary role is setting the context for your team, giving their work meaning, aligning interests, enabling decision-making, and inspiring motivation. This context goes beyond structured goals and dives into the deeper \\\"why\\\" questions: why employees should join and be excited, why customers should buy your products, why investors should invest, and why the world is better with your company. Effectively communicating your company's story clarifies this context for everyone—employees, partners, customers, investors, and the press. Without a clear story, confusion and misalignment c