al price was $27 \\\\[the stock’s initial offer price\\\\] and it closed on the first day at $122. It was great for many of the Baidu employees and for all of the Baidu investors. It was a very miserable thing for me because when I decided to take the company public, I was only prepared to deliver financial results that match the price of $27 or maybe a little higher, $30, $40. But I was really shocked to see that the price went to $122 on the first day. So that meant I needed to deliver real results that matched an expectation much, much higher than what I had prepared to do. But in any case, I thought I had no choice. So I put my head down and focused on operations, focused on technology, focused on the user’s experience, and I delivered.*\",\"index\":1338,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"Once we’ve taken all of this into account, we see that the results against objectives or “black box” results are a *lagging* indicator. And as they say in the mutual fund prospectuses, “past performance is no guarantee of future results.” The white-box CEO evaluation criteria—“Does the CEO know what to do?” and “Can the CEO get the company to do it?”—will do a much better job of predicting the future.\",\"index\":1339,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"When measuring results against objectives, it's essential first to ensure that the objectives are accurate. CEOs can manipulate outcomes by setting goals too low or too high. Early-stage companies face particular challenges in this area due to the uncertainty of the opportunity size. Additionally, comparing different types of companies, such as hardware versus consumer internet, can be misleading and detrimental. A prime example is Robin Li, CEO of Baidu, who experienced a dramatic shift in expectations after Baidu's IPO. Initially prepared for a stock price of $27, he was taken aback when the stock closed at $122 on the first day. Despite the pressure, he focused on operations, technology, and user experience to meet the heightened expectations. This story exemplifies the importance of setting realistic objectives and the ability of a CEO to adapt and deliver. Ultimately, while past performance (black box results) offers insights, forward-looking evaluation criteria—whether the CEO knows what to do and can execute it—are more predictive of future success.\",\"type\":\"section\"},{\"hierarchy\":[{\"content\":\"**CLOSING THOUGHT**\",\"index\":1340,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true},{\"content\":\"CEO evaluation need not be a byzantine, unarticulated art. All people, including CEOs, will perform better on a test if they know the questions ahead of time.\",\"index\":1341,\"type\":\"markdown\",\"summarizable\":true}],\"summary\":\"CEO evaluation need not be a byzantine, unarticulated art. All people, including CEOs, will perform better on a test if they know the questions ahead of time.\",\"type\":\"section\"}],\"summary\":\"As a CEO, your primary role is to provide context for your team, giving their work meaning and aligning interests to enable decision-making and motivation. This context goes beyond structured goals and delves into the deeper \\\"why\\\" questions: why employees should be enthusiastic, why customers should buy your products, why investors should invest, and why the world benefits from your company. Effectively communicating your company's story is crucial to avoid confusion and misalignment. Even if the CEO didn't create the vision, they must be its guardian, ensuring it's clear and compelling through a detailed narrative, such as Jeff Bezos's impactful 1997 letter to Amazon shareholders. Your effectiveness is measured by the speed and quality of your decisions, requiring intelligence, logic, and courage, often with incomplete information. For example, my decision to sell Loudcloud to EDS and pivot to Opsware, though unpopular, was necessary. CEOs must continuously gather knowledge about competitors, technology, org